<FIRST>r a AM-Hunt-Senate     08-17 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunt-Senate,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunt Says He Won't Run Against Helms in 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Jim Hunt ended months of
speculation Wednesday when he said he not seek a replay of the
bitter 1984 Senate campaign with Republican rival Sen. Jesse Helms.
   ``This was pretty well settled some time back,'' said Hunt,
citing a heart attack and stroke suffered by his mother. Hunt and
his parents live on adjoining farms in Wilson County.
   ``We just can't walk away from that,'' he said. ``You do your
duty to your family first.''
   Helms defeated Hunt in 1984 by a 52-to-48 percent margin. They
spent a combined $26 million, then a record for a Senate race. The
campaign was marked by negative campaigning and personal slurs, but
Hunt said the grueling 1984 campaign was not the reason for his
decision not to run.
   Hunt, 52, is a partner in a Raleigh law firm. He served four
years as lieutenant governor and was the first governor to serve
successive four-year terms.
   Helms, in a prepared statement, said he was relieved not to be
facing Hunt again. ``Mr. Hunt has demonstrated in four elections
that he is always a formidable opponent,'' Helms said. ``I would be
less than honest if I did not acknowledge that I was glad to learn
of his announcement today.''
   State Democratic Party Chairman Lawrence Davis said in a
statement that Hunt would have been an excellent candidate, but
``our party has a number of excellent potential candidates, any one
of whom can win the 1990 Senate race.''
</TEXT>
