<FIRST>r i PM-ThaiBorderVillage     08-17 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thai Border Village,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Villagers Caught in War Not Their Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BAN NON SAO-AE, Thailand (AP) _ The war has nothing to do with
them, but without warning it comes roaring in often on the 729
people of Ban Non Sao-Ae who make their living by farming.
   The war is Cambodia's _ government forces fighting rebels _ and
the villagers have the misfortune of living close to the border
where the fighting frequently breaks out with artillery barrages
that send shells crashing into Thailand.
   ``Bunker'' is one of the few English words that have worked their
way into the local language and that's because almost every family
has a bunker under their stilt-raised wooden houses.
   Phra Attikan Arun, a 30-year-old Buddhist monk, is recording the
war.
   When the artillery shells start pounding in, he turns on his tape
recorder and runs to the safety of his bunker.
   Later, he plays the tapes for visitors to show them what it's
like to live in Ban Non Sao-Ae in Thailand's Prachinburi province.
   The provincial defense office says that in Prachinburi alone 36
villagers have been killed and 120 wounded since 1984. More than
15,000 have fled.
   The effects of the war on Ban Noan Sao-Ae also are documented in
a few dozen color snapshots the monks have arranged on a display
board at their temple. The photographs show the bodies of two
victims of an August 1988 shelling, people building bunkers, looking
at houses blown to pieces, and gathered around an unexploded
artillery shell.
   The fighting flared in late July, just after villagers planted
the rainy-season crop. Scores of shells hit this and other nearby
villages.
   A woman, Wanpen Thonchul, 22, was wounded by shrapnel.
   Several hundred women and children fled down the road to the
Kaset College auditorium, where they slept on the concrete floor.
   Tin Janshu, 59, fled to his bunker after shells crashed in the
paddy field where he was working.
   When it was over, Tin sat on the bunker, saying he doesn't know
why they are fighting in Cambodia.
   ``I only grow my rice to eat,'' he said
   Why not move to another village?
   ``How can I move? The coconut and fruit trees have been growing
here since my parents. If I move somewhere else, by the time I can
grow a coconut tree like this, I would be dead.
   ``My grandfather died here. My father died here, so I'll die here
also.''
   Dum Jankeja, 64, said he also will stay. Dum and his wife share a
bunker with three other households, and he said adversity has
brought the villagers closer.
   ``We have to go through this together. We help each other out. If
we go into the bunker, we go in together.''
   Less fortunate was Somwang Janpit, 22, one of at least three
villagers who recently lost legs to landmines.
   In June, he was searching for bamboo shoots in a deserted field.
He thought the blast he heard was someone shooting birds _ until he
saw his right leg was gone.
   ``Yes, I'm angry,'' he said. ``Now I can't take care of my father
and mother.''
   His mother, 63, now toils nine hours a day in the fields to feed
him, his handicapped sister and their father, 84.
   At the village school, anything that sounds like gunfire sends
the children dashing for the bunker on the compound. Heavy shelling
last year shattered several school buildings.
   But most students have learned to cope, a teacher said.
   ``Their homes are here in the village. When they hear it (the
shelling), they are scared. When it's over, they go and play like
children everywhere.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
