<FIRST>r a AM-Baraka-Arrest     08-17 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baraka-Arrest,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baraka and Son Arrested for Allegedly Assaulting Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playwright and poet Imamu Amiri Baraka was
arrested Wednesday with his son on assault charges following an
altercation with police, officials said.
   Baraka, 55, and his son Ras, 20, were charged with assault and
making terroristic threats, said police spokesman Daniel Collins.
Ras Baraka was also charged with resisting arrest, Collins said.
   Baraka, who changed his name from LeRoi Jones, is the author of
plays including ``Dutchman'' and ``The Toilet.''
   The two argued with police at the South District Precinct after
they went to the station in response to the arrest of Baraka's
younger son, Ahhi, 15.
   The boy was arrested with four others for allegedly obstructing
the sidewalk in front of a business, Collins said.
   Baraka and his older son were being held at the lockup at police
headquarters Wednesday night. Ahhi was released into the custody of
his mother.
   Collins said Ras Baraka first went to the station with his mother
Amina, but began kicking and punching the officers and had to be
restrained. His father then arrived and joined the struggle with the
officers, he said.
   Baraka's cousin, Peter Jones, said that when Ras Baraka and his
mother arrived at the station, police harassed her and beat Ras
Baraka when he tried to intervene.
</TEXT>
