<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IncineratorPermit     08-17 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Incinerator Permit,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Agrees Rocky Flats Incinerator Needs Permit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement has been reached between
federal officials and the Sierra Club acknowledging that the
plutonium recovery incinerator at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons
plant needs a state permit.
   Officials said the agreement was reached Monday between the
Sierra Club, which had filed a lawsuit over the issue, and the U.S.
Department of Energy, which owns the plant which manufactures
plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons.
   The plan stipulates that the DOE won't restart the incinerator in
Building 771 until it gets a permit and holds public hearings.
   Fred Dowsett, of the state Health Department, said the
incinerator probably will be shut down six months to a year during
the permit application process.
   The new permit procedures could hasten a crisis in waste disposal
at the plant, which is storing wastes tainted with both hazardous
materials and radioactivity because of a lack of an approved waste
disposal site.
   Gov. Roy Romer has vowed to close the plant if that total exceeds
1,601 cubic yards, and officials say that limit could be reached in
March. A permanent waste site is planned, but not open, in New
Mexico.
   The agreement was signed by the U.S. Department of Justice for
the DOE; Rockwell International, which runs Rocky Flats; and the
Sierra Club.
   The Sierra Club said burning a mixture of plutonium and poisonous
chemicals without a state-authorized permit illegally endangers
public health.
   Most of the plutonium processed can be recovered without the
incinerator, said chemist Niels Schonbeck of the Rocky Flats
Environmental Monitoring Council, a group opposed to the incinerator.
</TEXT>
