<DOCNO> AP890817-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Rushdie     08-17 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Cut Off From Friends in Secret Hideouts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie, whose writings Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini found offensive to Mohammed and Allah, has spent seven
months in hiding, cut off from friends and protected by armed guards.
   On Feb. 14, the Iranian leader declared Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses'' blasphemous and told his followers to kill the
author. The Shiite Moslem patriarch died June 3 but his sentence
lives.
   Rushdie's American wife, Marianne Wiggins, has been quoted as
saying the couple have moved 56 times, to a succession of ``safe
houses'' used for spies and intelligence contacts.
   Friends say the Rushdies seem in good spirits but that the
Indian-born British writer, a non-practicing Moslem, feels his
seclusion may end only if Iran formally withdraws the threat.
   He issued a statement soon after Khomeini passed sentence
expressing ``profound regret'' for any offense to Moslems, but Iran
rejected it.
   Among parts of the ``The Satanic Verses'' many Moslems find
offensive are a scene in which prostitutes are given the names of
the prophet Mohammed's wives, and implications that Mohammed wrote
the Koran, the Moslem holy book.
   ``He's been silenced effectively and cannot speak in his own
defense, and that's a terrible plight for any writer to be in; it's
hideous,'' said a friend, Lisa Appignamesi.
   ``It's very hard to speak for another person, but I think he's
bearing up very well,'' she said in an interview. Ms. Appignamesi is
co-author of ``The Rushdie File,'' a recent book about the case.
   Rushdie, 42, and his wife of 19 months have not been seen in
public since police escorted them from their north London home on
Feb. 14. Rushdie has not given interviews and Ms. Wiggins, 41, also
a novelist, has said isolation is their greatest burden.
   ``You can no longer pass down the street and encounter a
stranger,'' the London magazine Options quoted her as saying last
month. ``You lose all sense of spontaneity because you live in fear.
Fear is an element that used to be on the far side of the Earth.''
   Ms. Wiggins says she and her husband keep diaries, stay in touch
with their families and world events, and always have at least one
armed bodyguard with them.
   They have dined occasionally with friends, literary acquaintances
or such political figures as Neil Kinnock, leader of opposition
Labor Party, but friends say the occasions have become fewer at the
insistence of the guards.
   The Rushdies have occupied a succession of houses operated by
Special Branch security police and MI5, the domestic intelligence
agency, Ms. Wiggins was quoted as telling The Sunday Telegraph.
   She returned to their home in London's Islington district to pick
up belongings, but neither has been home since.
   Their friends, literary agents and publishers do not know their
whereabouts, according to the London newspaper The Independent. It
said the Rushdies do not take telephone calls and mail is sent by a
roundabout route via police, but they can respond to messages.
   Security has cost tens of thousands of dollars, The Independent
said.
   More than 1.1 million hardback copies of ``The Satanic Verses''
have been sold, including 600,000 in the United States, earning
Rushdie more than $1.9 million, said sources at his publishers,
Viking Penguin.
   One said Viking Penguin had spent an amount equal to the
royalties on security for its buildings and at bookstores, ``so the
major winner is Rushdie in a sense.'' Plans for a paperback edition
had been shelved.
   Rushdie continues to review books for The Observer, a London
weekly, and news reports say he is writing a children's book.
   The International Committee for the Defense of Salman Rushdie and
his Publishers has gathered the signatures of 12,000 people,
including 2,500 writers.
   In a message to the committee last month, Rushdie said he
believed reconciliation with Iran was possible.
   He said many Moslems had written messages of support, and ``there
is no such unbridgeable gulf'' between his vision of Islam and that
of Moslems who accuse him of blasphemy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
