<FIRST>r a AM-SexAbuse     08-17 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Abuse,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Employee Indicted on 209 Counts of Sexual Abuse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Editors: The contents may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An systems analyst who had checked into
a psychiatric center was indicted Wednesday on charges of
sodomizing, sexually abusing and torturing young boys and filming
some of the acts for sale, a prosecutor said.
   Harold Hotchkiss, 45, of Ossining was charged in a 209-count
indictment with various counts of sodomy, sexual abuse, use of a
child in a sexual performance, promoting a sexual performance by a
child, obscenity, attempted aggravated sexual abuse and endangering
the welfare of a child.
   Westchester County District Attorney Carl Vergari said the
alleged abuse occurred between 1984 and 1989, and involved 10 boys
between the ages of seven and 17.
   ``There was anal and oral sodomy, shock treatments and
beatings,'' said Vergari.
   Apparently, Hotchkiss was friends with the family of one boy and
``one thing led to another. A friend introduced a friend introduced
a friend.''
   Vergari also said that he approached ``young boys who were
susceptible.''
   Three of the victims were brothers, Vergari said. He would not
disclose whether the boys received any kind of payment for their
activities.
   Jeanine Ferris Pirro, chief of the district attorney's Domestic
Violence and Child Abuse Bureau, said Hotchkiss photographed and
audiotaped the acts ``for sale and distribution'' so authorities do
not have all the film Hotchkiss allegedly took.
   Hotchkiss allegedly made the children perform acts with him and
with each other and he allegedly beat the boys and used shock on
them.
   Pirro said authorities were notified of the activities when the
mother of one of the boys ``found something in her home.'' She would
not disclose what it was. Vergari said there was a possibility that
there were more victims.
   The alleged abuse occurred in the Ossining-Peekskill area where
Hotchkiss has lived for many years. Much of the abuse occurred
within Hotchkiss' home, said Vergari.
   Hotchkiss, who is single, voluntarily checked himself into the
Institute of Living in Hartford, Conn., a few months ago, Pirro said.
   Authorities would not disclose why he checked himself into the
facility or whether his arrest Wednesday occurred there.
   His attorney, Frank Silverstein, asked Westchester County Court
Judge Kenneth Lange to allow his client to undergo psychiatric
tests. Lange agreed and Hotchkiss was remanded to the forensic unit
of the Westchester County Jail. No bail was set.
   Rita Black, a spokeswoman for IBM, said Hotchkiss was a senior
associate systems and procedures analyst with IBM at its White
Plains facility and had worked for the company since March 9, 1965.
   She said Hotchkiss was still on the IBM payroll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
