<DOCNO> AP890817-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0213EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AftertheEulogies Bjt   08-17 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-After the Eulogies, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parceling Out a Congressman's Perks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Claude Pepper lived, his office was a
five-room suite, among the best on Capitol Hill. With Pepper gone
and no successor in place, his staff is winding up his work in two
dingy storerooms with an air shaft for a view.
   ``Our quarters are so cramped, we figured the animal rights
people would be protesting,'' says Rochelle Jones, longtime press
secretary for the Florida congressman.
   The experiences of Pepper's staff undoubtedly differ little from
those of Reps. Jim Wright and Tony Coelho, who resigned, and Mickey
Leland and Larkin Smith, who were killed in recent plane crashes.
   Pepper, the champion of the elderly, enjoyed the power and perks
that grow with seniority and his staff shared them, too. When he
died, the perks died for his staff as well.
   ``When a member dies, it's over with,'' says Ray Colley, the
deputy clerk of the House who supervises the transitions when a
congressman leaves and another takes his place.
   When Pepper staffers returned from his funeral in June, there was
a message from the clerk's office: The telephone should no longer be
answered ``Congressman Claude Pepper's office.'' It was to be ``18th
Congressional District of Florida.''
   About the same time, recalls Ms. Jones, a procession of
congressmen and their staffs came by to look over Pepper's office,
which was in a prime location in the Rayburn Office Building _
commensurate with his 27 years in the House.
   ``They were really ghoulish people looking over the remains,''
says Ms. Jones. ``Five different people put in a bid for the
office.''
   When congressional suites become vacant, other members bid on
them and they are awarded on the basis of seniority.
   The visitors included congressmen and others who wanted
post-death autographs on books and pictures _ before the automatic
signing pen was put away.
   ``I can understand the staff's concern about not being able to
answer `Senator Pepper' but he's not Senator Pepper any more,''
Colley said. Many old-timers on Capitol Hill still referred to
Pepper as senator, since he served in the Senate for 14 years.
   Some of the Pepper perks were gone before the sun set on his
grave.
   ``I had a parking space in Rayburn that was just great _ a few
steps from the elevator,'' said Ms. Jones. ``One day I came in and
found (Texas congressman) Jack Brooks using my parking space. It was
my notification that the space was no longer mine.''
   Pepper died May 30 at age 88. The funeral was June 5 in Florida.
His congressional seat will be filled in a special election Aug. 29,
but until then his staff takes care of district business.
   At the end of June, the Pepper staff was told to move into two
rooms among storage spaces on the sixth floor of the Longworth House
Office Building next door _ with a view of an air shaft.
   The move meant packing up the congressman's belongings, first for
the office switch, then for transfer to the Federal Records Center.
   ``Pepper was in office from 1962. He never threw away a piece of
paper,'' said Ms. Jones. ``I found personnel files of people who
worked there in the 1960s.
   ``The Rayburn office was filled with memorabilia. It was a living
museum, pictures of Pepper with all the presidents he's known since
Roosevelt, pictures of Pepper with celebrities. One wall was filled
just with legislation he had participated in, from the cross-Florida
barge canal to Social Security reform.''
   Pepper's personal things, including the hundreds of pictures and
dozens of pens from bill signings, will go to the Mildred and Claude
Pepper Library at Florida State University in Tallahassee.
   Pepper's office was assigned by the clerk's office to Rep. Dale
Kildee, D-Mich., who is in his seventh term.
   ``We are very careful to answer the phone `18th Congressional
District of Florida,''' said Ms. Jones. ``There is usually a pause,
then `is this Congressman Pepper's office?' People still call up;
they need help getting a visa; a year-old Medicare claim hasn't been
paid.''
   The staff toils on, winding up the Pepper era.
   ``People have stopped answering our phone calls,'' Ms. Jones said.
   That, in Washington, is the ultimate loss of power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-China Bjt   08-17 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, Bjt,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Ambassador's Farewell Draws Limited Official Attendance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Official U.S. displeasure over the Chinese
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement is putting a damper on
departing Ambassador Han Xu's farewell to Washington.
   The most prominent Americans among about 500 guests at Han's
Chinese Embassy reception Wednesday night were retired rather than
active public officials.
   They included two former secretaries of state, Henry Kissinger
and Alexander Haig, and two former Senate leaders, Republican Hugh
Scott and Democrat Mike Mansfield. Also there was former Democratic
Sen. J. William Fulbright.
   The absence of top members of President Bush's administration and
cabinet reflected the president's post-June 3 policy of balancing
U.S. public outrage over the killings of Chinese pro-democracy
demonstrators against the decision to continue dialogue with the
Chinese government.
   Under that policy, the administration decided that the highest
representation at Han's reception would be at the assistant
secretary level, said a State Department official who insisted on
anonymity. From the department came Richard Solomon, assistant
secretary for East Asian and Pacific affairs, Ivan Selin,
undersecretary for management, and some lower level officials.
   Earlier in the day, the 65-year-old ambassador made a farewell
call on Vice President Dan Quayle. Their meeting was cordial and
``they talked about ways China could improve its relations with the
United States ... human rights were obviously mentioned,'' said
Quayle spokesman David Beckwith.
   Han also made official farewell calls on at least four members of
the Bush Cabinet and some members of Congress, all conspicuously
absent Wednesday. Cabinet members often attend diplomatic
receptions, and they appeared at the Chinese Embassy during the
heyday of Han's four upbeat years of expanding relations with the
United States.
   But U.S. officials say those times are over unless China halts
repression of its citizens.
   Han Xu and his wife, Ge Qiyun, smilingly greeted all the guests
at the entrance to two reception rooms filled with hot and cold
Chinese appetizers and drinks ranging from tea to whiskey. The
couple showed they have made some warm friends, the ambassador
embracing several Americans, including Haig, while Ms. Ge exchanged
kisses with some of the female guests.
   Haig, a retired four-star general, accompanied President Nixon on
his 1972 Beijing journey breaking the ice on U.S.-China relations.
Han, then chief of protocol, was one of the first officials to greet
them. Haig has visited China several times.
   Scott, 88, attended the reception in a wheelchair. He recalled
his first visit to China before World War II. Mansfield, who last
year completed a record 11 years as ambassador to Japan, was known
in Congress as an ``old Asia hand'' who advocated U.S. recogniion of
the communist government long before many other lawmakers. He first
visited Asia as a Navy sailor.
   Beijing Television on July 6 said Han Xu's term was up and he
would be succeeded by Vice Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen. Han will
leave for Beijing later this month and the new ambassador is
expected in mid-October, Chinese officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha Bjt   08-17 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Botha, Bjt,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha's Resignation May Help Right-Wing in September Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   P.W. Botha's bitter exit from
the presidency three weeks before parliamentary elections may help
far-right candidates at the expense of the National Party he served
for a half-century.
   The Conservative Party, which claims the Nationalists are
capitulating to blacks, quickly incorporated Botha's stern farewell
speech Monday into its campaign rhetoric.
   ``We support Mr. P.W. Botha in his viewpoint, which has been our
viewpoint all along,'' said Conservative Party leader Andries
Treurnicht at a campaign rally after Botha's nationally televised
address.
   Botha denounced a planned meeting between National Party leader
F.W. de Klerk and President Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia on grounds the
outlawed African National Congress guerrilla organization has its
headquarters in Zambia. Botha said his Cabinet ignored his
opposition to the meeting.
   Yet Botha and his predecessor, John Vorster, had met with Kaunda,
and the circumstances of the ANC were no different then.
   ``One conclusion is that Mr. Botha was using the Kaunda talks as
a stick with which to beat Mr. de Klerk, not because of any
objection in principle but because he was blinded by personal
antipathy for the man who succeeded him,'' said Patrick Laurence, a
political writer for The Star newspaper in Johannesburg.
   De Klerk was installed as acting president on Tuesday.
   ``The way Botha chose to do this, tarring de Klerk with the ANC
brush ... it is clear he wanted to do as much harm to de Klerk as he
could,'' said Steven Friedman, a researcher at the independent South
African Institute of Race Relations.
   Friedman suggested Botha had grown more conservative in recent
years.
   ``He had come to the end of the line as far as reform is
concerned. He was increasingly querulous and felt he hadn't gotten
credit, particularly from the outside world, for the major reforms
he did initiate,'' said Friedman.
   By proceeding with the Kaunda meeting, de Klerk could win over
some voters who might have backed the liberal Democratic Party. But
the greatest threat to Nationalists in the Sept. 6 elections appears
to be from the Conservatives, who say the ANC has no role to play,
ever, in South Africa. They also call for reimposing apartheid laws
Botha repealed.
   It was Botha's foreign policy that Treurnicht agreed with, not
the retired president's belief that whites must share power with the
black majority.
   At a minimum, the resignation saga has damaged the image of
stability developed by the National Party since taking power in 1948.
   ``For the last 40 years, the National Party has appeared to be
entirely in control. Incidents like this conflict don't do much for
that kind of image,'' said Friedman.
   Treurnicht, a member of Botha's Cabinet who broke away in 1982
over the issue of allowing Indians and people of mixed race into
Parliament, lost no time in decrying the National Party's ``lack of
unity.''
   Botha, who became prime minister in 1978, built up a personal
image as a defender of white, particularly Afrikaner, interests.
Even if people found it difficult to be fond of him, most white
voters, English- and Afrikaans-speaking, trusted him on security
matters. His suggestion that de Klerk is making a major error on
that front may be taken seriously.
   On the personal level, many white voters feel sorry for Botha.
The reaction in street conversations and radio talk shows indicates
the Cabinet is seen as bullying a sick, albeit cantankerous, old man
into a humiliating resignation instead of smoothing things over
until the election.
   Such sentiments may not translate into a loss of support for the
National Party, but the Conservative Party is not missing any chance.
   From the first hint of the dispute, Treurnicht has lamented
Botha's treatment by the Cabinet, and called the resignation a
``palace revolution.''
   Although Afrikaners, the whites most likely to vote
conservatively, may sympathize with Botha, they also believe
strongly in group loyalty. They may begin to frown on Botha's
turning against the party he served for 53 years.
   Beeld, an Afrikaans-language daily that supported Botha for many
years, said, ``The last image that will linger ... is that of a
blind Samson who with his last strength tried to overturn the
pillars of his party on himself and his own companions.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Laurinda Keys, based in Johannesburg, has covered
South Africa for The Associated Press since 1986.
</TEXT>
