<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     08-17 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearings Next Month on EPA Pesticide Decisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hearings are to begin next month on legislation
to get the Agriculture Department more involved with the
Environmental Protection Agency on pesticide decisions.
   A key feature of the measure, sponsored by Rep. George Brown,
D-Calif., would amend existing statutes to require the Agriculture
Department to report annually to EPA on which pests are attacking
crops and the chemicals or other methods being used to control them.
   It also would require USDA to say which pests are developing
resistance to products, said Skip Stiles, staff director of Brown's
House Agriculture subcommittee on department operations, research
and foreign agriculture.
   The idea, he said, is to set off an early warning system if EPA
is starting to eliminate all the pesticides used for certain crops
so alternatives can be developed.
   ``The Department of Agriculture doesn't get involved in these
regulation decisions until it is too late to do anything about it,''
Stiles said.
   He gave as an example the case of ethylene dibromide, suspended
by the EPA in 1984 after more than seven years of review. It was
used, among other things, as a fumigant against fruit flies on
imported produce, most specifically mangoes.
   A relatively simple alternative eventually was discovered, but it
took three years to move through the government approval process
from the time ethylene dibromide was taken off the market, he said.
   The Agriculture Department, Stiles said, could have been working
all along to find the alternative that would have been ready when
ethylene dibromide was canceled.
   Charles Smith, USDA pesticide research coordinator, said the
department was aware of the EPA review, but never knew what the
agency's decision would be.
   ``At the end of the seven years you can look back and say, `Why
didn't you do something?' And, we say, `We didn't know what we were
supposed to do,''' Smith said.
   He said the department has to ask: ``How many million dollars of
taxpayers' money should I spend to find an alternative to something
that may stay on the market?''
   But, Smith said, that doesn't mean the department isn't
constantly doing research on pest control.
   ``Finding chemical alternatives is not what we generally think of
as the area we think federal money is best spent,'' Smith said,
adding that the chemical industry usually shoulders that burden.
   He said the government is doing extensive biotechnical research,
and that federal and university researchers generally do the kind of
work that's not profitable for private industry because it's
high-risk.
   Just because a chemical is under review by the EPA doesn't mean
it will be canceled, he said.
   ``EPA has been reluctant to share any information until they are
certain there is a problem and then sometimes it is way down the
road,'' Smith said.
   Stiles said the major part of Brown's bill is devoted to
procedures for canceling pesticides.
   ``The big complaint has been the EPA takes forever to cancel a
pesticide,'' he said. ``Part of the delay is the fact that they have
cumbersome administrative hearings.''
   The bill, Stiles said, would eliminate some of those hearings.
</TEXT>
