<FIRST>r w PM-Fulbright-China     08-17 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fulbright-China,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Suspends Fulbright Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China says it is suspending participation in
the prestigious Fulbright program, forbidding an exchange of
American professors and Chinese scholars.
   The action comes in the wake of strained relations between the
United States and China over the communist nation's crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Richard Ware, chairman of the Board of Foreign Scholarships, said
Wednesday that the Chinese government told the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing that ``no American Fulbright professors would be permitted
to teach in China, and that no Chinese graduate students or research
scholars would be allowed to travel to the U.S.''
   The China Fulbright program has been one of the largest in the
world, with 24 American professors and a similar number of Chinese
scholars participating, Ware said.
   ``We deeply regret the Chinese decision to suspend an educational
exchange program that has been of great mutual benefit,'' he said.
   The 24 American professors assigned to China will be offered
Fulbright teaching posts in other countries, said W.B. Reinckens of
the U.S. Information Agency.
   Reinckens said China has participated for about 10 years in the
Fulbright program, administered by the USIA in cooperation with
other federal agencies and a number of private organizations. There
are 126 countries, including China, in the program.
   The Fulbright program was established in 1946 under legislation
by former Sen. J. William Fulbright, D-Ark. More than 167,000
people, including 58,000 from the United States and 109,000 from
abroad, have participated.
</TEXT>
