<FIRST>r w PM-PennyStocks     08-17 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penny Stocks,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Tightens Rules on Penny Stock Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock brokers will have a harder time
pressuring new customers into buying low-priced, often risky
securities known as ``penny stocks,'' under a new rule adopted by
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The rule, unanimously approved Wednesday, requires brokers
offering certain securities to get the new customer's written
approval before completing the sale.
   SEC staffers hope it will curb the practice of unsolicited
telephone stock sales _ known as ``cold calling'' _ by providing a
``built-in cooling off period'' for the customer to reconsider his
or her decision, said Sarah B. Ackerson of the SEC Enforcement
Division.
   The rule, which takes effect Jan. 1, comes in response to a
dramatic rise in the fraudulent sale of penny stocks. In the first
half of the current fiscal year, the SEC has received 2,462
complaints about penny stock fraud compared with 1,510 for all of
the last year.
   John C. Baldwin, president of the North American Securities
Administrators Association, a group of state-level investment
regulators, said the action puts ``new obstacles in the path of the
penny stock firms that use the telephone as a weapon to mug
unsuspecting investors.''
   Before the 5-to-0 vote to approve the change, SEC Chairman David
S. Ruder said the problem was of ``great concern'' to the agency.
   Last fall, Ruder created a Penny Stock Task Force, which found a
key element of penny stock fraud was high-pressure sales tactics _
often over the telephone _ used on unsophisticated investors.
   The new rule, Ruder said, ``brings us today a weapon against this
scurrilous conduct _ a weapon that's effective but not intrusive.''
   But he and several other commission members also noted most penny
stocks and penny stock dealers are legitimate.
   The SEC created several exceptions in response to numerous
complaints that the proposal would make it tough for new companies
short of capital _ traditionally a major segment of penny stock
issuers _ to raise money.
   The rule would apply to stocks selling at $4.99 or less per share
or to stocks issued by companies with less than $2 million in
tangible assets.
   Penny stocks, trading for a few cents up to a few dollars, are
usually issued by new companies or concerns with an uneven earnings
history.
   They usually are not traded on exchanges or quoted on the
National Association of Securities Dealers Automated Quotation
(NASDAQ) System, commonly known as the national over-the-counter
market.
   Because most penny stocks are not listed nationally, information
about them is hard to come by and fraudulent claims are difficult to
dispute.
   The new penny stock rule, first proposed in February, will
require brokers and dealers to get written purchase agreements from
new customers before completing their first three transactions in
stocks that are neither traded on stock exchanges nor through the
NASDAQ system.
   Broker-dealers also would have to get financial information from
the customer such as income, investment experience and investment
objectives; determine whether the transaction is suitable for the
customer's needs and write down the basis for that determination.
   Exempted were initial public offerings that are scheduled to be
listed with NASDAQ or a stock exchange.
</TEXT>
