<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     08-17 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Indicates Noriega Can Stay In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is demanding that Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega relinquish power in Panama, but apparently
won't insist that he leave the country.
   ``We've always said that he must leave power. We've always said
that there can be no accommodation with a Noriega-dominated
regime,'' State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday.
   However, Boucher declined to say whether Noriega, under
indictment in Florida on drug charges, must leave Panama.
   The Organization of American States resumed talks in Panama this
week with government and opposition forces. Boucher said the
administration supports the attempt ``to achieve a democratic
transfer of power.''
   President Bush, at a news conference Tuesday, left open the
possibility of seeking Noriega's extradition _ or even abducting him
_ to face trial.
   ``I have an obligation to try to bring people to justice,'' he
said.
   The Reagan administration initially demanded that Noriega not
only surrender power but leave Panama. Behind the scenes, though,
the United States worked out a deal for the general to leave during
national elections and to be free to return afterward _ but without
power. The deal fell apart in 1988 and the administration stopped
calling for him to leave Panama.
   Last year, Noriega bought a home in the Dominican Republic,
raising prospects he could be persuaded to go there. However, the
Reagan administration scuttled any such deal on the grounds the
Dominican Republic was too close to Panama.
</TEXT>
