<FIRST>r w PM-North'sNotebooks     08-17 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North's Notebooks,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suits Seek Copies of Handwritten Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two private groups say the Freedom of
Information Act entitles them to copies of Oliver North's notebooks
from prosecutors in the Iran-Contra scandal.
   The National Security Archive and Public Citizen filed suit
Wednesday in U.S. District Court, asking a judge to order
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh to turn over copies of some 3,000
pages of handwritten notes compiled by the former White House aide.
   The notes are daily accounts of North's activities in the Reagan
administration's Iran arms sale initiative and secret support for
the Contras during a congressional ban on military aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   North took the notebooks when he was fired in 1986 and was forced
to give copies of them to Walsh's office when he took the witness
stand in his own defense at his criminal trial. North was convicted
on three felony counts.
   In a July 24 letter, Walsh told the archive that ownership of the
documents is uncertain and denied its request to turn over copies,
according to the lawsuit.
   Mary Belcher, a spokeswoman for Walsh's office, declined to
comment on the lawsuit.
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee subpoenaed the notebooks
more than a year ago.
   In an effort to cooperate with Congress, Walsh tried to turn over
copies to the White House in June but was rebuffed, according to
administration and congressional sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``We shall supply a copy of these documents to the National
Security Council along with a copy of your letter expressing a need
for them,'' Walsh said in a June 23 letter to Sen. Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I., the foreign relations committee's chairman.
   It was shortly after sending the letter that a courier from
Walsh's office tried to deliver the documents to the NSC and was
told that ``they're not the property of the NSC,'' said one
government source.
</TEXT>
