<FIRST>r w PM-DC-10Engines     08-17 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Engines,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Says More, Tougher DC-10 Inspections Considered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board
reportedly is likely to recommend more frequent and more thorough
inspections of all DC-10 engines as a result of the Sioux City,
Iowa, crash that killed 111 people.
   The safety board is ``fairly certain'' to make the recommendation
as a precaution against another explosive engine failure such as the
one that led to the July 19 crash of United Airlines Flight 232, ABC
News reported Wednesday.
   Ted Lopatkiewicz, an NTSB spokesman, said he could not confirm
whether the board was considering a recommendation for increased and
tougher inspections for DC-10 engines.
   ``We don't discuss anything that might be considered or discussed
until the board votes on a recommendation,'' he said.
   Nothing in the records for the engine and the plane showed any
problems or violations of maintenance regulations, the network
reported.
   Engines on two DC-10 passenger jets have suffered explosive
failure in the past month.
   About two weeks after the Sioux City, Iowa, crash, a Northwest
Airlines DC-10 made an emergency landing in Denver after its No. 2
tail engine apparently began disintegrating in flight.
   The Federal Aviation Administration has since formed a
government-industry task force that is examining possible design
changes in the planes manufactured by McDonnell-Douglas. Though the
DC-10 is no longer in production, McDonnell-Douglas plans a
derivative, the MD-11.
   Lopatkiewicz said investigators are still trying to find out what
caused the engine on Flight 232 to fail, sending pieces of the
engine flying and cutting hydraulic control lines.
   With pilots struggling to control the aircraft by changing power
on the remaining two engines, the United DC-10 with 296 aboard
cartwheeled into a cornfield while trying to land at Sioux City.
   ``Significant portions of the fan portion are still missing,''
Lopatkiewicz said, adding that search teams are looking for them
below the plane's flight path.
   Parts that have been recovered have been taken to the Evendale,
Ohio, plant of General Electric, the engine manufacturer, and are
being compared with engines produced at the same time.
</TEXT>
