<FIRST>r w PM-SenateMoney-CommonCause     08-17 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate Money-Common Cause,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Raising Large Amounts for Next Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 32 senators up for re-election next year
already have campaign warchests totaling more than $30 million, with
six raising more than $3 million each since their last elections, a
Common Cause study says.
   The 32 had a total of $30.6 million available to spend on June
30, said the report Wednesday by the self-styled citizen's lobby,
which is based on reports filed with the Federal Election Commission.
   The two top money-raisers since Jan. 1, 1985, were Sens. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J., who raised $6.87 million by June 30; and Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, who raised $6.7 million.
   The other four were Jesse Helms, R-N.C., $5.4 million; Rudy
Boschwitz, R-Minn., $4.1 million; Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., $3.4
million; and John Kerry, D-Mass., $3.3 million.
   A total of 34 Senate seats are up next year but the Common Cause
compilation does not include Sens. William Armstrong, R-Colo., and
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who are retiring.
   Since their last campaigns in 1984, the 32 senators have raised a
total of $53.57 million, including $10.73 million that came from
political action committees, Common Cause said.
   Following is a list of the cash-on-hand as of June 30 for the
senators up for election next year:
   Howell Heflin, D-Ala., $1.5 million; Ted Stevens, R-Ala.,
$468,000; David Pryor, D-Ark., $862,000; Joseph Biden, D-Del., $1.02
million; Sam Nunn, D-Ga., $822,000; James McClure, R-Idaho,
$299,491; Paul Simon, D-Ill., $1.22 million; Dan Coats, R-Ind.,
$482,588; Tom Harkin, R-Iowa, $856,445; Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.,
$135,053.
   Also, McConnell, $2.79 million cash on hand as opposed to the
total $3.4 million raised; Bennett Johnston, D-La., $2.53 million;
William Cohen, R-Maine, $338,236; Kerry, $994,205; Carl Levin,
D-Mich., $1.08 million; Boschwitz, $1.66 million; Thad Cochran,
R-Miss., $521,016; Max Baucus, D-Mont., $656,076; Jim Exon, D-Neb.,
$478,576; Bradley, $3.37 million.
   Also, Pete Domenici, R-N.M., $656,832; Helms, $159,352; David
Boren, D-Okla., $675,006; Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., $180,417; Claiborne
Pell, D-R.I., $444,686; Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., $331,163; Larry
Pressler, R-S.D., $671,726; Al Gore, D-Tenn., $403,028; Gramm, $3.72
million; John Warner, R-Va., $243,345; Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.,
$779,165; Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., $250,408.
