<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Earthquake     08-17 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Earthquake,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slight Earthquake Shakes Southern Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake measuring 4.7 on the Richter
scale shook southern Mexico on Wednesday, the National Seismological
Institute said.
   No damage or injuries were reported, the center said.
   The report said the quake occurred at 6:53 p.m. (8:55 p.m. EDT)
and was centered in the southern state of Guerrero, near the Pacific
coast.
   The temblor lasted eight seconds, the government news agency
Notimex quoted Pedro Pellandini of the National University as saying.
   The Richter scale gauges energy released by an earthquake. An
increase of one number means a 10-fold increase in the amount of
energy released.
   An earthquake measuring four on the Richter scale can cause
moderate damage. One registering five is capable of considerable
damage.
   An earthquake measuring 8.1 on the Richter scale hit the Mexico
City area on Sept. 19, 1985, killing at least 10,000 people.
</TEXT>
