<FIRST>r a PM-FireDeaths     08-17 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire Deaths,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Claiming More Victims in U.S., Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from fires in the United States hit
a seven-year high last year, signaling a need for stricter fire code
enforcement and widespread installation of smoke detectors, a trade
group said.
   The National Fire Protection Association said Wednesday the 1988
death toll of 6,215 people was up 7 percent over 1987, when there
were 405 fewer deaths.
   The report said steady progress has been made in reducing fire
deaths this century, but since 1982 fire deaths have remained fairly
constant, staying within 4 percent of 6,000 every year except 1984.
   ``The implications of the plateau reached by civilian fire deaths
are clear today as they have been for the last several years,'' the
report said. ``The steady stream of good news to which we have
become accustomed will not resume unless we make it.''
   The figures exclude 62 firefighters who died in the line of duty.
   Eight years ago, the death toll from fires hit 6,700. The
previous high had been 7,575 in 1979, said Julie Reynolds, a
spokeswoman for the non-profit association based in suburban Quincy.
   Fires caused property damage last year estimated at $8.35
billion, the report said, an increase of 16.7 percent from 1987.
   The report noted that a significant part of the total, 5.6
percent, resulted from large industrial fires at a refinery in
Norco, La., a chemical manufacturing plant in Henderson, Nev., and a
telephone switching station in Hinsdale, Ill.
   Fires caused by arson or suspected arson dropped 5.2 percent to
99,500 in 1988, but the association said the $1.594 billion in
property damage they caused still amounted to nearly a quarter of
the property loss in structures.
   Of the 1988 deaths, 5,065 happened in residential properties, an
increase of 8.7 percent over the previous year. The association
defines residential properties as one- and two-family houses,
apartments, mobile homes, hotels and motels.
   Michael J. Karter Jr., the association's senior statistician,
said a combination of education, greater use of smoke detectors and
wider installation of sprinkler systems in residential buildings are
needed to reduce fire deaths.
   Karter also called for steps to make home products safer,
including development of child-resistant cigarette lighters and
marketing of cigarettes that go out quickly when they are dropped or
thrown away.
   The association reported that public fire departments responded
to 2,436,500 fires last year, an increase of 4.6 percent from a year
earlier. About 30,800 people were injured in fires last year, the
association said.
   The report noted that wildfires sharply increased last year, with
675,500 brush and grass fires, an increase of more than 22 percent
over 1987. The drought that struck much of the country last summer
was blamed for most of that increase.
   The association arrived at its figures by sampling 2,948 fire
departments, including all departments that protect communities of
100,000 or more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
