<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-US 1stLd-Writethru a0459 08-17 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Lawmaker Says Congress Would Support New Bases Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD position of critics and supporters of bases, INSERT 3
grafs after 7 grafs pvs, `All the...' Pickup 8th graf pvs, `Fascell's delegation...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American bases in the Philippines are
so important to regional security that Congress will probably
support any agreement to allow them to stay, a U.S. lawmaker said
today.
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., made the statement during a news
conference before concluding a four-day visit.
   Fascell, leader of a six-member delegation and chairman of the
House Committee on Foreign Affairs, said talks with President
Corazon Aquino and other officials on the bases made him feel ``more
optimistic than I did when I came here.''
   The U.S. and Philippine governments are expected to begin talks
later this year on whether to extend the lease on the bases.
   The lease expires in September 1991 and Mrs. Aquino refuses to
say whether she supports an extension. Any extension is subject to
ratification by two-thirds of the 23-member Philippine Senate, where
sentiment against the bases is strong.
   Fascell said many nations in Southeast Asia see the presence of
the U.S.-run Clark Air Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and the four other
smaller military installations as essential to stability in the
region.
   ``All the countries in the Pacific basin recognize the importance
of mutual security and the value of it in this area,'' Fascell said.
``I don't anticipate that we we would have any great difficulty in
reaching an understanding.''
   U.S. officials say the bases are essential to maintaining the
balance of military power in the Far East and protecting sea lanes
to Japan and the newly industralized countries of East Asia.
   But Filipino critics say the bases represent an infringment on
national sovereignty and contribute to social problems such as drug
addiction and prostitution.
   Critics also say the United States regularly interferes in
internal Philippine affairs to keep the bases. About 40,000 American
service members, civilian employees and military dependents are
stationed here.
   Fascell's delegation is among three groups of U.S. congressmen to
visit the Philippines this month. Fascell's group also will visit
Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand.
   The others in his party are Democratic Reps. Sander Levin of
Michigan and William Richardson of New Mexico, and Republican Reps.
William Bloomfield of Michigan, Benjamin Gilman of New York and Ben
Blaz of Guam.
   On Wednesday, Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., who is leading another
delegation, said he hoped the two countries could agree to extend
the bases. If not, he said, the United States would develop
``operative facilities elsewhere'' in the Pacific.
</TEXT>
