<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Bosch     08-17 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Bosch,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Staying Out of Cuban Militant's Case, for Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is following the case of anti-Castro
militant Orlando Bosch but won't respond to calls for his freedom
while the case is in federal court, a Cuban-born Republican
congressional nominee said.
   ``The president himself brought it up on Air Force One,'' said
state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, who flew to Miamia on Wednesday with
Bush from Washington for a luncheon that raised at least $250,000
for her campaign. ``He was well abreast on it.''
   Bush noted that Bosch has a hearing next month before a federal
judge, she said. Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Bush would not comment on the matter.
   ``He's going to be interested in seeing what the decision is
going to be,'' Ms. Ros-Lehtinen said.
   While the case is in court, ``it's not really a presidential
matter,'' she said. ``If and when that time comes, certainly we're
going to call on the President to try to help out.''
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, who faces Democratic attorney Gerald Richman in
an Aug. 29 special election to replace the late Rep. Claude Pepper,
has long urged that Bosch, 62, be freed. She made a similar appeal
to Ronald Reagan during his last presidential visit to Miami last
year.
   Bosch, a Cuban-born pediatrician, was taken into custody by
federal officers when he returned to this country in February 1988.
He had spent 11 years in Venezuelan prisons successfuly fighting
accusations that he masterminded a 1976 bombing of a Cuban airliner
near Barbados, killing 73 people.
   After reviewing his case, the Justice Department this year
ordered Bosch's deportation. Federal officials have said Bosch has a
long history of terrorist activities, including during the 1960s
when he lived in Miami. He was convicted in 1968 of firing a small
artillery weapon at a Polish freighter at the Port of Miami, and
later fled the United States, violating his probation.
   But his supporters point out that he was acquitted three times in
Venezuelan courts on the Cuban bombing. They say he is a heroic
freedom fighter who is a victim of changing U.S. policy.
   Bosch had the active support of the Central Intelligence Agency
during his 1960s anti-Castro exploits, which included bombing raids
over Cuba, they say.
   Bosch's appeal of the deportation order will be taken up in U.S.
District Court next month.
   Many Republican officials, whose increasing clout in Florida has
been boosted by the conservative Cuban-American community, have
voiced support for Bosch's release. He's being held without bond in
a federal prison near here.
</TEXT>
