<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Scene     08-17 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Scene,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Corridors Buzzing Over Government's Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six workers waiting outside the Sejm were
adamant when they approached a Solidarity senator on his way to an
urgent meeting on who will govern Poland.
   ``Do something. Have you seen the price of bread? We can't make
ends meet anymore,'' one told Sen. Lech Kaczynski.
   Lawmakers moved through the corridors of parliament Wednesday in
search of a solution to the protracted political and economic
crisis, and by dawn today, a Solidarity-led governing coalition had
emerged as a real possibility.
   Kaczynski urged the workers to have patience, and cautioned them
against staging a strike today.
   ``Strikes are the worst thing now,'' he told them as he rushed to
a meeting of lawmakers from Solidarity and two smaller parties that
are preparing to form a non-Communist coalition.
   After a government minister droned too long about the rising
price of bread and coal, a Solidarity deputy inquired whether it
wasn't premature to discuss the government budget when there was no
government yet.
   As interest waned in parliamentary proceedings, lawmakers left
the chamber and resumed speculating: Would there be a Solidarity-led
coalition? Would the Communists accept such a configuration? Does
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa want to become prime minister?
   Many of the politicians who could provide answers stayed away
from reporters. Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak huddled with top
Solidarity advisers Bronislaw Geremek and Jacek Kuron, and voices
lowered when reporters drew near.
   ``I understand when I don't understand what the Communists are
doing, but I don't understand when I don't understand what we are
doing,'' said one leading Solidarity deputy over lunch.
   The pace of debate quickened late in the day when Solidarity
lawmakers drew up and approved a resolution calling for a
non-Communist coalition government, the first in the East bloc.
   ``We have to go fast. The situation is deteriorating from hour to
hour,'' Kaczynski told a reporter in the corridor.
   Solidarity has hesitated before taking responsibility for the
country's economic crisis, but now its lawmakers seem to feel that
only a government they create will have real public support.
   ``We must take some risks. Such are the times,'' Deputy Jaroslaw
Kaczynski told opposition lawmakers.
   The Solidarity meeting was joined by the independent movement's
two new allies, the Peasant and Democratic parties, long allied with
the Communists but now ready to form an opposition coalition.
   During the three-way discussion, Solidarity lawmaker Aleksander
Malachowski interrupted a speaker and asked where the Communists
were.
   ``I had the impression that a miracle had taken place, that the
Communist Party had evaporated from this country,'' he said.
   Actually, they were in another chamber just out of earshot,
debating a resolution on Poland's participation in the invasion of
Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   That debate seemed irrelevant to one Communist lawmaker who was
taking a cigarette break.
   ``I don't know, I just don't know. It's strange, very strange,''
she said when asked why the 1968 invasion was being debated at such
a time.
   ``By the way, what's going on at the other meeting?'' she asked.
</TEXT>
