<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-17 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Tokyo Stocks Nearly Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar gained against the Japanese yen
today on expectations of an improved U.S. trade deficit, while the
Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index was almost unchanged.
   The dollar closed at 142.32 yen, up 0.52 yen from Wednesday's
close of 141.80 yen. Following a rise on the New York market, it
opened in Tokyo at 142.25 and ranged between 142.20 yen and 142.45
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Index of 225 selected issues rose 5.96 points,
or 0.02 percent, closing at 35,090.11.
   Foreign exchange traders were anticipating an improvement in the
U.S. merchandise trade statistics for June to be announced later
today by the Department of Commerce, said a dealer at Mitsui Bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Other dealers said the market lacked direction as it waited for
the trade figures, but most participants expected the data to show
an improvement.
   ``If the trade figures are as expected, the dollar will be pushed
to the 143-yen level in the Tokyo market,'' said a dealer with the
Bank of Tokyo, also requesting anonymity.
   The Nikkei's slight gain compares with a rise on Wednesday of
273.46 points.
   One trader, requesting anonymity, said most market participants,
including institutional investors, hesitated to act before
announcement of the U.S. trade figures. Volume was a slow 450
million shares.
   Traders reported a shift of buying interest from high-priced
issues, bought mainly for quick profit-taking, to shares with lower
price-earnings ratios.
</TEXT>
