<FIRST>r p PM-Hunt-Senate     08-17 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hunt-Senate,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Governor Says He Won't Run Against Helms in 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Jim Hunt's decision not to seek
a rematch against Republican Sen. Jesse Helms leaves the way open
for a host of fresh Democratic faces to enter the race.
   Hunt said Wednesday he thought he could beat Helms, but he said
his mother's poor health persuaded him not to run. He also indicated
he wasn't eager for a replay of his bitter 1984 race against Helms,
although he said that wasn't why he was bowing out.
   ``I especially believe I would win if the campaign focused on the
issues and on the future of North Carolina and the nation,'' he said
in a statement. ``But, given the experience of 1984, that probably
would not be its nature. Further, given the result of 1984, it is
clear that I do not enjoy or perform very well in a campaign that
emphasizes negative ads and character attacks.''
   Hunt and Helms spent a national record $26 million in a race
marked by negative campaigning and personal slurs. Helms won by a
52-to-48 percent margin against the backdrop of former President
Reagan's landslide re-election win.
   Helms said he was relieved he would not face Hunt.
   ``Mr. Hunt has demonstrated in four elections that he is always a
formidable opponent,'' Helms said in a statement. ``I would be less
than honest if I did not acknowledge that I was glad to learn of his
announcement today.''
   Hunt, 52, is a partner in a Raleigh law firm. He served four
years as lieutenant governor and was the first governor to serve
successive four-year terms.
   National Democratic leaders had been pushing Hunt to run again.
   Former state Sen. Bo Thomas, the only Democrat actively
campaigning for the nomination, welcomed Hunt's decision, saying it
``is not the time or place for him to run.'' Thomas said he expected
other Democrats to enter the race.
</TEXT>
