<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-SovietUnion     08-17 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Soviet Union,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koreans Living in Soviet's Shakhalin Likely to Visit Homeland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will allow thousands
of Koreans living in the Soviet Far Eastern district of Sakhalin to
visit their homeland, governing party sources said today.
   One source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Rep. Kim
Hyon-wook of the governing Democratic Justice Party is in the Soviet
Union discussing procedures for Koreans to return to their homeland
for the first time since World War II ended in 1945.
   Thousands of Koreans were brought to Sakhalin by Japan as forced
labor in the final years of the war. They since have been stranded
there simply because of the lack of diplomatic relations between
Seoul and Moscow.
   But the two coutries exchanged trade offices this year and the
Soviet Union, closely allied with communist North Korea, has shown
willingess to promote non-political ties with South Korea.
   Officials of the Democratic Justice Party said about 36,000
Koreans are living in Sakhalin and that about 3,000, mostly
first-generation Koreans, want to return home permanently or at
least visit.
   Under an agreement with Soviet officials, a chartered South
Korean plane may be allowed to bring home several hundred Koreans
before the end of the year, the party sources said.
   They said the South Korean government would pay all travel
expenses.
   The central executive committee of the Democratic Justice Party
reviewed the issue today and discussed seeking financial
compensation from Japan for the Korean residents of Sakhalin, the
party sources said.
</TEXT>
