<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-SomaliRefugees     08-17 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Somali Refugees,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Somalis Cross into Kenya After Troops Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 people fleeing government
raids in southern Somalia have crossed into neighboring Kenya the
last two weeks, according to a newspaper report.
   The refugees started moving into Kenya July 31 after Somali
troops killed 27 people in five days of raids near Doble, 12 miles
east of Kenya's border, The Standard reported Wednesday.
   The daily said the refugees were camped in Harhar, a town
straddling the Kenya-Somalia border about 300 miles northeast of
Nairobi.
   The raids reportedly followed government charges that the Absame
clan, the largest in southern Somalia, was expelling members of
President Siad Barre's Marehan clan from the region, the newspaper
said.
   One of those fleeing the fighting, Ahmed Hussein Barre, told The
Standard he was the former police chief in the Doble district and
said the raid was the fifth in the region.
   Ahmed Hussein Barre said that after the raids he and another
former security officer had turned against the government and would
battle to bring it down, according to the newspaper.
   The Somali National Movement has been fighting in northern
Somalia to topple the government since 1981.
   Since fighting intensified in northern Somalia in May 1988,
hundreds of thousands of Somalis have fled into refugee camps in
eastern Ethiopia.
   The government has refused to let journalists visit Somalia since
May 1988, and residents contacted by telephone in Mogadishu have
little knowledge of events outside the capital.
