<FIRST>r a PM-Flight255Memorial     08-17 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 255 Memorial,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Years Later, Survivors Gather to Mourn 156 Crash Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jets thundered overhead and cars zoomed
past on the nearby interstate as 300 people gathered on a hill where
Northwest Flight 255 crashed two years ago, killing 156 people.
   The Phoenix-bound MD-80 crashed after takeoff from Detroit
Metropolitan Airport on the evening of Aug. 16, 1987, killing all
but one of the 155 people aboard as well as two passing motorists.
   ``All the people here _ they know what you've experienced. They
know how you feel,'' said mourner Nancy Engelhart of Bay City.
   As she did last year, she drove the 90 miles from Bay City on
Wednesday to attend the memorial service at Middlebelt Road and
Interstate 94 in suburban Romulus. Around her neck hung a color
photo of a couple and two children.
   ``This is my sister, Sue Byelich, and her husband, Don,''
Engelhart said.``They had their two boys with them, Mike and Brad.
The whole family was wiped out.''
   Her sister's family was on their way back to Phoenix after a
visit.
   ``My brother-in-law had his folks' golden wedding anniversary the
night before the crash,'' she said.
   The two years haven't erased the pain of their loss, Engelhart
said.
   ``It's hard to get used to,'' she said. ``You still expect to see
them walk through the door.''
   The jet failed to gain altitude during takeoff and slammed into
an overpass on the interstate.
   The sole survivor was Cecelia Cichan, then 4. She is living with
her aunt and uncle, Rita and Frank Lumpkin, in Birmingham, Ala.,
shielded from the media. She lost her parents and 6-year-old brother
in the crash.
   At the site, 12 rows of white wooden doves, 156 in all, bore the
names of the victims. At 8:46 p.m., the exact time of the crash, the
Rev. Ron Lund began reading the names of the dead.
   ``William Acker, George Amabile, Jamie Amabile ... '' he began.
As each name was called out, survivors flicked on pen lights and
pointed them toward the darkening sky. Ten times, passing jets
interrupted the roll call.
   Lund, a leader of the survivors' group Flight 255: The Spirit
Lives On, said their grief has drawn members together.
   ``This is our second anniversary family gathering, because we are
a family,'' he told the gathering. ``We wipe each others tears. We
joke together now, but we didn't always.''
   Not mentioned at the ceremony was a liability trial scheduled to
begin Oct. 2 in U.S. District Court in Detroit.
   Northwest attorney Carroll Dubuc says it could take four to five
months to settle the 102 suits pending against Northwest and
McDonnell Douglas, which built the aircraft. Forty-six suits have
been settled, Dubuc said. Federal investigators cited pilot error as
the cause of the crash.
   Edward Shepherd of Sun Lakes, Ariz., lost a niece, Dorian
Wallington, 13, and granddaughter, Arlene Nelson, 12, in the crash.
   ``The things that bring it back are when you see the family photo
album and see their pictures,'' Shepherd said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
