<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0412 08-17 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Blames Overworked Captain for Rhode Island Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 12th graf, `The captain...', to CORRECT that ship left
for Greece last month. Picks up 13th graf, `Georgudis previously...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker captain was overworked and
distracted, causing the oil spill off Newport for which he and a
shipping company have agreed to pay $510,000 in fines, a prosecutor
said.
   The captain, Iakovos Georgudis, and Ballard Shipping Co. each
pleaded guilty Wednesday to one misdemeanor count of violating the
federal Clean Water Act.
   Almost 300,000 gallons of heating oil flowed from the Greek
tanker World Prodigy when it ran aground June 23 on Brenton Reef at
the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   Georgudis, 43, of Athens, Greece, agreed to pay a $10,000 fine to
avoid prison and Ballard, a Liberian company, agreed to pay $500,000
to the state for environmental research and land acquisition.
   U.S. District Judge Ernest C. Torres set sentencing for Sept. 15
but reserved the right to reject the pleas if a presentence
investigation turned up other facts.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond said Georgudis ``became distracted
and was also doing computations to double-check'' estimates of how
oil would have to be shifted for unloading.
   ``The ship at some point should have taken a left turn,'' he said.
   Instead, it ran straight onto the rocks.
   According to testimony at a U.S. Coast Guard hearing, Georgudis
and a helmsman were on the bridge at the time. A harbor pilot was
preparing to board the ship to guide it through Narragansett Bay.
   ``He was simply trying to handle more than one person could
handle at one time,'' said Peter DiBiase, Georgudis' attorney.
   Georgudis could have faced one year in prison, and he and Ballard
each could have faced fines of twice the damages, Almond said.
   The captain remained free on $50,000 bail but restricted to Rhode
Island, Massachusetts and New York City, where the ship was repaired
before it left for Greece late last month.
   Georgudis previously told Gov. Edward D. DiPrete and Coast Guard
officials that he made a mistake by not steering the ship away from
the reef and warning buoys and by not having a harbor pilot on board.
   The captain also faces state charges of causing pollution and
failing to have a harbor pilot on board. If convicted of the state
charges, Georgudis could be sentenced to more than one year in
prison and fined $20,000. State Attorney General James O'Neil has
said he would not seek prison time.
   Claude Cote, acting legal counsel for the state Department of
Environmental Management, said the state was negotiating a
settlement for cleanup costs with Ballard. He said the federal plea
agreement would not block state legal action.
   Almond said he decided the state should get the fines because it
suffered more damage than the federal government.
   Ballard will pay $250,000 to an environmental trust fund, some of
which Cote said would be used to develop better oil containment
booms for ocean work. The remaining $250,000 would be used to help
the state acquire coastal property.
   The Coast Guard has estimated cleanup costs at nearly $2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
