<FIRST>r a PM-Smith-Inmates     08-17 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smith-Inmates,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Among Those Mourning Congressman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of prisoners sent flowers to the
wake of Rep. Larkin Smith as a tribute to the former sheriff who
always treated them with respect, one inmate said.
   Twenty prisoners at Harrison County Jail sent a flag-shaped
arrangement of red and white carnations to Wednesday's memorial at a
convention center in Biloxi. Smith and pilot Chuck Vierling, 58,
were killed in a small plane crash Sunday night.
   ``He was a man who helped us realize we weren't just dogs and
trash to throw away,'' said trusty inmate Dennis Alexander, night
shift head cook at the jail.
   Alexander said he and other trusty inmates owe their vocational
skills to programs begun by Smith when he was Harrison County
sheriff.
   ``I liked the man. You talk to some of the trusties and they'll
say, `I don't like you because you're the police,''' said Alexander,
a former truck driver serving a 20-year sentence for sexual battery.
   ``But he never looked at you and said, `I don't like you because
you're an inmate.' He treated people with respect,'' he said.
   Alexander, speaking from the telephone at the jail Wednesday
night, fought back tears remembering the man he had met only once _
after he landed in jail last year.
   Lt. Bruce Carver, a jail supervisor, said Smith began the
vocational programs in 1985 as a way to help prisoners to one day
become ``taxpayers rather than tax-eaters.''
   ``That's the kind of man he was,'' Carver said. ``He left this
kind of impact even on the inmates.''
   Carver was among nearly 2,000 people who had streamed past
Smith's closed casket by Wednesday night. The memorial was to
continued this morning, followed by a funeral Mass and burial in
nearby Gulfport.
</TEXT>
