<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-17 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winds Take Zing Out of Depression; Storms Soak Northern Plains, Arizona</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Upper level winds shredded an Atlantic tropical depression but a
tropical storm watch remains in effect today for the Leeward
Islands, forecasters said.
   At 6 a.m. EDT today, the center of the depression was near
latitude 17.2 degrees north and longitude 54.7 west, about 500 miles
east of the northern Leeward Isles, according to the National
Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla.
   A tropical storm watch continued from Dominica Island in the West
Indies north to the British Virgin Islands as the depression moved
west at about 20 mph with maximum sustained winds of 35 mph.
Forecasters said if the storm threatens the United States, it won't
be until late in the weekend or next week.
   Atmospheric conditions do not favor strengthening of the
depression, a forecaster said. The depression would become a named
storm if its maximum sustained winds reach 39 mph.
   Elsewhere, strong thunderstorms socked the northern Plains with
high winds, large hail and heavy rains, while torrential rains
soaked Arizona.
   Hail one inch in diameter fell Wednesday at Mitchell, Neb.
Thunderstorm winds gusted to 47 mph at Dalhart, Texas.
   More than an inch of rain fell in an hour at Gila Bend, Ariz.,
and strong winds elsewhere in the state caused dust storms.
   Humid air flowing out of the Gulf of Mexico also triggered
thunderstorms across Florida and the middle and southern Atlantic
Coast states.
   Late Wednesday afternoon, strong thunderstorms blew down trees at
Fort Lauderdale, Fla. The trees broke a water main and snapped
utility wires.
   Temperatures early this morning were in the 40s and 50s over the
northern Rockies, the Great Lakes and northern New ENgland. Readings
in the 50s were also along the Pacific Coast.
   The high temperature in the nation Wednesday was 112 degrees at
Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
from the southern half of the Atlantic Coast to across the Tennessee
Valley and the Gulf Coast region to the eastern half of the southern
Plains; showers and thunderstorms also may extend from the northern
Plateau to the northern high Plains Region, and from the southern
and central Rockies to the southern Plateau region.
   Predicted highs: into the 90s from the Florida peninsula to
coastal South Carolina, from Louisiana to New Mexico, and across
much of the Great Basin and the Southwest; above 100 degrees over
the desert Southwest; in the 70s from New England to the northern
Ohio Valley and eastern upper Mississippi Valley, from western
Montana to the northern Pacific Coast, and along the California
coast. Much of the remainder of the nation was to have temperatures
in the 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Gwinn, Mich., to 90 degrees at Imperial, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 cloudy; Boston 70 fair; Buffalo 56 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 76 fair; Cleveland 67 partly cloudy; Detroit 57
partly cloudy; Miami 78 partly cloudy; New York 73 foggy;
Philadelphia 73 foggy; Portland, Maine, 64 fair; Washington, D.C, 75
hazy.
   _Central: Chicago 62 fair; Denver 60 fair; Des Moines 65 fair;
Fort Worth 75 partly cloudy; Indianapolis 65 cloudy; Kansas City 64
foggy; New Orleans 71 foggy; St. Louis 66 foggy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 60 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 cloudy; Anchorage 58 showers; Phoenix 84
cloudy; Salt Lake City 74 partly cloudy; San Diego 67 cloudy; San
Francisco 57 partly cloudy; Seattle 57 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 fair; Toronto 54 fair.
</TEXT>
