<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Congressman     08-17 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Congressman,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Lawmakers See Soviet Laser Shot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several top U.S. lawmakers saw a powerful Soviet
laser fired in a rare display of Soviet high technology, Tass
reported today.
   A group from the House Armed Services Committee, led by Rep. Les
Aspin, D-Wis., toured a branch of the Kurchatov Institute of Atomic
Energy in Troitsk near Moscow on Wednesday.
   ``They were shown the Tokamak experimental thermonuclear
installation and the Angara-5 experimental thermonuclear inertia
installation. The guests were shown a powerful laser in the process
of operation,'' the official news agency said.
   Tass did not describe the installations further, and the
congressmen, who have been touring Soviet military and space
facilities since Aug. 7, were in meetings and unavailable for
comment. They were scheduled to give a news conference Friday before
leaving the country later in the day.
   The New York Times quoted one delegation member, John H. Hammond,
former head of the directed energy program for the Pentagon's
Strategic Defense Organization, as saying the visit revealed
``important new information about Soviet research on gas lasers.''
The article, in today's editions, said the laser blasted a sheet of
metal.
   Hammond said he believed the laser was of limited military value.
   The Pentagon says the Soviets are developing high-energy lasers
for strategic air defense, space-based anti-satellite missions and
defense against ballistic missiles.
   The United States has a similar program.
   The congressmen have also visited a launch site for an SS-11
intercontinental ballistic missile and the Soviet space center at
Baikonur, where they saw the shuttle Buran.
</TEXT>
