<FIRST>r i PM-Turkey-Bulgaria     08-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkey Denies Entry to Bulgarian Train Carrying Ethnic Turks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today said it was barring
indefinitely the entry of a Bulgarian train that for three months
has carried an average of 600 ethnic Turks daily to this country.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Murat Sungar, told The Associated
Press that the decision was made to protest the ``disorderly and
inhuman'' transfer of the ethnic Turks by the Bulgarian government.
   Sungar said the train was overcrowded and the immigrants'
belongings were sent three days later.
   He added that Turkey could review its decision if the Bulgarian
government agrees to make the transfers in a more orderly and humane
way.
   ``The decision does not mean that Turkey closes its border with
Bulgaria,'' Sungar said.
   The exodus continued today with more immigrants crossing the
border by private cars. The number of immigrants who have arrived in
Turkey so far has reached 291,500.
   In May, Bulgaria began deporting ethnic Turks after subjecting
them to a forced assimilation campaign that included changing their
Turkish names to Slavic ones and banning Islamic rites and use of
the Turkish language.
   The deportation grew into an exodus as the ethnic Turks were
permitted to acquire passports and leave the country.
   Bulgaria refuses Turkey's call for talks on an immigration
agreement that would protect the ethnic Turks' legal rights,
including social security benefits and compensation for property
left behind, and restoration of minority rights to those who remain
in Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
