<SECOND>PM-BRF--Juvenile Curfew,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Court Rejects Challenge to Curfew Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iowa Supreme Court has freed local
governments to impose curfews on minors to fight drug abuse and
crime.
   The court, in a 5-4 ruling Wednesday, said a curfew is only a
minor infringement on the rights of children and parents. It upheld
a curfew set in Panora that barred people under 18 from being out
from 10 p.m. to 5 a.m.
   David Simmons, then 15, had challenged the Panora curfew after he
was caught skateboarding at 10:35 p.m. He argued that curfews
unconstitutionally interfere with family rights and violate his
right to move about as he pleased.
   Dissenters in the ruling said the court was allowing fundamental
rights to be trampled because of panic over crime and drugs.
