<FIRST>r a PM-SCLCConvention     08-17 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SCLC Convention,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>SCLC Plans Affirmative Action Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affirmative action programs, weakened by recent
court rulings, can be saved only by lobbying and intensive
fund-raising, an NAACP lawyer told civil rights leaders.
   The NAACP Legal Defense Fund has received seven requests for help
in defending minority set-aside programs, Julius Chambers told the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference at its annual meeting
Wednesday.
   He said it would take about $1 million to lobby for minority
set-aside programs and more to take the cases to court.
   The Supreme Court ``set out with an agenda to rewrite civil
rights, and they've done a pretty successful job,'' Chambers said.
   During its recent term, the court made it easier to challenge
affirmative action programs already in place and made it harder to
initiate and win discrimination suits.
   SCLC President Joseph Lowery said civil rights leaders will
continue trying to persuade the Bush administration to seek
legislation to preserve affirmative action.
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh said earlier this year that
the administration did not intend to pursue the matter.
   Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste, a Democrat, said the Bush
administration has lagged on education and training programs and
affirmative action.
   If the government can find enough money to bail out the savings
and loan industry, ``why can't we find a few billion dollars'' for
Head Start programs and set-aside programs that award public
contracts to minorities, he asked.
   SCLC members agreed to use the vote to pressure lawmakers for
action and said they would work to raise money to help the NAACP
Legal Defense Fund handle requests for help.
   The SCLC convention runs through Friday.
</TEXT>
