<FIRST>r w PM-DC-10Tape 1stLd-Writethru a0449 08-17 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Tape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead and adds one graf at end to change attribution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the interchanges between air
traffic controllers at Farmington, Minn. and the crew of United
Airlines Flight 232 after the explosion of the tail engine on July
19.
   UAL: ``We just lost No. 2 engine. Like to lower our altitude
please.''
   A little later:
   UAL: ``We just lost No. 2 and some hydraulics. The airplane is
marginally controllable here.''
   Controllers issued instructions to other flights and to United
232:
   FARM: ``United 232 descend and maintain flight level 290 and what
will be your intention sir?'' Flight level 290 means 29,000 feet.
   The answer:
   UAL: ``Stand by. Stand by.''
   Seconds later:
   UAL: ``United 232. We're declaring an emergency here (controllers
interject here: ``Declaring an emergency'') and request landing at
the nearest available airport.''
   FARM: ``232, you are cleared to Des Moines.''
   UAL: ``Sir we need the works, 232, we are just, uh, having
trouble controlling the airplane right now.''
   The flight crew is patched through to the company's maintenance
base at San Francisco, where experts can offer nothing that helps.
   Watching the gyrations of the DC-10, a controller notes that
Sioux City is now the closest airport.
   FARM: ``United 232, your present heading looks a little better
for Sioux City. Would you like to go to Sioux City?''
   UAL: ``Affirmative.''
   The pilots are steering by applying different amounts of power to
the two remaining engines, one on each wing.
   UAL: ``We have zero rudder control, uh, no aileron control.''
   The controllers are preparing to turn over the flight to the
control tower at the Sioux City airport:
   FARM (to Sioux City): ``He's having a hard time controlling the
plane right now, trying to slow down and get set on a steady bearing
right now. As soon as he gets comfortable, I will shift him over to
you and he will be yours.''
   Just before touchdown, a wing dipped and caught the ground,
sending the plane spinning into a cornfield and killing 111 of the
296 aboard.
   The tape was first broadcast by ABC News Wednesday night.
</TEXT>
