<FIRST>r p PM-AtlantaMayoral     08-17 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Mayoral,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hosea Williams Enter's Mayoral Race in Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Councilman Hosea Williams, a longtime civil
rights activist, has entered the mayoral race against Maynard
Jackson, offering the most serious challenge to the former mayor's
comeback attempt.
   The 63-year-old former aide to the Rev. Martin Luther King joined
six political unknowns Wednesday, including a comedian and a college
student, in filing to run against Jackson in the non-partisan race
Oct. 3.
   Last week, the withdrawal of Jackson's sole announced opponent,
Fulton County Commissioner Michael Lomax, had cleared the way for
him to return to City Hall for a third term. Lomax had concluded he
couldn't win.
   ``After they scared all other qualified candidates out of the
running, it just didn't leave me no choice if I was to adhere to the
principles I lived by over the past 35 years,'' Williams said in
entering the race.
   Williams, who like Jackson is a black Democrat, said the former
mayor is the candidate of ``a small black clique, an elite clique
and the rich power structure.''
   The 51-year-old Jackson, who served two four-year terms beginning
in 1974, said he is ``elated'' to have opposition.
   Williams, who resigned his City Council seat to make the mayoral
race, said he had no money, no campaign manager and no headquarters
but expects his longtime supporters to rally around his campaign.
   ``I'm not just running a symbolic campaign,'' Williams said.
``I'm running to win. I have something Michael Lomax didn't have _
that's the people. One good volunteer is worth 15 people you hire.''
   He entered the race on the last day of a three-day qualifying
period. Three other candidates avoided the $3,000 filing fee by
qualifying as paupers.
</TEXT>
