<FIRST>r a PM-CamilleRemembered 1stLd-Writethru a0486 08-17 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Camille Remembered, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Recall the Destruction of Hurricane Camille 20 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 bgng, `Savel said ...' to CORRECT name to Sevel
sted Savel.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Sevel wasn't overly concerned that
night 20 years ago as he helped his father maneuver their 65-foot
shrimp boat up the Biloxi River to shelter from an approaching storm.
   But for the Sevels and hundreds of other fishermen along the
Mississippi Gulf Coast on Aug. 17, 1969, the destructive power of
Hurricane Camille would soon become painfully clear.
   Camille's 200 mph winds pushed a wall of water over Mississippi's
coastline, tossing ocean-going ships onto the beach, ripping away
all but the pilings in harbors and damaging or destroying thousands
of coastal homes and businesses.
   The most powerful storm in U.S. history, Camille danced along the
coast for days before roaring ashore in Mississippi. Two hundred
forty-eight people died, including 141 in Mississippi.
   Sevel said his father decided to move their boat to the safety of
the river as soon as the outward winds of the hurricane reached
Gulfport's commercial small craft harbor.
   ``After we moved up the river we tied our boat up to a paperwood
barge,'' said Sevel, 16 at the time. ``Nearby there was a cluster of
pilings and three or four boats tied up between them.''
   Sevel said the water rose higher throughout the night and the
winds whipped up to a howl.
   ``And while you couldn't see them you knew there were tornadoes
moving around us because you could hear the sudden roar,'' he said.
``We had tied to the pilings with several lines and after Camille
came through there was only one line left, the rest had snapped.
   ``We fought all night long and there were times I wasn't sure we
could make it.''
   He said some of the other boats in the pack either sank under the
weight of the rushing water or were pounded into the river banks.
   Frank Wells, 65, said he left Gulfport ahead of the storm and
took his 35-foot shrimp boat up a bayou near his Empire, La., home.
   ``We took shelter behind a ferry on the bayou and we made it fine
but while we were saving the boat, we lost our home,'' he said. ``We
had 18 feet of water come through Empire.''
   Camille destroyed 6,744 homes and damaged 46,709 more, while
destroying or damaging 746 businesses.
   Shrimper Luther Rowell, 53, said his most vivid memory of Camille
was returning to the harbor at Gulfport after weeks of waiting
aboard his boat on the river while crews worked to restore power to
drawbridges.
   ``I remember that when he got back there was no wharf, only
pilings,'' Rowell said. ``We had to take scraps of wood to make a
walk. There was destruction everywhere you turned.''
   Commercial fisherman James L. Ladner of Gulfport spent that night
at his brother's supermarket a few blocks inland but returned the
next morning to the beach area.
   ``I can still remember seeing those three ships that got caught
up on the beach. Two of them had to be scrapped,'' he said. ``All
along the beach there was total destruction and there was nothing
left of U.S. 90,'' then the major traffic route along the
Mississippi coast.
   ``And I remember there were plenty of shrimp out there,'' he said
pointing to the Mississippi Sound. ``But so much stuff had washed
into the water that when you pulled in your nets they were filled
with things like refrigerators, bathtubs and even car batteries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
