<DOCNO> AP890817-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0522,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BEIJING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chinese Defense Minister Reportedly Detained During Power Struggle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with power struggle in Chinese military.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops loyal to China's president detained the
nation's defense minister and several military commanders after a
dispute over who would fill a top military post, Chinese sources
said today.
   The sources said President Yang Shangkun, a mastermind of the
martial law crackdown in Beijing, apparently ordered the move to
strengthen his control of the Chinese military. The post had been
held by Communist Party boss Zhao Ziyang, who was purged for
allegedly supporting the pro-democracy movement.
   Control of the military is an essential ingredient in Chinese
politics. Senior leader Deng Xiaoping's only official post is
chairman of the Central Military Commission, China's top military
body.
   Troops went to the Beijing residence of Defense Minister Qin
Jiwei Wednesday evening and took him and one of his guards away, the
Chinese sources said. Troops later took away the heads of the
Beijing, Guangzhou and Nanjing military districts, who supported Qin
and were in Beijing for an important meeting, the sources said.
   One source said the troops were from the Garrison Headquarters of
Beijing, a special force that protects top military and political
leaders and is directed by Yang. The sources said they believed that
Qin and the others went unwillingly, and the sources said they did
not know where the officials were. It was not immediately possible
to confirm the report.
   However, the sources contacted The Associated Press separately.
   One source is a military officer who called the AP early this
morning from Beijing. The other is a Hong Kong-based businessman,
who said he has extensive contacts within the Chinese military.
   In other developments, a Chinese government spokesman confirmed
in an interview published today that Wang Dan, a leader of the
spring pro-democracy movement and one of the country's most wanted
fugitives, has been arrested.
   State Council spokesman Yuan Mu said Wang was arrested July 2
after meeting with a Taiwanese reporter, who was detained and later
expelled from China.
   Yuan was interviewed by the Japanese newspaper Yomiuri Shimbun,
and his comments were reported by China's official Xinhua news
agency.
   Wang, a 20-year-old history student at Beijing University, went
underground after authorities issued an arrest warrant for him and
20 other students involved in the democracy protests. Eight fugitive
students have been arrested and two are known to have fled the
country.
   Also today, a Shanghai newspaper said authorities arrested or
were investigating 99 people accused of involvement in illegal
workers' groups that plotted to establish a ``people's party'' and
kidnap officials. The groups planned to overthrow the government,
the Shanghai Liberation Daily said.
   Regarding the reported military dispute, Qin and Yang are both
jockeying to fill the post of first vice chairman of the Central
Military Commission, which was occupied by Zhao before he was purged
in June.
   Zhao was purged following the student demonstrations for sweeping
political change in China. Those demonstrations ended on June 3 when
thousands of soldiers attacked protesters and crushed the movement.
   Earlier, Chinese sources had said Qin had opposed martial law in
Beijing and the use of force to clear Tiananmen Square. He was
overruled.
   Moves by Yang to take over Zhao's old post appear to indicate
that he hopes to solidify his control of the military upon Deng's
death. Deng, 84, is reported to be in poor health.
   Yang, who is also 84, is reported to be healthy.
</TEXT>
