<FIRST>r w PM-BostonSludge 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boston Sludge, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0437,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Says Boston Sludge Won't be Shipped to Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, bgng: ``Well, then xxx to give
deatail in contaminants in the sludge.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal official dismisses fears that sludge
from the polluted Boston Harbor will be sold as fertilizer in Texas,
but Sen. Lloyd Bentsen is taking the idea seriously.
   Bentsen, D-Texas, says he's made it clear to the Environmental
Protection Agency that Texas should not become ``the repository of
sludge that is too contaminated to remain in the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts.''
   Bentsen and Texas Agricultural Commissioner Jim Hightower point
to a draft proposal to market Boston sludge as fertilizer, as well
as an internal EPA memo that said the sludge is ``too filthy to be
used as fertilizer under Massachusetts law. It is too filthy for all
of New England and New York.''
   ``Well then, I believe it's too filthy for Massey, New Deal and
New Ulm, Texas, too,'' Hightower told Bentsen in seeking the
senator's support in his fight against hauling ``Boston's pollution
problem halfway across the country so it can then become a Texas
problem.''
   According to Hightower, the sludge contains a relatively high
percentage of industrial toxic waste that is not pretreated,
``leaving it replete with such potentially dangerous contaminants as
mercury, molybdenum, copper and cadmium.''
   Boston Harbor pollution was an issue in the 1988 presidential
campaign, with George Bush accusing Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis of acting too slowly to deal with the problem. Bentsen was
Dukakis' vice presidential running mate.
   ``The Massachusetts Water Resources Authority has no intention,
no contracts, no plans to use these pellets in Texas, principally
because of the high cost of transportation,'' Paul Keough, acting
administrator of the EPA region that includes Massachusetts, said
Wednesday,
   ``There doesn't seem to be any interest in sending the material
to Texas. So there seems to be much ado about nothing,'' Keough said.
   Paul DiNatale, chief spokesman for the Massachusetts water
authority, which is coordinating the Boston Harbor cleanup, took
strong issue with the memo written by EPA headquarters staffers.
   That memo accused the EPA and the water authority of ignoring
proposed water regulations and proceeding to ``shop around for
states with weak environmental laws where they can market their
contaminated sludge as fertilizer. They have focused in on the
Southeast and on Texas and Florida in particular.''
   Although Bentsen said he understands drafts of reports sometimes
never advance beyond the preliminary stages, ``this is one proposal
that should never reach the status of a mature idea.''
</TEXT>
