<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0512,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Accuse Indian Soldiers of Killing 6,000 Civilians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 24 Indian soldiers slain by
guerrillas. Pickup 3rd pvs, `A spokesman...' Edits thereafter to tighten.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil guerrillas today entered a
hospital in a northern town and fired rockets and guns at an Indian
army post on the street below, killing at least 24 soldiers,
officials said.
   The guerrillas entered the main hospital at Mannar, 160 miles
north of Colombo, late Wednesday night and launched the attack
shortly after midnight, officials in Colombo and New Delhi said.
   ``They opened fire in utter disregard of the 89 patients inside
the hospital,'' said a Foreign Ministry official in New Delhi.
``Because the Indian peacekeeping troops were conscious that
retaliatory fire would cause casualties in the hospital, they did
not use heavy weapons.''
   The official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
blamed the attack on the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a rebel
group that has been fighting Indian soldiers deployed in Sri Lanka
to contain the Tamil insurgency.
   He said he knew of no casualties among the rebels or civilians
but added that sporadic fighting around the hospital was continuing.
   In other sectarian violence, the government said 20 killings
occurred Wednesday night and today. The victims included at least
eight young Sinhalese men, whose bodies were found near the capital.
   Before the attack on the Indian army post, the Liberation Tigers
accused Indian troops of killing 6,000 Tamil civilians during the
past 22 months. The accusation was included in an appeal addressed
to the United Nations and demanded the troops be withdrawn as early
as possible. A copy of the appeal was released to reporters
Wednesday night.
   A spokesman at the Indian High Commission, or embassy, said he
had not seen the statement and could not comment on it. An Indian
Foreign Ministry spokesman in New Delhi also declined comment.
   The Tigers' statement also accused Indian troops of widespread
atrocities, torture and extra-judicial killings and claimed that
more than 3,000 Tamil civilians are being held by the soldiers.
   ``During the first months of the Indian offensive to secure the
control of Jaffna city, over 2,000 civilians (were) killed and
several thousand (were) wounded,'' the statement said.
   The Indian offensive began in October 1987. The Tigers' claim of
6,000 deaths since then is nearly double the total compiled from Sri
Lankan and Indian estimates that about 2,500 Tamil civilians and
about 1,100 Tamil guerrillas have been killed in the past 22 months
of fighting. In addition, about 1,000 Indian soldiers have died in
the peacekeeping operation.
   India sent troops to Sri Lanka on July 30, 1987, to enforce an
Indian-Sri Lankan peace accord aimed at ending a Tamil insurgency
for an independent nation. The accord offered limited autonomy to
Tamils in exchange for an arms surrender by Tamil militias.
   The Tamil Tigers reneged on the accord and soon started attacking
the Indian soldiers. Other separatist groups abided by the accord
and joined the political mainstream.
</TEXT>
