<HEAD>Leland Crash Investigators End Inspection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with probe finished. Pickup 3rd,
`They...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crash investigators left Ethiopia
today after inspecting the wreckage of the twin-engine plane that
carried U.S. Rep. Mickey Leland and 15 other people to their deaths.
   The American and Canadian specialists spent Wednesday nd part of
today on the steep slopes of Tam mountain in southwestern Ethiopia
looking through the remains of the Twin Otter that slammed nose
first into a cliff while en route to a refugee camp Aug. 7.
   They announced no findings, but sources close to the
investigation said bad weather and faulty judgment by the pilot were
at least contributing factors in the crash.
   The sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the
pilot had been warned by weather forecasters of heavy clouds, rain
and poor visibility all along his planned 300-mile route.
   The plane's takeoff from Addis Ababa's Bole Airport was delayed
for two hours by bad weather and flying conditions were still only
marginal when it finally left the ground.
   Sources said the weather was even worse in the southwest,
although radar scans showed a break in the clouds over Leland's
destination, the Fugnido refugee camp.
   The investigating team was made up of members of the U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board, its Canadian counterpart and
representatives of the Boeing and Pratt and Whitney companies.
   Boeing provided the airframe and Pratt and Whitney built the
engines of the craft, which was manufactured in a Canadian plant.
   The investigation is being conducted jointly with the Ethiopian
Civil Aviation Authority.
   Eight other Americans and seven Ethiopians, including the pilot,
accompanied the Texas Democrat on the flight. U.S. military forensic
experts were trying to identify their remains, which were recovered
from the mountain Tuesday.
</TEXT>
