<FIRST>r i PM-ZiaMemorial     08-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zia Memorial,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zia Memorial Turns into Anti-Bhutto Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people today
marked the first anniversary of the death of President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq by holding an anti-government rally denouncing his successor,
Benazir Bhutto.
   The Zia loyalists either walked or jammed teetering buses to
converge on the capital's huge Faisal Mosque for a prayer sevice.
   ``Death to Benazir Bhutto!'' and ``Benazir is a traitor and an
agent of the Russians and Indians!'' the crowd shouted. It was the
largest rally by oppenents of Ms. Bhutto's 8-month-old government.
   Unofficial estimates put the crowd total at 50,000.
   ``What we had before was a military dictatorship. Now we have a
civilian dictatorship,'' said one bystander.
   Zia, U.S. Ambasador Arnold Raphel and 28 other people died in the
crash of Zia's presidential plane Aug. 17, 1988. Investigators said
it appeared to be sabotage, but they have not said who was
responsible.
   Pakistani officials have blamed hundreds of terrorist attacks in
recent years on Soviet-trained agents of neighboring Afghanistan's
communist government. Zia was a staunch supporter of Afghan
guerrillas fighting to overthrow the communists. The guerrillas also
have long received military equipment sent by the United States at
their bases in Pakistan.
   Hundreds of policemen and federal officers were called into the
tree-lined capital to keep order today.
   The government appealed to activists of Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan
People's Party not to hold counterdemonstrations that might provoke
violence.
   Zia seized power in a 1977 military coup by ousting Ms. Bhutto's
father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto. The elder Bhutto was hanged two years
later after being convicted of plotting to kill a political opponent.
   After Zia's death, Pakistan held its first free elections in more
than a decade. Ms. Bhutto's party won a simple majority in the
national legislature. Conservatives and Zia's proteges captured the
biggest of Pakistan's four provinces.
   There were no formal speeches given at today's rally.
   Banners bearing Zia's picture fluttered from light poles along
the avenue leading to the mosque.
   Zia's son, Ijaz, led a late afternoon prayer service with family,
friends and right-wing political allies at Zia's sarcophagus.
</TEXT>
