<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     08-17 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>121 Boat People Return To Vietnam, Largest Group Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 120 Vietnamese who fled their homeland
by boat headed back by plane today in the biggest voluntary return
of refugees from this British colony.
   Waving handkerchiefs and clutching bags packed with clothes and
radios, the refugees boarded a Boeing 737 at Hong Kong's airport and
took off for Hanoi.
   From there the 46 men, 40 women, 17 boys and 18 girls will be
taken to their hometowns and monitored by the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees.
   ``I think this is an extremely hopeful sign,'' said Robert van
Leeuwen, head of the U.N. refugee office in Hong Kong, as the jet
took off.
   Originally, 124 people had volunteered to return, but three were
forced to stay in Hong Kong for medical reasons, van Leeuwen said.
   He said 190 more people were awaiting a chance to return to
Vietnam and that 600 to 700 more refugees had already applied to go
back.
   ``Voluntary repatriation is the best shot,'' van Leeuwen said.
   The remark was significant because Vietnam and Britain are
negotiating a plan to force many of the 51,000 Vietnamese refugess
living in Hong Kong back to Vietnam.
   The communist government in Hanoi said it will not prosecute
those returning to the country, one of the poorest in Asia. U.N.
officials today reiterated that they will closely monitor the fate
of the returning refugees.
   Until last year, Hong Kong allowed all Vietnamese refugees to
settle in Hong Kong if they could not go to another country.
   But to stem the flood to the crowded colony of 5 million, the
government in June ruled out resettlement for new refugees unless
they could prove they were escaping political persecution.
   Since then, about 38,300 Vietnanmese have sailed to Hong Kong and
are being housed in a series of camps, detention centers and halfway
houses. About 4,700 live in tents on a nearby island and another
1,800 cram five ferries.
   Van Leeuwen said adult returnees had been given $150 each and
children 14 years or under were given $75 each when they returned.
   Several boat people interviewed this week said they were going
home because they missed their families.
   ``I miss my old mother very much,'' said Le Thi Minh, from
Haiphong. She said her brother was unable to care for their mother
because he is in jail for attempting to flee Vietnve to take risks,'' she
said about returning home,
``but the pull of my family is too strong.''
   Van Leeuwen said U.N. officials will help resettle the returning
refugees, providing assistance on a case-by-case basis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
