<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Germany-Space     08-17 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Germany-Space,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Attempt to Ignite Booster Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARMSTADT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fourth attempt to boost a
star-gazing satellite into its designated orbit failed Thursday, and
the mission may have to be revised, the European Space Agency said.
   A fifth attempt to ignite the booster of the High Precision
Parallax Collecting Satellite will be made Monday, the agency said.
   The Apogee Boost Motor is needed to propel the satellite into its
geostationary orbit at an altitute of 22,320 miles above the equator.
   Hipparcos, launched Aug. 9 by the space agency's Ariane rocket,
is designed to provide precise measurement of the positions and
motion of the stars.
   Scientists involved in the project are considering a revised
mission for the satellite in case the they fail to ignite the
booster, according to a statement from the space agency's operations
center in Darmstadt, near Frankfurt.
   The satellite then may remain in an elliptical orbit that would
reduce its projected mission goals by about half.
</TEXT>
