<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0533,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Suggests Rewrite of Union Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CORRECT that party did not accept rewrite
of treaty. Pickup 7th pvs, `That could...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party today suggested a rewrite of
the agreement that formed the Soviet Union, opening the possibility
for complete change in the nation's structure.
   Party leaders also said the 15 Soviet republics might be able to
``question'' national laws before a high court with greater powers,
according to a draft policy published in the Communist Party daily
Pravda.
   It appeared to be a partial concession to the Baltic republics of
Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania, which have amended their
constitutions to have the right to reject national laws. The Kremlin
has said this violates the Soviet Constitution.
   The draft policy also calls for a law banning ``nationalist and
chauvinist'' organizations, which could be used against groups
demanding independence from the central government.
   The party's Central Committee is to act on the measures at a
meeting in September.
   The party said that to achieve a transformation of the Soviet
federation, ``the question has been raised of working out and
signing a new union agreement instead of the Treaty on the Formation
of the U.S.S.R. of 1922.''
   That could be limited to expanding the powers of the 15
republics, but it also opens the possibility that radicals could
push through a complete change.
   Human rights activist Andrei Sakharov has suggested a loose
confederation of sovereign states, and many nationalists in the
Baltics and Georgia have called for secession from the Soviet Union.
   Aigar Irgens, an editor at Atmoda, the newspaper of the Latvian
Popular Front, said of the party's proposal: ``We don't want a new
agreement. We want complete independence.''
   Many of the more than 100 nationalities in the Soviet Union have
formed groups to agitate for changes ranging from restoration of
their native languages to secession.
   The proposed law against ``nationalist and chauvenist
organizations'' could target pro-secession groups such as the Party
of National Independence in Georgia, Russian strikers protesting a
new language law in Estonia, or the mass-membership Estonian Popular
Front, which supported the language law.
   Irgens said the effect of the proposed ban would depend on the
definition of nationalist. ``We have nationalist groups in Latvia,
but the term is very broad,'' he said.
   The Communist Party proposal says the republics ``can raise the
question'' of rejecting national laws they believe exceed the
authority of the central government. But it says the central
government has the power to cancel unconstitutional laws passed in
the republics.
   The party suggests that such disputes be settled by the
Constitutional Control Commission, a new quasi-Supreme Court created
in last year's political reform.
   Publication of the draft proposal was highly unusual in that it
came prior to its adoption. Until recently, the party did not
announce the dates and agendas of its Central Committee meetings
until they were under way.
   The draft, which was approved by the ruling Politburo, is
expected to be discussed by party officials in the republics prior
to next month's meeting.
   That meeting has been postponed several times because of ethnic
violence that has killed more than 200 people in the last year and a
half.
   In hopes of heading off futher conflict, the party proposal calls
for a law that would guarantee the rights of citizens living outside
their national boundaries.
   It also calls for creation of a government entity to handle
ethnic relations.
   In Helsinki, Finland today, Gen. Dmitri Yazov, the Soviet defense
minister, said the Soviet Union would not increase its military
presence in the Baltic republics, despite strikes and demonstrations
in the region.
   ``The situation in the Baltic republics is due to our domestic
policies of glasnost and perestroika, and as you well understand,
the results have not always been positive,'' Yazov told reporters
during a three-day visit to Finland that ends Friday.
   ``Glasnost and perestroika are not meant for everyone, and the
new legislation in Estonia is a step backward,'' Yazov said,
referring to new Estonian legislation requiring a minimum two years
residence in the republic to vote in local elections. ``Glasnost''
and ``perestroika'' are the catchwords of President Mikhail
Gorbachev's economic and social reforms.
   The new Estonian legislation prompted the strikes by ethnic
Russians alleging discrimination. On Wednesday, the national
Presidium declared the new Estonian election law unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
