<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Crash     08-17 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-Crash,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Blames Pilot For Air Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilot error was to blame for the Aug. 3
crash of an Olympic Airways plane that killed all 34 people aboard,
the government said Thursday.
   An investigation blamed veteran pilot Petros Moutzoureas for his
``wrong assessment'' of the aircraft's position in the clouds, his
``failure to change the plane's altitude to avoid the mountain'' and
his ``failure in maintaining flight regulations,'' according to
Communications Minister Nikos Gelestathis.
   The Shorts SD 3-30 twin-engine turboprop aircraft was on an
inter-island flight after departing from Salonica, northern Greece,
when it slammed into the sheer granite slopes of 4,785-foot Mount
Kerkis in dense fog minutes before it was scheduled to land on Samos
island.
   Olympic said Moutzoureas, 42, had logged 8,000 hours of flight
time on the British-built aircraft.
   Rescuers found the remains of the three crew and 31 passengers
and parts of the plane, at the 3,960-foot level of Mount Kerkis, the
highest mountain in the Aegean. Eight of the dead were from Canada.
</TEXT>
