<FIRST>r a PM-SymphonyDispute     08-17 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Symphony Dispute,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Symphony Performances Scrubbed in Labor Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oregon Symphony Association's first two
concerts of the season have been canceled in a contract dispute with
its 85 musicians.
   Orchestra management said it considers the musicians to be on
strike, which the union disputed. Contract talks have been going on
for nine months.
   The first performance of the 1989-90 season was to have been
Tuesday. Besides canceling that and an Aug. 27 concert in Astoria,
the dispute threatens the opening of the symphony's subscription
season on Sept. 17.
   ``In light of the union's public statements that it would not
play without a contract, the symphony considers the union to be on
strike as of today,'' Carlos Wilson, managing director of the
association, said Wednesday.
   ``This is not a strike,'' said Robert Findlay,
secretary-treasurer of the American Federation of Musicians Local
99. ``The musicians have not walked off the job.''
   The players' old three-year contract expired June 13. At issue
are wages and hours.
   The American Symphony Orchestra League ranked the Oregon
Symphony's pay 32nd among the country's 40 major symphony orchestras.
</TEXT>
