<SECOND>AM-BRF--Satellite Launch,0123</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navigation Satellite Scheduled for Launch Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force will try again Friday
to launch the third in a new series of military navigation
satellites.
   Liftoff of the Delta 2 rocket was scheduled for 1:50 a.m. Four
earlier dates were scrubbed by weather and by a schedule conflict
with the Aug. 8 launch of space shuttle Columbia.
   The $65 million Navstar satellite is to join a network of
navigation spacecraft whose signals can tell U.S. and allied
military forces where they are to within 50 feet anywhere in the
world.
   The satellite is the third of 21 improved Navstars the Air Force
plans to orbit to complete a global system by 1992.
