<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GeorgesBank     08-17 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georges Bank,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georges Bank Surf Clam Beds Closed Because of Toxins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clam beds on Georges Bank have been closed because
of high levels of toxins caused by red tide.
   The 90-day closing of the fishing grounds 100 miles east of Cape
Cod to surf-clam harvesters was declared last week by the U.S.
Department of Commerce.
   High quantities of paralytic shellfish toxins were found in the
clams, said Brian Gorman of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration. Red tide toxin causes tingling on the tongue and
lips and can lead to respiratory failure and death.
   Gorman said he believed it was the first time in the roughly five
years that surf clams have been extensively fished on the bank that
the area was closed because of red tide, an algae-like organism
normally found in shellfish closer to shore.
   Surf clams are used mainly in canned soup and other processed
food because they are tougher than regular clams found in coastal
waters, Gorman said.
   The value of the surf clam catch in that area last year was
$800,000, said Jack Terrill, a resource policy analyst for the
National Marine Fisheries Service in Gloucester.
   Terrill said finding the toxins in shellfish so far from shore
``caught everybody by surprise.''
</TEXT>
