<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     08-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Killed, 41 Injured in Series of Explosions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded in the Chittagong
hills, killing at least 11 people and injuring 41 others, police
said Thursday. A senior police officer blamed Buddhist insurgents.
   At least 10 people were killed and 40 injured in two blasts
Wednesday, according to the officer in Khagrachari, 110 miles
southeast of Dhaka.
   One explosion occurred in a crowded market in Khagrachari and the
other in a passenger boat on a lake in Rangamati, 45 miles south of
Khagrachari, he said.
   The boat was severely damaged in the blast, he said. It was not
known how many people were aboard.
   On Tuesday, a bomb exploded on a road in Khagrachari, killing one
person and wounding another, according to the officer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   No one has claimed responsibility for the blasts, but the officer
blamed them on Buddhist tribal insurgents from the Army for Peace.
The insurgents are fighting for more autonomy for the tribes of the
Chittagong Hill Tracts.
   More than 4,000 people have been killed since the insurrection
began 14 years ago. The hills cover 5,200 square miles of
inhospitable land bordering Burma and the northeastern Indian states
of Tripura and Mizoram.
   Police said one suspected member of the Shanti Bahini was killed
in a gunbattle Tuesday with the border security guards. The fighting
between the security forces and the guerrillas has prompted more
than 50,000 tribespeople to flee to Tripura.
</TEXT>
