<FIRST>r a PM-TankerCollision     08-17 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Collision,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship, Tanker Collide in Columbia River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian vessel carrying soda ash
collided with a fully loaded oil tanker and ran aground today on the
Columbia River, but neither vessel lost any cargo, the Coast Guard
said.
   The Panamanian ship, the 172-foot T.S. Prosperity, was about five
miles from Longview, Wash., and 55 miles inland when the collision
with the 11 million-gallon Chevron Louisiana occurred at 2:50 a.m.,
said Lt. Cmdr. David Gault.
   The cause of the accident was under investigation, said Lt. Cmdr.
Guy Nolan.
   ``Both vessels sounded all their tanks and there's no sign of
anything leaking,'' he said.
   The Panamanian ship, which was carrying about 24,500 metric tons
of soda ash, was refloated at 5:48 a.m. and continued on to Japan,
Gault said.
   The 651-foot oil tanker, which had been headed for Portland with
a heavy mixture of asphalt and diesel, was anchored in Longview this
morning, Nolan said.
   ``We'll have divers and the appropriate people checking things
before they go anywhere,'' he said.
</TEXT>
