<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia-Refugees     08-17 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia-Refugees,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>8,000 Flee Renewed Fighting in Northwestern Somalia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed fighting in northwestern
Somilia has forced about 8,000 people to flee to Ethiopia in the
past two weeks, according to a U.N. official.
   Albert-Alain Peters, an Addis Ababa representative of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, said Wednesday that about 650
refugees were entering Ethiopia daily, up from 150 at the beginning
of August.
   The refugees had reported heavy fighting between the rebel Somali
National Movement and government troops around the garrison town of
Borama near the Ethiopian border, Peters said.
   Borama is about 60 miles northwest of Hargeisa, Somalia's
second-largest town.
   The refugees, mostly women and children, are camped in a remote
area six miles from the border and about 250 miles northeast of
Ethiopia's capital, Addis Ababa.
   Peters, who returned from a visit to the area Wednesday, said the
U.N. agency would start caring for the refugees as soon as Ethiopian
authorities moved them to more easily accessible areas farther
inside the country.
   They are the latest in a wave of refugees who started coming
across the border in May 1988 when fighting intensified between the
rebels and government troops around the northern towns of Hargeisa,
Burao and Berbera. An estimated 350,000 Somalis have sought refuge
in U.N.-managed camps near Jijiga, about 60 miles southwest of the
new arrivals.
   The Somali National Movement has been fighting to topple the
government of President Mohamed Siad Barre since 1981.
   Exiled dissidents recently have claimed Barre's government has
lost control of all but the capital and is experiencing the most
widespread fighting across the East African nation since Barre
seized power in 1969.
   The dissidents say that in addition to the northern fighting,
soldiers who belong to the Ogadeni clan have turned against the
government in the south.
   A Kenyan newspaper reported that more than 5,500 Somalis had fled
to Kenya following government raids on their southern Somali border
town last month.
   It is impossible to confirm rebel claims independently. The
government has refused to let journalists into Somalia since May
1988 and Mogadishu residents contacted by telephone say they know
little about events outside the capital.
</TEXT>
