<FIRST>u w PM-Trident-DesignFlaw 1stLd-Writethru a0472 08-17 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trident-Design Flaw, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Navy: Design Flaw Caused Two Failed Launchings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Top 9 grafs new with Navy comment; picks up at pvs 8th graf,
The Trident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is looking into a possible design
miscalculation in its largest nuclear missile, the Trident 2, that
may have caused the latest test failure of the weapon.
   Rear Adm. Kenneth C. Malley, chief of the Navy's ballistic
missile program, said that despite computer simulations, engineers
seriously underestimated the amount of pressure on the Trident as it
thrusts upward after being launched from underwater.
   Malley, in an interview published today in The New York Times,
said designers had failed to foresee how the movement of the missile
would cause ``water jets'' and the effect they would have on the
missile.
   Although the Navy said it could not make Malley available for an
interview, it did confirm that his statements to the Times were
accurate.
   Navy spokesman Lt. Greg Smith said the service retains ``full
confidence'' in the Trident system, and that ``no impact is
presently foreseen'' on the planned deployment of the submarine USS
Tennessee with the missiles in early 1990.
   In a statement, the Navy said the submarine will undergo a
two-month ``shakedown'' at the Electric Boat docks in Groton, Conn.,
where ``evaluation and correction action for the test failure will
be conducted.''
   In the interview, Malley said the missile ``is much larger than
anything we've fired before. ... We expected some extra pressure on
the rear end of the missile and its rocket nozzles, but not as much
as we're seeing. It turns out that the pressure and the aft load are
much more severe than was anticipated.''
   Asked if the failures were a result of a design error or a flaw
in the manufacturing, the admiral said: ``The device was built to
specification. There is no question that it was designed the way it
was intended to be designed.''
   The first Trident 2 exploded off the east coast of Florida four
seconds after it was launched from a submarine on March 21. The
second test was considered largely successful but the third missile
to be launched self-destructed on Tuesday.
   The Trident 2 is expected to be deployed in the 1990s aboard a
new generation of submarines. With up to eight large nuclear
warheads, it is supposed to be the Navy's centerpiece in the U.S.
nuclear arsenal until 2032.
   Until the test failures, the missile had been one of the Defense
Department's nuclear modernization programs to be mostly
problem-free, with 16 of 19 successful land launchings.
   Engineers apparently failed to anticipate the amount and effect
of turbulence on the new missile during its underwater movement. At
44 feet and 130,000 pounds, it is much longer and almost twice as
heavy as its earlier version, the Trident 1.
   Because of the miscalculation, the original nozzles on the
missile's first-stage rocket did not have the strength to withstand
the increased turbulence, Malley said.
   The nozzles were redesigned after the first failure but tests
must be done to determine why they failed during Tuesday's
launching, he said.
   Malley said he was confident the Trident 2 would be ready as
scheduled on March 31 once the department he heads, the Stategic
Systems Program Office, fixes the missile.
   Because of the large number of Navy officials and subcontractors
working on the Trident program, it was not immediately clear when or
by whom the miscalculations were made, the Navy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PhoneStrikes-Impact Bjt   08-17 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Strikes-Impact, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Installation, Repairs Slower; Operator Service Picking Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New telephone installation remained backlogged
Thursday by a strike at four regional Bell phone companies, but
customers were having better luck reaching operator assistance,
company and union officials said.
   Bill Bickers, spokesman for the striking Communications Workers
of America local at Bell Atlantic, said service was ``spotty in some
places'' as management personnel were pressed into unfamiliar
duties. ``The company's slow on installation and repairs in some
locations.''
   Operator-assisted calls also were ``not up to normal snuff, but
it's moderate,'' Bickers said. ``In some locations it's really
slow.''
   Recorded messages continued to tell 411 directory assistance
callers that ``due to the work stoppage, your call may be delayed.''
But telephone company officials said the waits were becoming shorter
as managers got to know the computer equipment.
   ``We're finding that the delays have dissipated some because of
the fact that our temporary operators have become more proficient
with their skills,'' said Steve Ford, a spokesman for one of the
four companies, Ameritech.
   Operator-assisted calls, maintenance and repairs were being
handled at near pre-strike levels in many areas, officials said.
   But on-premises installations continued to be hard hit because of
the strike by nearly 200,000 operators, clerks, technicians and
others represented by the CWA and the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   The strike began Aug. 6 against NYNEX, Bell Atlantic and Pacific
Telesis and on Aug. 13 against Ameritech. The walkouts affected
phone service in 20 states and the District of Columbia.
   ``We are deferring service that requires dispatch of a human
being,'' said Larry Plumb, a spokesman for Philadelphia-based Bell
Atlantic. ``But if they are using service already in place ... that
kind of service is being taken care of. In a typical week that is 65
percent of the work.''
   ``Customers who are doing direct dialing are receiving service as
normal,'' Plumb said. ``Where customers need to talk to a company
representative, we've seen improvement in services since the work
stoppage as managers have gotten more familiar with their jobs.''
   Plumb said operator assistance ``has returned to pre-work
stoppage levels.'' As for directory assistance, ``There are some
customers who will experience delays ... but we have seen
improvements.''
   Plumb said the lengths of the delays ``vary widely.''
   The phone companies urged callers to dial direct when possible,
use their telephone directories and postpone routine calls about
billing.
   The phone networks are highly automated, and the strike primarily
was affecting labor-intensive areas such as installation and
operator assistance.
   Melissa Morin, president of striking local 1400 of the CWA in New
Hampshire, said, ``Directory assistance is running about a minute to
two minutes delay.''
   She added, however, ``In some cases I know some people sat
waiting 15 minutes for an operator.''
   Morin said her 200-member local had shut down business phone
installation in the New Hampshire areas served by NYNEX.
   ``As far as business offices are concerned, you can't get new
service at all,'' Morin said. ``Repairs are considerably backed up.
The last I heard it was about a five-day wait to get a phone fixed''
in Northeastern areas where heavy rains have sparked failures.
   However, Andrea Dudley, a spokeswoman for NYNEX-owned New England
Telephone Co., said installations were proceeding, albeit slowly.
   ``Obviously, we are having to set priorities, and phone service
to fire departments and police ... would have priority,'' she said.
``Obviously, we are having delays, but we are working through our
orders.
   ``There are still delays in reaching directory assistance and
getting assistance for operator calls, and we still have
installation and repair delays,'' Dudley said.
   ``The key challenge is installation,'' Ameritech's Ford
acknowledged. ``If it requires a promised visit, that may take
longer than it normally would.''
   In Indiana, for instance, ``instead of two days it may be three
or four days'' before an on-premises installation may be arranged,
Ford said.
   Scott Smith, a spokesman for Pacific Bell in San Francisco, said:
``Our repair service is normal, for the most part. ... Directory
assistance and operator assistance are near normal.'' Installation
was ``slow'' in some areas.
</TEXT>
