<DOCNO> AP890817-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nixon     08-17 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Refuses Judge Walter Nixon New Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Thursday refused to
grant a new trial for U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon, a
Mississippi judge who was convicted of perjury and impeached.
   The three-judge panel of the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
a lower court ruling.
   Nixon, who is serving a five-year sentence, was convicted of two
counts of perjury after denying in 1984 before a federal grand jury
and Justice Department investigators that he intervened in a
narcotics case involving the son of a Hattiesburg, Miss., business
executive. Nixon was acquitted of accepting an illegal gratuity.
   The U.S. House unanimously impeached Nixon in May and sent the
case on to the Senate for trial to decide if he should be ousted
from office. The case is expected to go before before a 12-member
Senate panel next month.
   Nixon, who was imprisoned at Eglin Air Force Base in Florida, has
been sent to a halfway house in New Orleans to complete his
sentence. He has collected more than $286,000 in salary since his
conviction.
   Nixon based his appeal for a new trial on claims that the
government withheld information, that the business executive
recanted some of his trial testimony, and that the government
knowingly presented false testimony.
   The court disagreed, saying, ``Judge Nixon was not denied a
fundamentally fair trial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
