<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-17 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Warns Against Protests on Invasion Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it
will crack down on all public protest on Monday, the anniversary of
the 1968 Soviet-led invasion. Four activists were charged with
incitement.
   The warning, carried by the state news agency CTK, reflected
official concern and the determination to stifle all shows of
dissent by activists seeking political reforms.
   Police investigators in Bratislava, capital of Slovakia, charged
four dissidents with incitement for ``spreading alarming material in
Bratislava and other places in Slovakia,'' an Interior Ministry
statement said. They were identified as Jan Carnogursky, Miroslav
Kusy, Hana Ponicka and Anton Selecky.
   Carnogursky and Kusy also were charged with subversion of the
republic and were arrested Thursday, the Interior Ministry said. The
two had called on people to lay wreaths on the graves of victims of
the 1968 invasion.
   If convicted, they could be sentenced to up to five years in
prison on the incitement charge and 10 years under the subversion
charge.
   The 1968 invasion crushed the short-lived ``Prague Spring''
liberalization period spearheaded by then Communist Party leader
Alexander Dubcek, who was ousted in April 1969 and lives as a
pensioner in Bratislava.
   ``The Czechoslovak government ... has decided to thwart
anti-social intentions to secure law, peace and order,'' the
government statement said. ``We are appealing to all citizens to
support these efforts with their actions and attitudes.''
   ``It is no accident that exactly at this time so important for
further process of restructuring and democratization, anti-socialist
groups supported from abroad want to misuse the anniversary of Aug.
21, 1968, to create tension and violence,'' the government said.
   ``Disregarding the demagoguery used, their actions are
objectively aimed against restructuring and democratization,
fundamental human values, against socialism,'' it said.
   Six independent groups last week called on activists to stage
short silent public protests on streets Monday but suggested they
refrain from demonstrations to avoid police brutality.
   Similarly, prominent Czech dissident Vaclav Havel on Tuesday
appealed to citizens not to resort to street protests. He instead
urged citizens to sign the petition known as ``A Few Sentences,''
which has garnered an estimated 15,000 signatures since June.
</TEXT>
