<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1411EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     08-17 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-U.S. Laser Expert Says Soviet Laser Not State-of-the-Art</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of U.S. laser weapons research said
Thursday he was impressed by a Soviet laser he saw melt a piece of
metal, but added that neither superpower would consider the
equipment state-of-the-art technology.
   John Hammond, former head of the directed energy program for the
Pentagon's Strategic Defense Organization, and several top U.S.
lawmakers saw the powerful laser in action Wednesday.
   Hammond said in an interview the powerful ``megawatt carbon
dioxide'' laser at a secretive branch of the Kurchatov Institute of
Atomic Energy in Troitsk near Moscow once was thought to have
potential military applications, but now other types of lasers are
more promising.
   ``This type of laser technology as to high power does not have a
lot of relevance to more strategic-type weapons such as SDI,''
Hammond said, referring to the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative,
popularly called ``Star Wars.''
   ``Nevertheless,'' he added, ``it was quite an impressive thing to
accomplish.''
   Of the visit itself, he said, ``This does in fact represent an
openness on the part of the Soviet Union.''
   Hammond was joined by a group from the House Armed Services
Committee, led by Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., who wind up a visit to the
Soviet Union on Friday.
   The former SDI official said the United States developed the type
of laser he saw demonstrated 10 years ago and that both Washington
and Moscow later concluded it would be ``unprofitable for laser
weapons.''
   In the demonstration, the laser produced a beam for three seconds
that partially melted a block of metal and spewed out balls of
ignited gas, Hammond said.
   The congressmen were also shown two devices used in research on
fusion energy.
   The Pentagon says the Soviets are developing high-energy lasers
for strategic air defense, space-based anti-satellite missions and
defense against ballistic missiles.
   The United States has a similar program.
   The lawmakers have been touring Soviet military and space
facilities since Aug. 7 and have seen several previously secret
facilities.
   On Thursday, they met with Yevgeny Primakov, the chairman of one
of the two houses of the Soviet legislature, and discussed setting
up a Soviet-American committee on arms control, Tass reported. They
also discussed joint work between the U.S. Congress and Supreme
Soviet in freeing Soviets missing or captured in Afghanistan and
Americans missing or captured in North Korea, Vietnam and Laos, the
news agency said.
   Later in the day, Rep. Arthur Ravenel Jr., R-S.C., challenged a
Soviet official about emigration policy. He said the congressmen met
Wednesday night with a group of refuseniks, Jews refused permission
to emigrate, whom he described as ``very sad, poor, dissatisfied
apparently harmless people who just want to leave.''
   Georgy Arbatov, head of the U.S.A.-Canada Institute _ a Kremlin
think tank and a member of the Communist Party's policy-making
Central Committee _ replied: ``If it depended on me, I would kick
them out immediately.''
   Arbatov blamed bureaucrats obsessed with preserving ``state
security'' for blocking the emigration of some Soviets. He
challenged Ravenel's estimate that there were 700 refuseniks, saying
there were just ``a couple dozen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
