<FIRST>r a AM-AbusedWifeTrial     08-17 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abused Wife Trial,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Abused Wife Takes Stand At Her Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with murdering her
husband after he beat her detailed years of abuse during testimony
Thursday, then broke down as she recalled stabbing him and seeing
him covered with blood.
   ``I saw the blood coming from his ear, from his nose and his
mouth. Then I hugged him and kissed him. That's how I got blood all
over me,'' Donna Ordway said, sobbing loudly.
   Superior Court Judge Robert D. Krause called an early lunch
recesss so Mrs. Ordway could regain her composure.
   David Ordway was stabbed Feb. 7, 1987, in the couple's Glocester
home. Mrs. Ordway claimed self-defense. She could face life in
prison if convicted.
   Her first-degree murder trial is believed to be the first time
the battered-spouse defense has been used in Rhode Island.
Prosecutors contend her statements after the stabbing showed that
Mrs. Ordway planned the killing.
   Mrs. Ordway, 28, said the beatings began 1{ years before her June
1985 marriage to Ordway, a neighbor who had moved in with her.
   ``He'd backhand me, punch me, kick me, rip my clothes off.... .
In my head, my ribs, anywhere,'' she testified, sometimes crying and
dabbing her eyes with tissues.
   Mrs. Ordway recalled having her head smashed through a wall and
seeking medical treatment several times, at least once for a cracked
rib. The beatings occurred as often as three times a week after they
were married and would start after they had been drinking, or if her
husband had financial or work problems.
   Mrs. Ordway said her husband would beat her after telling her:
``I'm not a woman, that I'm not any good in bed. Things like that.''
   On the night of the killing friends came to the house from
another party, but Ordway became enraged and stomped out after his
wife asked one guest if she could have his puppy, Mrs. Ordway said.
   He returned, found her talking on the telephone with her mother
and began beating her and dragged her by the hair into the living
room, where he forced her to lie down, she said.
   Mrs. Ordway said she got up, but her husband had an ``enraged,
blank look in his eyes.''
   ``He had his hands out coming for me and I noticed the knife on
the TV and I said, `Stay away from me you s.o.b.' ... He said
nothing and just came after me and I stabbed him.''
   Mrs. Ordway said her husband fell but she thought he would attack
again until she saw the blood. Then she ran into the kitchen, threw
the knife in the sink and called an emergency squad, she said.
   Krause denied a defense motion to dismiss the charges, saying
there was ``ample evidence'' that Mrs. Ordway may have had malice.
   Witnesses have testified Mrs. Ordway told them she knew her
husband would be killed. Krause noted police testimony that Mrs.
Ordway told them they should have let her husband bleed to death
rather than calling medics.
   Mrs. Ordway testified that she stayed with her husband despite
the beatings because, ``I loved him, and I didn't have any money and
I had kids and I had no family and nowhere to go.''
</TEXT>
