<FIRST>r a PM-DescramblingRaid 1stLd-Writethru a0598 08-17 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Descrambling Raid, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0598,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Seizes Thousands of Pay TV Decoders in Raid of Two Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `He said ...' to fix `when' to `which.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents say they raided two electronics
companies and confiscated up to 18,000 illegal devices for
unscrambling pay TV signals.
   Wednesday's seizure was the largest such haul in a series of
raids across the country aimed at cable TV piracy, an industry
official said.
   B &amp; B Inc. in Eagan and Lake Sylvan Sales in Burnsville, which
were selling the devices, are being investigated for possible
copyright and wire fraud violations, the FBI said. No arrests were
made Wednesday.
   The devices unscramble cable and satellite TV signals, allowing
viewers to receive broadcasts without paying for them.
   Dennis Sackreiter, Minneapolis FBI agent in charge of
white-collar crime investigations, said cable companies supply
converters that unscramble channels such as HBO and ESPN to TV
viewers who pay for those channels. The unscrambling is done by
patented and copyrighted computer chips.
   He said cable companies sell outdated converters to companies
such as Lake Sylvan and B &amp; B, which then update them, illegally.
   Some 10,000 to 15,000 descramblers were taken from Lake Sylvan
Sales and 2,000 to 3,000 were confiscated from B &amp; B, Sackreiter
said.
   Both companies denied any wrongdoing.
   ``We always have our customers sign a disclaimer waiver that says
they will not use this in any illegal manner,'' Lake Sylvan owner
Bill Donaldson said today. ``If it is used at all, they agree to
notify the cable companies and pay the fees.''
   ``It's not illegal to sell or buy the decoders,'' said B &amp; B
Manager Bill Shultheis. ``It's what people do with them afterwards
that may be illegal _ like a gun. We advertise in about 20
magazines. We have nothing to hide.''
   Cable TV operators have worked with the FBI for several years to
crack down on unauthorized suppliers of such equipment, and similar
raids have been conducted across the nation.
   Of those, Wednesday's haul was the largest, said Jim Allen,
director of the National Cable Television Association's office of
cable signal theft.
</TEXT>
