<DOCNO> AP890817-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WindShear 1stLd-Writethru a0502 08-17 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wind Shear, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radar Helps Three Commercial Pilots Dodge Microburst</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and 9th graf pvs, `The wind ...' to CORRECT that detection
system is not radar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airport system designed to detect dangerous wind
shears helped three jetliners avoid a potentially catastrophic shear
last month, officials said.
   ``You can definitely say the system worked,'' John McCarthy,
director of wind-shear research for the National Center for
Atmospheric Research in Boulder, said Wednesday.
   A wind shear is a sudden change of wind direction that creates a
powerful downburst of air. The gust can be strong enough to drive a
jetliner into the ground when it is landing or taking off.
   Powerful wind shears called microbursts have caused at least five
accidents that claimed more than 500 lives in the last 15 years,
including the l985 crash of a Delta Air Lines L-1011 that killed 137
people near Dallas.
   A microburst recorded at 95 knots, or 109 mph, was detected on
July 8 by Stapleton International Airport's Low-Level Wind Shear
Alert System, officials said. That was about 25 knots faster than
the microburst that downed the Delta jet.
   Three planes were approaching Stapleton when air-traffic
controllers alerted them to the probability of the wind shear,
Federal Aviation Admnistration spokesman Mitch Barker said. The
pilots, whose names and carriers were not identified, took evasive
action.
   ``The absence of the alert to the pilots could have been very
potentially catastrophic,'' McCarthy said.
   The crew of one of the aircraft said the microburst was so strong
that it slowed the jet by approximately 58 mph and caused it to drop
400 feet, to within 600 feet of the ground, McCarthy said.
   The wind shear, which lasted 10 minutes, was detected by a system
using 16 wind gauges spread over the airfield. Winds speed and
direction readings from the devices were automatically relayed to a
computer for analysis.
   Officials have been testing Doppler systems at Stapleton for
their ability to detect wind shear. Last November, the FAA awarded a
$180 million contract to Raytheon Co. to install such systems at 47
major airports across the country, beginning in the early 1990s.
   The Stapleton microburst is the strongest ever measured by a
machine, McCarthy said. But he added, ``We think microbursts can be
a lot stronger than this 95 knotter.''
   Scientists estimate microbursts can be as powerful as 200 knots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
