<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-17 0900</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Townshend of the Who suffered a minor
puncture wound to his right hand while doing his distinctive
windmill guitar strum.
   Townshend hit his hand Wednesday night on his guitar's whammy
bar, a handle that allows the musician to vary the pitch of an
electric guitar, during the song ``Won't Get Fooled Again.''
Townshend grimaced, set his guitar on the ground and walked off the
Tacoma Dome stage.
   The other band members checked up on Townshend, and lead singer
Roger Daltrey announced to the crowd that Townshend had been taken
by ambulance to St. Joseph Hospital in Tacoma.
   He was treated for cuts on his finger and palm and released.
   The group's next concert is scheduled Friday in Vancouver,
British Columbia. Dave Clarke, production coordinator for Perryscope
Productions, which is handling the Who's appearance there, said
Thursday that as far as he knows, that concert is still on.
   Because his hearing has been affected by loud music after years
of touring, Townshend has been playing mostly acoustic guitars on
his current tour.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Robert P. Casey ran into a bit of
trouble a few weekends ago when he tried to buy a fishing license.
He couldn't prove he was a Pennsylvania resident.
   Casey told the tale at a recent builders' convention as a way of
demonstrating that you're never as big a fish as you might think.
The tale was recounted this week by The Philadelphia Inquirer.
   It happened in Hamlin, population 300, in rural Wayne County,
while the governor was taking a few days off at his vacation home at
Lake Ariel. Casey was chauffeured and escorted by a state police
trooper, and wasn't carrying any identification.
   The governor, dressed in shorts and a golf shirt, filled out an
application and handed it to the clerk. Then, according to Casey,
came the following exchange:
   ``She looks at me and says, `Are you a Pennsylvania resident?'''
   ``And I just deadpanned. I said, `Yes, I'm a Pennsylvania
resident.'''
   ``She says, `You got a driver's license?' ''
   ``I said no.''
   ``You got a voter's card?''
   ``No.''
   ``You got the certificate of title to your car?''
   ``No.''
   ``She said, `Where do you live?'''
   ``And I said, `I live in Scranton, I got a place in Lake Ariel
and I'm a Pennsylvania resident.' ''
   Finally, a trooper with Casey came to the governor's rescue and
vouched for him, the newspaper reported. The clerk finally approved
the application, telling the governor, ``I'm going to make an
exception in your case.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Joanne Woodward says she might have been
a bigger star if she hadn't put her marriage to actor Paul Newman
ahead of her career.
   In an interview in Lear's magazine, Ms. Woodward, 59, said she
was raised in Georgia ``to believe that a woman should be both wife
and mistress to her husband, and only in that could she find her
true fulfillment.''
   She married Newman just as her movie career was taking off. ``I
would have liked to be a major star,'' she said. ``If I hadn't been
torn in my desires, I might have attained both'' stardom and a happy
marriage.
   ``But I never felt I had the option,'' she added.
   She said she always ``felt an enormous rivalry with Paul ...
because he was living my fantasy, being what I had always wanted to
be: a star.''
   Ms. Woodward, who has three daughters with Newman, still puts her
marriage ahead of other activities. She's been pursuing a bachelor's
degree at Sarah Lawrence College on and off for 17 years, and failed
to graduate last spring in part because ``Paul was working on a film
down in Louisiana and he asked me to join him because he missed
me,'' she said.
   ``There's no academic degree in this world that can compare in
importance to the fact that the person you've loved for 31 years is
missing you,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Charlie Daniels made a visit here
to support Vietnam War veterans who are staging a vigil in a bamboo
and wire cage to call attention to American soldiers still missing
in southeast Asia.
   Daniels visited the cage outside the city's lakefront War
Memorial Center on Wednesday and led people gathered at the site in
a brief prayer.
   ``I pray for those soldiers who have come back and those who are
still missing,'' Daniels said. ``I ask that proof be gathered and
action be taken to bring them home.''
   Some activists believe that some of the 2,400 Americans listed as
missing in action in Southeast Asia are in fact alive and being held
prisoner. U.S. officials say there is no proof that any of the
missing soldiers are alive, although they don't rule the possibility
out entirely.
   ``There are still people in southeast Asia,'' Daniels said.
``They are fighting men that we have left. It's a disgrace.''
   Members of Wisconsin Vietnam Veterans are taking turns spending
time inside the cage to raise awareness. The vigil began Aug. 10 and
will end 37 days later on National POW-MIA Day on Sept. 15.
   Daniels, known for hits such as ``The Devil Went Down To
Georgia,'' took a few minutes to crawl inside the cage and talk with
a veteran who had been taking part in the vigil.
</TEXT>
