<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1447EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Student'sSupernova     08-17 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student's Supernova,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Undergrad Discovers Exploding Star 806,000,000,000,000,000,000 Miles
Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old engineering student has
discovered a supernova, or exploding star, in a spiral galaxy more
than 137 million light-years from Earth, the California Institute of
Technology announced Thursday.
   Celina Mikolajczak, of San Diego, made the discovery while
examining photographic films taken on the 18-inch Schmidt telescope
at Palomar Observatory, northeast of San Diego.
   Caltech spokesman Robert Finn said Mikolajczak was looking for
comets and asteroids as part of a summer program in which
undergraduates conduct research under faculty supervision.
   ``My first thought was that it was a speck of dust,'' said
Mikolajczak, who then examined more film and realized, ``Wow, I
think I've found something.''
   The discovery was confirmed with the help of Mikolajczak's
faculty sponsor, Eleanor Helin, a planetary scientist at Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, which Caltech operates under contract to NASA.
   The supernova, designated SN 1989N, is the 14th discovered this
year and is much too dim to be seen by the naked eye. It is in the
eastern part of the constellation Leo, within a large spiral galaxy
named NGC 3646 located 137 million light-years _ or 806 quintillion
miles _ from Earth. A light year is equal to the distance light
travels in a year, about 5.88 trillion miles.
   Fifteen to 20 supernovas are discovered during a typical year; 27
were found in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
