<FIRST>u a PM-High-RiseRazing     08-17 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Rise Razing,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newark, N.J., Agrees To Scale Back Plans To Demolish Public Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newark housing authorities today agreed to
scale back drastically the amount of public housing to be demolished
under a slum clearance plan and committed themselves to replacing
the razed apartments.
   The agreement beween the Newark Housing Authority and housing
activists was announced by U.S. District Judge Dickinson R.
Debevoise.
   The agreement provides for the demolition of eight apartment
buildings containing about 1,900 units. To make up for those lost
apartments, 1,500 new apartments will be built and hundreds of
others will be renovated.
   In addition, tenants in buildings being demolished will be given
a place immediately in a new building or a renovated apartment.
   Previously, the housing authority planned to raze 39 buildings
with about 5,700 units in the biggest demolition of public housing
by an American city. The program is aimed at getting rid of what
critics call ``high-rise slums.''
   But opponents of the plan wanted assurances that the demolished
apartments would be replaced.
   Debevoise said that without the settlement, the city would have
lost about $100 million in federal funds previously approved for
replacement housing.
   ``In this case, there is no loser,'' the judge said.
   Many cities have destroyed or plan to demolish some of their
aging high-rise public projects, saying they are unmanageable and
dangerous and should be replaced by townhouses and low-rise
buildings.
   Harris David, an attorney for tenants in a lawsuit against the
Newark plan, said, ``My clients are extremely pleased. They consider
it a substantial victory for poor people and the cause of low-income
housing in the city.''
   The Newark authority, the nation's eighth-largest, controls
13,000 apartments and has a waiting list of 10,000 families. Nearly
40 percent of the apartments are vacant, many awaiting demolition.
More than 800 units have already been razed.
   One-third of the city's more than 300,000 residents receive
public assistance.
   Daniel Blue Jr., executive director of the housing authority,
said the first demolition probably won't begin until 1990.
</TEXT>
