<FIRST>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0609 08-17 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0609,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Defense Minister Reported Detained</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 1 graf to ADD background on students. SUBS
12th graf, ``The sources ...'' with 1 graf to ADD dropped word ``not.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers loyal to China's president detained the
defense minister and several commanders in a dispute over a top
military post vacated by Zhao Ziyang, the purged Communist Party
boss, Chinese sources said Thursday.
   They said President Yang Shangkun, a central figure in the
martial law crackdown on the student-led pro-democracy movement,
apparently ordered the action to strengthen his control of the
Chinese military.
   In Beijing, government spokesman Yuan Mu confirmed reports that
student leader Wang Dan had been arrested and said Zhao, who has not
been seen in public since May 18, was leading a ``completely normal
life.''
   A Shanghai newspaper said authorities arrested or were
investigating 99 people accused of involvement in illegal workers'
groups that plotted to establish a ``people's party'' and kidnap
officials. The Shanghai Liberation Daily said The groups planned to
overthrow the government.
   Staff members of the Guangming Daily, the Communist Party's
leading newspaper for intellectuals, said senior editor Yao Xihua,
61, had been ``asked to retire.''
   He appeared to be the latest victim of a purge in which at least
10 intellectuals have been dismissed from colleges and research
centers and an outspoken columnist for the paper, Dai Qing, was
arrested for supporting pro-democracy protests.
   In the military power struggle, soldiers loyal to Yang went to
the Beijing residence of Defense Minister Qin Jiwei about 6:40 p.m.
Wednesday and took him and one of his armed guards away, the sources
said.
   Other troopers detained the heads of the Beijing, Guangzhou and
Nanjing military districts, who supported Qin and were in Beijing
for an important meeting, they said.
   Control of the military is essential in high-level Chinese
politics. Senior leader Deng Xiaoping's only official post is
chairman of the Central Military Commission, China's top military
body.
   Qin and Yang have been competing to become first vice chairman of
the commission, left vacant by Zhao's dismissal June 24.
   One source said the soldiers were from the Garrison Headquarters
of Beijing, a special force that protects military and political
leaders and is directed by President Yang.
   The sources said they believed Qin and the others went
unwillingly, but did not say they were kidnapped or arrested. They
said they did not know the men's whereabouts.
   No confirmation of the reports was possible, but the sources
contacted The Associated Press separately. One is a military officer
who telephoned Thursday morning from Beijing and the other is a
businessman, based in Hong Kong, who says he has extensive contacts
within the Chinese military.
   Zhao was purged because of he allegedly supported student
demonstrations for sweeping political change in China, which ended
with the bloody military crackdown of June 3-4.
   Chinese sources had said earlier that Qin was against imposing
martial law in Beijing and the use of force to clear Tiananmen
Square.
   According to the sources, Qin and several commanders met with
former Defense Minister Zhang Aiping and Yang Dezhi, former army
chief of staff, on Aug. 8 to discuss Qin's possible appointment to
Zhao's former military post.
   Among the officials accompanying Qin were Zhou Yibing, commander
of the Beijing military area; Xiang Shouzhi, commander of the
Nanjing area, and Zhang Wannian, the Guangzhou commander, they said.
   Zhang Aiping and Yang Dezhi, who opposed a violent crackdown on
the democracy movement in a letter written in late May, expressed
support for Qin, the sources reported.
   The Central Military Commission met the next day to choose a
first vice chairman, but took no action because Qin and Yang argued
and Qin walked out, one of the sources said.
   Both said the meeting was adjourned until this week, but that
Wednesday's developments had placed it in doubt.
   Yuan, the Chinese government spokesman, said Wang, a 20-year-old
Beijing University student who helped lead the pro-democracy
movement, was arrested July 2 after meeting with a Taiwanese
reporter who was detained and later expelled.
   An interview published Wednesday in the Japanese newspaper
Yomiuri quoted him as saying the Communist Party continued
investigating links between the demonstrators and Zhao.
   ``If it is determined that (Zhao) took part in the turmoil or had
a role in planning and leading it, it will cease to be an internal
party matter, but I am not saying it will definitely lead to
criminal proceedings,'' he said.
   Yuan said without elaboration that Zhao and Hu Qili, another
moderate party leader also purged for opposing the army crackdown,
were leading normal lives.
   China will not use force to ``pry'' dissident astrophysicist Fang
and his wife from their refuge in the U.S. Embassy, he said, but
they will not be allowed to leave the country even for a third
``neutral'' nation.
   He said resolution of the diplomatic standoff ``lies with the
U.S. government. ... Whoever started the trouble should end it.''
</TEXT>
