<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSCount     08-17 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Count,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 100,000 AIDS Cases Reported in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS has reached a new milestone in the United
States, with more than 100,000 cases of the deadly disease reported,
according to the federal Centers for Disease Control.
   Through July, 102,621 cases of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome were reported in the United States, the CDC said this week.
A total of 59,391, or 58 percent, of those patients have died.
   As scientists have noted since AIDS was discovered in 1981, the
case count is growing at a faster pace as the disease spreads. The
first 50,000 AIDS cases in the United States were reported from 1981
to late 1987, but the next 50,000 were reported from December 1987
to July 1989.
   U.S. health officials estimate 1 million to 1.5 million Americans
are infected with HIV, or human immunodeficiency virus, which causes
AIDS. A study among homosexual or bisexual males _ the largest risk
group for AIDS _ suggests that up to 99 percent of those infected
will eventually develop the disease.
   AIDS continues to occur increasingly among abusers of injectable
drugs. In the first six months of 1989, 23 percent of reported AIDS
patients were female or heterosexual male users of intravenous
drugs, compared with 18 percent among the cases reported before
1985, the CDC said.
   Fifty-six percent of the cases reported in the first half of this
year were among homosexual or bisexual males, compared with 63
percent prior to 1985.
   Overall, homosexual or bisexual men make up 60 percent of the
102,621 reported AIDS cases. Twenty percent are intravenous drug
abusers, and 7 percent are both. Four percent of AIDS cases are
blamed on heterosexual contact.
   The virus that causes AIDS damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by
drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
