<DOCNO> AP890817-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-AIDS-Drug     08-17 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Drug,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Finds AZT Significantly Helps Some Early-Stage AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is ending part of its trial for
the AIDS drug AZT because the study found it significantly slowed
the progress of the deadly disease in certain patients, the
Department of Health and Human Services announced today.
   AZT, also known as zidovudine, was being given to participants in
the drug trial whose blood tested positive for the AIDS virus but
whose disease progression was in a very early stage.
   Patients in the study were those who had blood tests of fewer
than 500 T4 blood cells per cubic millimeter. Half of those in the
study received AZT and the others received placebo.
   HHS announced that a data and safety monitoring board ``found
that those participants with fewer T4 cells who received zidovudine,
the rate of progression to AIDS or severe ARC (AIDS-related complex)
was roughly half that of participants ... who received placebo.''
   The announcement said that all patients in the trial will now
receive AZT. The study continues for patients whose T4 cell count is
above 500.
   The drug trial involved more than 3,200 volunteers. The trial was
begun two years ago and was conducted in 32 locations. The
announcement follows by two weeks a report that shows AZT slowed
progression of the disease in persons with early AIDS-related
complex.
   About 1,300 of the participants had fewer than 500 T4 cells at
the beginning.
   ``These results provide real hope for the millions of people
worldwide who are infected'' with the AIDS virus, HHS Secretary
Lewis W. Sullivan said in prepared remarks.
   Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, director of the National Institute of
Allergy and Infectious Diseases which was in charge of the study,
said the results have ``clearly demonstrated that early treatment
with zidovudine can slow disease progression without significant
side effects (in AIDS patients) with fewer than 500 T4 cells who do
not yet have symptoms.''
   AZT is currently the only anti-viral drug approved to combat
AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
