<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Trip     08-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Trip,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Will Find Rapidly Changing Spain on Third Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will make his third trip
in seven years this weekend to Spain, a former bastion of Roman
Catholicism that is becoming increasingly secular.
   Some observers say the visit to the northwestern cities of
Santiago de Compostela, Oviedo and the Covadonga mountain shrine _
all important sites of early Christian Spain _ is an effort to stem
the secularization and a dramatic decline in church attendance.
   A limited abortion law and another giving the state effective
control over religious schools, both passed by the Socialist
government of Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, took effect in 1985
after the pope's 10-day trip in 1982 and a shorter visit to the
Virgin of Pilar shrine in Zaragoza in 1984.
   Divorce was made legal in 1981, six years after the death of
dictator Francisco Franco, under whose regime Roman Catholicism was
the state religion and the church the arbiter of public and private
morality.
   In July, the Justice Ministry declared Islam, under whose banner
Moorish warriors destroyed Santiago de Compostela in 997, a religion
of ``recognized foothold'' in Spain, making Moslem establishments
eligible for tax-exempt status. Similar decrees already had been
issued for Protestants and Jews.
   The highlight of John Paul's trip will be the fourth
Vatican-sponsored World Youth Day, expected to attract 300,000 young
people from 60 countries to Santiago on Saturday, when the three-day
visit begins.
   Monsignor Peter Coughlan, undersecretary of the Vatican's Council
for the Laity, said the purpose was to demonstrate church's emphasis
on youth and evangelization. His agency organized the event.
   Polls indicate half the Spaniards under age 25 believe in God.
Polls in the archbishopric of Oviedo, which the pope will visit
Sunday, say 22 percent of those aged 18-30 call themselves
practicing Catholics.
   A study by the archbishop's office said only 17.6 percent of the
1.1 million inhabitants of Asturias, of which Oviedo is the capital,
considered themselves active church members.
   Advance press coverage has focused on the financing of the visit
and the use of public funds to pay for the estimated 5,000 police
needed to keep order and guard John Paul.
   Although the visit is not official, the pontiff will meet with
both King Juan Carlos and Gonzalez, the prime minister.
   Cardinal Angel Suquia, archbishop of Madrid and head of Spanish
Conference of Bishops, acknowledged problems with ``who is to pay
what for what.''
   The bishops have not said what the papal visit will cost, but
Gabino Diaz Merchan, archbishop of Oviedo, told the state radio the
church was spending $300,000 on the visit to his diocese.
   Nueva Espana, an Oviego daily, said the Asturias government
contributed part of the $165,000 needed to refurbish the Covadonga
shrine.
   Cavadonga, in the Picos de Europa mountain range 50 miles
southeast of Oviedo, houses the 18th century statue of the Virgin of
the Battlefield or ``Santina,'' patron of Asturias.
   Galicia, of which Santiago is the capital, is providing $1.65
million to help pay for the visit and accommodations for the young
visitors, said David Cheda, provincial government spokesman.
   He said the government hoped to recover 40 percent of it from
fees to food and soft drink concessionaires.
   Archbishop Antonio Maria Rouco Varela of Santiago said John
Paul's visit was ``of decisive importance for the church,'' but did
not say how much his archbishopric was spending on it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
