<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     08-17 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistanis Mourn Zia, Protest Bhutto, on Anniversary of Zia's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Pakistanis
marched for miles Thursday to Faisal Mosque to mourn President Mohqa
laid down his life for Pakistan'' fluttered from light poles along
the avenue leading to the huge mosque.
   Vendors hawked Zia posters, along with ice cream.
   Zia ruled Pakistan for 11 years, eight of them under martial law.
His death in a mysterious plane crash Aug. 17, 1988, paved the way
for the country's first free elections in more than a decade.
   Ms. Benazir Bhutto's party won control of the National Assembly
in the November vote.
   Organizers had said the first anniversary of Zia's death would be
used as a rally to show the strength of those opposed to Ms. Bhutto,
the prime minister. Pakistani TV estimated the crowd Thursday at
70,000 and said it biggest anti-Bhutto showing ever.
   ``It was a referendum in our favor,'' said Ms. Bhutto's main
rival, Nawaz Sharif, who heads a nine-party conservative alliance
that controls Punjab, Pakistan's largest province.
   Zia's son, Ijaz ul-Haq, led a late afternoon prayer service at
Zia's marble sarcophagus, shaded under a gazebo on the mosque's lawn.
   ``It was a religious service but it was also an approval of the
policies of my father,'' Ijaz, 38, said.
   Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others died in the
crash of Zia's presidential plane. Investigators said it appeared to
be sabotage but they did not say who was responsible.
   Ijaz claims Ms. Bhutto was behind the crash and that her Pakistan
People's Party is trying to cover it up.
   Many Pakistani observers believe Zia's death was the work of
foreign agents. Pakistani officials have blamed hundreds of
terrorist bombings in Pakistan on Soviet-trained agents of
neighboring Afghanistan's communist government. Zia was a staunch
supporter of Afghan rebels fighting to topple it.
   Hundreds of policemen and federal officers were called into
Islamabad, the Pakistani capital, to keep order for Thursday's
rally, but there were no reports of violence.
   The government appealed to Ms. Bhutto's supporters not to hold
counter-rallies that might provoke violence.
</TEXT>
