<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0642 08-17 1054</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0642,1080</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT ^President Agrees to Let Solidarity Lead, Lawmakers Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs 4th graf ``I am ...'' with analytical background
on what power communist party will still hold, Soviets.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski will choose a
Solidarity member to lead Poland's next government, a lawmaker said
Thursday, a move that would end four decades of Communist domination.
   The stunning development came during a historic meeting between
Jaruzelski and Lech Walesa, whose Solidarity labor movement was
crushed by Jaruzelski eight years ago but which has now become
Poland's most potent political force.
   Solidarity lawmaker Jacek Kuron said Jaruzelski accepted ``in
principle'' Walesa's offer to form a government led by
non-Communists. Such a government would be unprecedented in the
Soviet bloc.
   ``I am satisfied,'' Walesa said after the meeting.
   Even in a government led by Solidarity, however, Jaruzelski would
remain president, controlling the army and foreign affairs; local
governments would still be in the hands of the Communist Party; and
party members would still control the courts. In addition, tens of
thousands of Poland's bureaucrats owe their jobs to the party, and
75 percent of management jobs _ ranging from shop managers to
factory heads _ are held by party members.
   The possibility of a non-communist government in Warsaw has
alarmed the Soviet Union, Poland's superpower neighbor and ally, but
the Soviets have always stressed that political changes in Poland
were an internal affair. In addition, Walesa has said that the
interior and defense ministries would remain in communist hands.
   After the meeting between Walesa and Jaruzelski, state-run media
announced that Communist Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak formally
turned in his resignation to Jaruzelski, apparently as a prelude to
the formation of a new government.
   Kiszczak, who has been in office only since Aug. 2, had said
earlier this week he would resign because the Solidarity-led
opposition in parliament fought his efforts to form a coalition
government.
   Walesa, a Gdansk shipyard electrician who built his labor
movement as Poland slid into an economic morass, has said he does
not want to become prime minister.
   Jaruzelski, as president, must nominate a prime minister and
present him for approval to the Sejm, the lower house of the
National Assembly. Solidarity and two minor parties that are allied
with it form a majority in that chamber.
   Kuron said he is among three Solidarity candidates the coalition
has offered for prime minister. Kuron, a activist in the Polish
opposition for more than 20 years, spent nine years in prison for
anti-government activities.
   Also to be considered are Solidarity parliamentary leader
Bronislaw Geremek, a historian; and Tadeusz Mazowiecki, editor of
the union's weekly newspaper Tygodnik Solidarnosc.
   Jaruzelski ``said he will grant nomination (as prime minister) to
one of the Solidarity candidates in the nearest future,'' Kuron told
a gathering of Solidarity lawmakers.
   Walesa has said any Solidarity-led government would appoint
Communist Party members to lead the ministries of defense and
interior, which control the army and police. This appeared to be a
move to allay Soviet fears about a fissure in the Warsaw Pact
military alliance.
   Solidarity was the East bloc's first independent trade union when
it was formed in 1980 by Walesa.
   It was legal for 16 months and its membership ballooned to 10
million until Dec. 13, 1981, when Jaruzelski declared martial law
and jailed thousands of members, including Walesa. Solidarity was
outlawed the following year.
   A series of strikes caused by Poland's collapsing economy last
year forced officials to seek a conciliation with the union,
resulting in a historic accord reached in April that allowed limited
opposition participation in elections and the legalization of
Solidarity.
   The trade union and its allied candidates dominated the elections
in the Sejm and the newly formed Senate. Under the accord, the
Communists were guaranteed a narrow majority in the National
Assembly.
   But the defection this week of two minor parties typically
associated with the Communists, the United Peasant and the
Democratic parties, swung the balance of power to Solidarity.
   Jaruzelski was to make an announcement on the meeting Friday and
both government and opposition figures were vague on details.
   Jaruzelski, agreed to the basic concept of the plan, said Jerzy
Jozwiak, leader of the Solidarity-allied Democratic Party who
attended the meeting. ``The concept has been approved by the
president,'' he said.
   An official communique issued after the meeting said Jaruzelski
would work for the ``quickest possible appointment'' of a government
such as proposed by Walesa.
   ``Lech Walesa presented the concept of establishing a coalition
government of national responsibility with the participation of all
pro-reformatory political forces represented at the Sejm,'' said the
communique carried on the state PAP news agency.
   ``Jaruzelski ... declared that he will urgently consider the
presented propositions and conduct appropriate consultations aiming
at the quickest possible appointment of such a government in the
interest of the nation,'' it said.
   Walesa and Jozwiak expressed satisfaction with the outcome but
were vague about details, apparently not wishing to speak until
Jaruzelski issued his written decision Friday.
   Jozwiak said the outcome was ``favorable for the nation and the
state.''
   After the meeting, Walesa went to see the leader of Poland's
Roman Catholic Church, Cardinal Jozef Glemp.
   Asked if the coalition leaders were close to a new government, he
added ``closer than farther.''
   Asked if the president favored a government such as the coalition
had suggested, Walesa replied: ``What Poland needs is agreement, a
government of reforms. Everybody is in favor of that. So it is only
a technical matter.''
   President Bush was monitoring the developments in Poland and the
White House said the ``sensitive situation'' was a positive
development.
   ``We do encourage and support the process of pluralism, and it
appears that is the general direction that they are aimed,'' in
Poland, Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater told reporters who
accompanied the president to Maine.
   ``Certainly a non-Communist government would be a remarkable and
history-making occurrence,'' he added.
   There was no immediate comment from the Soviet Union. The Soviet
TV news program ``Vremya'' on Thursday night showed a report that
had been shot before the meeting with Jaruzelski, painting a picture
of constant strikes, chronic food shortages and political turmoil.
An announcer read a dispatch saying Walesa had offered to form a
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
