<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   08-17 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>June Trade Deficit Drop Fails to Impress Economists</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETANSMITTING a0655, a0632, a0622 to restore lost material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit shrank to $8.17 billion
in June, the smallest monthly imbalance since December 1984, the
government said Thursday in a report viewed by many economists as
only a short-lived improvement.
   The Commerce Department said the June deficit showed a dramatic
18.9 percent narrowing from a revised May figure of $10.08 billion,
reflecting record U.S. export sales and a drop in imports.
   The June report, which was significantly better than had been
expected, was hailed by the Bush administration as evidence that
American manufacturers were enjoying continued success in
penetrating foreign markets.
   ``The decline (in the trade deficit) was greater than market
expectation and certainly is good news for the country,''
presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told reporters in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   The June improvement came from a 1.5 percent increase in U.S.
exports, which pushed them to a record level of $30.91 billion, and
a 3.6 percent drop in imports, which fell to $39.08 billion.
   Private forecasters were decidedly less enthusiastic than the
administration, with some contending that the June deficit figure
was likely to be the best trade news America would get for some time.
   They predicted that the deficit would widen in coming months
under the impact of a stronger dollar, which makes U.S. products
more expensive on overseas markets.
   The stock and bond markets also reacted negatively to the report,
which was interpreted as showing that economic growth was stronger
than previously believed. While such a development eases recession
fears, it also diminishes hopes that the Federal Reserve will move
to lower interest rates further.
   Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said the
unexpectedly sharp improvement in the June trade figure and other
recent good economic news would probably result in a big upward
revision in the government's estimate of overall economic growth for
the April-June quarter.
   The overall economy, as measured by the gross national product,
was originally shown growing at a very weak 1.7 percent annual rate
in the second quarter. Steinberg said that figure would likely be
revised upward to around 2.5 percent, reflecting not only better
news on trade but also upturns in industrial production and retail
sales.
   ``During the period when the Fed was easing monetary policy in
the second quarter, the economy was not nearly as weak as the
central bank thought it was,'' he said.
   For the first six months of the year, the trade deficit was
running at an annual rate of $108.6 billion, down 8.4 percent from
last year's total merchandise trade deficit of $118.5 billion.
   But many economists believe the monthly deficits will begin
creeping upward for the rest of the year, reflecting both the
stronger dollar and a growing appetite for foreign oil.
   The American Petroleum Institute reported Wednesday that imported
crude and refined oil accounted for more than half the country's
total oil use in July, the first time that has occurred in 12 years.
   ``The June trade report is a good report, but you can't jump to
the conclusion that the trade deficit is on a downward trend,'' said
Cynthia Latta, an economist at DRI-McGraw Hill.
   She predicted that the overall deficit would show only a small
improvement this year, perhaps declining to $110 billion, while
Michael Evans, head of a Washington forecasting firm, said he was
looking for no improvement at all in the trade deficit for 1989 as a
whole.
   The improvement in exports was led by a jump in sales of U.S.
capital goods overseas. The import decline was widespread,
reflecting lower shipments of foreign autos, capital goods and oil.
   America's foreign oil bill dropped 11.5 percent in June to $4.2
billion as both the volume and price of imported oil fell. However,
analysts, noting the American Petroleum Institute report for July,
said oil imports would likely be rising for the rest of the year.
   As usual, the largest trade deficit in June was with Japan, an
imbalance of $3.9 billion, down from a May deficit of $4.3 billion.
The deficit with Taiwan totaled $1.2 billion in June, while the
deficit with China was $700 million.
   The total June deficit of $8.17 billion was the lowest since a
$6.79 billion deficit in December 1984.
</TEXT>
