<FIRST>u w AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0618 08-17 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0670 to restory dropped matter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Deficit Climbing, Climbing, CBO Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 10th graf, Assuming Congress, to show $24 billion sted
$14 billion in cuts would be necessary; SUBS 12th graf, Deficit reduction,
to change deadline to Oct. 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal deficit is on a path leading to
$128 billion of red ink in 1993 _ when the law requires the budget
to be in balance _ the Congressional Budget Office said Thursday.
   In the short run, even if Congress fully implements an agreement
worked out with the White House, the deficit will be $118 billion in
1990, or $18 billion above the target set by the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law, CBO projected.
   And for budget year 1991, which begins in less than 14 months, a
$127 billion deficit, $63 billion above the figure allowed by law,
was forecast.
   ``Clearly, this implies Congress and the administration are going
to face a very difficult challenge in fiscal year 1991,'' CBO
Director Robert S. Reischauer told a news conference. Cutting the
1991 deficit to the target level would require a deficit-reduction
effort more than twice as large as any previous plan, he said.
   ``The key message is that we have a very long way to go if the
deficit is to be brought down to a level Americans will be
comfortable with,'' Reischauer said.
   The CBO figures indicate a deficit each year that would be large
enough to force across-the-board spending cuts in most federal
programs, as required by the Gramm-Rudman law. However, it is
forecasts from the White House Office of Management and Budget that
determine whether those reductions will be made _ and the OMB is
expected to project deficits low enough to avoid the mandated
spending cuts.
   OMB forecasts will be made public Monday.
   Reischauer made his comments as CBO issued a five-year economic
forecast of continued slow growth, gradually declining short-term
interest rates, inflation in the 4.6 percent range and a slight
increase in unemployment.
   CBO's economic forecasts are less optimistic than those of OMB,
which accounts for a big share of the difference between the two
agencies' outlook for the deficit.
   Assuming Congress fully implements the deficit-cutting plan
worked out with the administration, and if one-time-only collections
from selling government assets are not counted, Reischauer said, the
CBO figures indicate a 1990 deficit of $124 billion, or $24 billion
above the Gramm-Rudman maximum. Such a shortfall would result in $24
billion in spending cuts, divided evenly between defense and
domestic programs.
   However, the administration projection is likely to show a $105
billion deficit, which would be $5 billion below the level that
would trigger automatic spending cuts, Reischauer said.
   Deficit reduction will be a major issue when Congress returns to
Washington after the August recess. Lawmakers face an Oct. 15
deadline _ two weeks after the start of budget year 1990 _ for
completing work to implement the deficit-cutting agreement with the
White House.
   The major proposal under consideration would cut the deficit by
about $13 billion by reducing spending and raising new revenues.
Almost $9 billion of the $24-billion package of deficit reduction
for 1990 would come from accounting changes and one-time
collections, including asset sales.
   Deficit reduction, Reischauer said, ``is a political problem as
much as it is an economic problem. The American people have to send
a message to their legislators.''
   That message, he added, should indicate a willingness to accept
some short-term pain as the price for long-term improvement in the
government's budget policies.
   Continued high deficits could lower the nation's standard of
living, reduce the government's ability to influence the economy,
and boost international interest rates, which would drain resources
from poorer countries, Reischauer said.
   Asked if the deficit can be cut significantly without raising
taxes, Reischauer replied, ``The more programs and policies that are
under consideration, the easier it will be to craft a
deficit-reduction package.''
   CBO estimates this year's deficit at $161 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
