<FIRST>u w AM-Borders-Hastings     08-17 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Borders-Hastings,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0626 AM-Borders-Hastings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Witness to Testify in Senate Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday ordered former
Washington lawyer William Borders to testify in the Senate
impeachment trial of U.S. District Court Judge Alcee Hastings.
   U.S. District Court Judge George Revercomb said Borders must
respond to questions from the Senate panel considering the Hastings
matter or face a possible contempt of court order which could send
the prominent onetime lawyer to jail.
   Revercomb said a June 27 immunity order by U.S. District Court
Judge Louis Oberdorfer was proper and that ``sanctions would be
imposed'' if it is violated.
   ``You must testify'' before the Senate Impeachment Trial
Committee or show cause why he should not be held in contempt,
Revercomb told Borders, who served nearly three years in prison for
his conviction in a bribe conspiracy allegedly involving Hastings.
   Senate legal counsel Michael Davidson said he would check to
determine how soon a committee meeting can be scheduled so that
Borders can be called.
   Borders was subpoenaed to testify before the Senate panel, but
twice refused to answer questions, on July 24 and July 27.
   Hastings and his close friend Borders were charged in 1981 with
conspiring to accept a $150,000 bribe in exchange for agreeding to
reduce the sentences of two convicted criminals to probation and
returning nearly $1 million in forfeited property.
   Borders was convicted while Hastings was acquitted in a separate
trial.
   The House voted a year ago to impeach Hastings for bribery and
perjury in connection with the case in which he was acquitted and
also for allegedly leaking confidential wiretap information in a
separate case.
   Borders' attorney, Michael Rosier, argued against ordering his
client to testify. Rosier said in court papers filed earlier this
week that the court-authorized grant of immunity to Borders was
defective.
   Rosier said the Senate trial committee failed to notify the
attorney general at least 10 days in advance of the panel's
intention to seek court-authorized immunity for Borders. Rosier also
raised constitutional concerns, saying that forcing him to testify
amounted to cruel and unusual punishment.
   Borders ``has paid his debt to society'' by serving nearly three
years in federal prison for conspiring to bribe Hastings, said the
court papers. ``The conduct of the government in its constant
efforts to force Mr. Borders' testimony has now reached the level
that it shocks the conscience and violates fundamental principles of
fairness, justice and decency.''
   Borders ``has the right to be free from the constant threat of
incarceration,'' his lawyers said.
   Revercomb said that under the immunity order, Borders ``always
has a right to relieve himself of incarceration'' by testifying to
the Senate.
</TEXT>
