<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1739EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     08-17 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Accuses U.S. Of Supplying New Rockets To Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan claimed Thursday that the
United States was supplying the anti-communist guerrillas with new
rockets that explode in the air and shower warheads, which detonate
on the ground.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said reporters on
Friday would be shown pieces of the rockets, which he did not name
but said had U.S. markings.
   The United States has said it is providing the guerrillas with
new weapons to counter arms shipments to the Afghan government from
the Soviet Union. Published reports say these include cluster bombs
and Spanish 120mm mortars, designed to crater airport runways.
   ``It is a long-range, U.S.-type missile, it's very strong and it
can destroy vast areas,'' Amani said. ``You can see the U.S.
markings.''
   He said the guerrillas fired 53 missiles, including the
previously unused rockets, at Kabul late Tuesday and early Wednesday.
   One of the new rockets killed five civilians and injured 23
others in the former Soviet-occupied Mikrorayan housing complex near
Kabul airport, now home to many government workers, Amani said. One
of the victims was a child who picked up a piece of rocket that then
exploded, he said.
   He said casualties were low because the attack was at night and
most people were asleep.
   ``But I can assure you that if they continue firing these new
rockets, the people will suffer casualties and their hatred against
the opponent groups and the United States of America will
increase,'' Amani said.
   Explaining how the new rocket worked, Amani said it exploded at
some point in the air, and its 30 warheads then exploded on the
ground.
   ``Even its pieces have exploded sometimes after one hour without
being touched,'' he said.
   The government has said that in the last four weeks, 354 rockets
hit Kabul, killing 193 civilians and injuring more than 500.
   Most of the rockets fired at Kabul are Egyptian-made Sakers, with
a range of up to 25 miles.
   The guerrillas have claimed responsibility for some attacks but
not those in recent days. They claim the government aims rockets at
civilian targets to discredit them.
   The United States and the Soviet Union have accused each other of
escalating the arms race in the 11-year Afghan war since Soviet
troops pulled out in February.
   Last week, the U.S. government said the Soviets were supplying
Afghanistan with MiG-29 fighters and the latest Su-27 ground attack
jets to be used in the event of a Pakistani attack.
   The Afghan government has confounded Western predictions of a
quick guerrilla victory after the Soviet pullout. The army has
repulsed guerrilla attacks on several major provincial cities,
including towns near the border with Pakistan such as Jalalabad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
