<DOCNO> AP890817-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1746EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pakistan-Plane     08-17 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Plane,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crash That Killed Pakistan's President Still a Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year later, mystery still surrounds
the plane crash that killed President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, U.S.
Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 other people on Aug. 17, 1988.
   U.S. And Pakistani investigators all but ruled out technical
failure on the presidential plane, a sturdy, four-engine Lockheed
C-130 turboprop known as Pak One.
   Their report said the ``most probable cause was a criminal act or
sabotage,'' but did not say by whom. Gen. Zia's son speaks of a
coverup.
   The plane climbed into a clear sky over the Sutlej River near the
Indian border, behaved erratically three minutes later, then dived
into a sandy plain and exploded, killing everyone aboard.
   In addition to Zia and Raphel, the dead included the U.S.
military attache and most of Zia's top military officers.
   Some Pakistanis believe it was an assassination by domestic
political enemies Zia accumulated during 11 years of military rule.
Others prefer a foreign motive.
   Investigators said the explosion and fire obliterated most clues
but they found residues of chemicals that could, if combined, be
used in a detonator.
   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, president of the Senate, assumed the
presidency and declared Zia a martyr, bolstering the belief that the
general was murdered.
   Zia's death opened the way, three months later, for the first
free elections in more than a decade. The opposition Pakistan
People's Party won and its leader, Benazir Bhutto, became the first
woman prime minister in the Islamic world.
   The U.S.-Pakistani investigation report, parts of which were made
public, said the plane could have been put out of control by
``mechanical or deliberate'' interference with the flight control
system, interference with cockpit controls, disabling of the pilots
or ``explosive devices used'' to achieve one of those results.
   A popular theory holds that the six crew members were knocked out
by traceless nerve gas, possibly by someone aboard. Another says a
small explosive device damaged some critical part of the flight
control system.
   Suspicion fell on four groups:
   _Agents of Afghanistan's communist government, possibly trained
by the Soviet KGB secret police. Zia, with U.S. support, was a
staunch supporter of Moslem guerrillas in the neighboring country.
   _Domestic political foes, especially those loyal to Ms. Bhutto.
Zia overthrew her father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a 1977 military
coup and he was hanged two years later.
   _Pakistan's minority Shiite Moslems, because of the assassination
of their spiritual leader a month earlier.
   _Agents of India. The two nations have fought three wars since
1947, when the subcontinent was divided and they became independent
of Britain.
   Zia's son, Ijaz ul-Haq, said he believed the Bhutto family was
involved and the new government was covering up.
   ``I am certain that Al-Zulfikar had a hand in it,'' Ijaz, 38,
said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``I have evidence,
but if I made it public now, I'd be eliminated.''
   His reference was to an organization named for the prime
minister's father and once run by Benazir's brother Murtaza, who
lives in Syria.
   Murtaza and another brother, now deceased, planned a Pakistan
Airlines hijacking in 1981 that forced Zia to release 52 political
prisoners. The hijackers killed a passenger they claimed had
betrayed Bhutto while serving under him.
   Benazir Bhutto has said her brother must face charges of air
piracy if he returns to Pakistan.
   An Al-Zulfikar member in London claimed responsibility for the
Pak One crash, but later recanted. The Bhutto family and officials
of the governing party have denied any involvement or coverup.
   The U.S.-Pakistani report recommended a separate investigation of
possible criminal acts. President Ishaq Khan appointed F.K. Bandial,
a career civil servant with few political connections, to conduct it.
   No findings have been published. When asked by The Associated
Press, Bandial would not say how many people were involved or
whether they had made progress.
   ``The investigation is still in hand,'' he said. ``Whatever we
send to the government will be private.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
