<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Hostages     08-17 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Hostages,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Obeid Believes Israeli Prisoners Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials confirmed Thursday that Sheik Abdul
Karim Obeid, the Shiite Moslem cleric kidnapped by Israel, told
interrogators he believed two of the three Israeli soldiers taken
prisoner in Lebanon were dead.
   It was the first Israeli confirmation of a report of the
soldier's deaths in The Sunday Times of London.
   Officials also said, however, that Obeid's belief was based on
second-hand information and they seriously doubted its reliability.
   Israel's policy is that soldiers are considered alive until there
is proof of their deaths. Officials said they would investigate the
source of the leak to the London paper.
   Commandos abducted Obeid from his home in south Lebanon on July
28. Israel has offered to trade him and hundreds of other Lebanese
Shiites it holds for the three Israelis and all 16 Western hostages
in Lebanon, who include eight Americans.
   Obeid is affiliated with Hezbollah, or Party of God, the
pro-Iranian group thought to sponsor hostage-takers.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the soldiers' families were
told last week about what the captive said, and ``knew this
information from Obeid's interrogation before the leak,'' Israel
Television reported.
   A senior Defense Ministry official, apeaking on condition of
anonymity, said Obeid told investigators he ``heard from somebody''
that soldiers Yossi Fink and Rahamim Alsheik died after Shiite
extremists captured them in February 1986.
   The Sunday Times said Israeli officials considered Obeid's
statements accurate.
   ``That is not true,'' Fink's father, Mordechai, said in a
telephone interview. He said he was in constant touch with military
officials, who told him they had ``no substantial information
whatsoever'' on his son's fate.
   He confirmed the families were told last week about Obeid's
comment.
</TEXT>
