<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1903EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DEAArrest     08-17 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DEA Arrest,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Agency Checking Agent's Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Drug Enforcement Administration is
investigating whether an agent arrested in Boston while allegedly
attempting to deliver cocaine revealed any information on DEA
operations to drug traffickers, a spokesman said Thursday.
   ``There is an internal security investigation going on,''
concerning agent Edward K. O'Brien, 44, said spokesman Frank Shults,
who declined to reveal details of the probe.
   O'Brien, an 18-year veteran of the agency, was arrested late
Monday at Boston's Logan International Airport while allegedly
delivering suitcases filled with 62 pounds of cocaine to informants,
authorities said.
   A bail hearing scheduled for Thursday before a U.S. magistrate
was postponed until Aug. 24.
   Shults rejected as having ``no factual basis'' a published report
that during the investigation of O'Brien by the DEA's Office of
Professional Responsibility, allegations surfaced linking O'Brien to
a major Miami-to-Boston cocaine-distribution ring that allegedly
remains the target of an independent DEA probe.
   ``There is no DEA investigation of such a ring,'' Shults said.
While the DEA is probing many East Coast drug-trafficking rings, he
said, none was ``known to be associated with Mr. O'Brien.''
   Asked whether the agency were checking all of its ongoing probes
to see if there might be some connection to O'Brien, he said, ``That
gets back to our internal investigation.''
   Shults denied that, in order to protect an agency investigation
of the drug ring, he was attempting to debunk an article in
Thursday's Washington Post.
   He noted that O'Brien was arrested in connection with a sting
operation: ``It was a controlled delivery arranged by the DEA in
Miami to somebody in Boston, arranged and controlled by DEA at both
ends,'' Shults said.
   O'Brien faces charges of possession with intent to distribute
more than five kilograms (11 pounds) of cocaine, and if convicted
could be sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined up to $4 million.
   O'Brien received $14,000 to transport the drugs and was expecting
to receive another $14,000 in Boston, said DEA Special Agent John J.
Coleman in Boston. Last month, Coleman said, DEA watched as O'Brien
obtained about 55 pounds of cocaine and sham cocaine and brought it
to Boston for $25,000.
   The internal DEA investigation, an administration source said,
may involve a check of the agency's computer indexing system to see
if O'Brien used it to get information on drug investigations in
which he was not involved.
   From May 1988 until last month, O'Brien was a staff coordinator
within the international programs office overseeing DEA operations
in Europe and the Middle East. He was assigned last month to prepare
a drug law enforcement museum for the DEA's new headquarters. From
1982 to 1988, he was agent-in-charge in Springfield, Mass.
   Coleman said Tuesday that O'Brien was in charge of many
successful DEA sting operations and that they had worked together in
southern France trying to uncover heroin labs in the 1970s. ``Those
were the hotbeds of activity in the French Connection days,'' he
said.
   The French Connection was the title of a 1971 movie about the
operation.
   O'Brien received a special citation from Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis in 1984 for supervising the crackdown on a major
cocaine ring in western Massachusetts. He also had received several
DEA commendations.
   Tom Cash, special agent in charge of the Miami office, told The
Associated Press after the arrests of three DEA agents in Miami this
spring, ``It's not the average special agent who is involved in
these types of incidents _ it's the very best.'' After a while, he
said, such agents believe they know the system and can beat it.
</TEXT>
