<DOCNO> AP890817-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EPA-Toxics     08-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EPA-Toxics,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group accused the
Environmental Protection Agency on Thursday of contributing to
increased air pollution by promoting the burning of toxic wastes.
   The EPA issued a statement saying the group ``seriously
distorts'' the agency's role in the disposal of such wastes and that
its primary goal is to promote waste reduction, not a particular
method of disposal or treatment.
   The National Toxics Campaign Fund, a private organization that
focuses on toxic pollution issues, told a news conference outside
the agency's headquarters EPA's policies will ``encourage more toxic
waste production.''
   The group argued that the EPA does not focus enough in getting
companies and industrial plants to invest in technology that would
reduce toxic emissions.
   Instead, the critics maintained, agency policy requires state and
local officials to develop new toxic disposal facilities such as
additional landfills or incinerators.
   ``New disposal capacity will only encourage toxic waste
production,'' said the group. It said putting such wastes in
landfills risks pollution through leakage and the burning toxic
wastes results in the release of ``massive quanities of toxic fumes
and carcinogenic compunds'' into the air.
   ``The only thing we're prompting is waste reduction,'' said EPA
spokeswoman Robin Woods. ``We're encouraging (states) to consider
all waste reduction opportunities. Secondly we're looking at them to
look at existing (disposal) facilities out of state. And as a last
resort build new facilities.''
   She said that the EPA requires strict emission controls when
toxic wastes are burned.
   Congress has directed states to certify by next October to the
EPA that they have enough toxic waste disposal capacity to manage
wastes generated over the next 20 years.
   Ms. Woods said the EPA has yet to receive any of the state toxic
waste disposal plans that are due Oct. 17 and that she could not say
to what extent states intend to rely on incineration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1932EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Walesa'sDay     08-17 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa's Day,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Busy Day for Lech Walesa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a busy day for the stocky man in the
graying mustache and patron saint's pin. Lech Walesa, shipyard
worker and Nobel Peace Prize winner, was trying to form the first
non-Communist government in the Soviet bloc.
   The Solidarity and Black Madonna badges were prominent on his
lapel, as always, when Walesa emerged from the Europejski Hotel
shortly before 9 a.m. Thursday, wearing a natty plaid jacket.
   He stepped into a dented dull-gray Polonez car flying a
Solidarity flag and his driver sped away, with a convoy of camera
crews and journalists in pursuit.
   His first stop was the headquarters of the small United Peasant
Party, where Walesa hoped to enlist party leader Roman Malinowski in
a coalition.
   ``This is something really new for us,'' the switchboard operator
said as Walesa strode in. The party was allied with the Communists
for years, but has become more independent.
   An hour later, Walesa came out beaming, with an agreeable
Malinowski in tow.
   The Polonez, just as dull and dented despite its occupant's
political success, negotiated congested streets to the headquarters
of the Democratic Party, another small group with a history similar
to the United Peasants.
   Less than an hour later, party leader Jerzy Jozwiak had agreed to
join the coalition.
   Another Walesa grin for the cameras, into the Polonez and back to
the hotel.
   Just after noon, Walesa was off again, to a palace in a wooded
park near the Vistula River to seal the deal with Solidarity's
coalition partners.
   A guard slammed the door and reporters took shelter under the
trees from the hot sun.
   Another hour and another picture, this time of the three men,
with Walesa in the middle raising the hands of his new partners high.
   ``I don't have to say anything,'' he said. ``This picture says it
all. Now to work.''
   Lunch in the cavernous hotel dining room drew a crowd. It became
a working meal with Bronislaw Geremek, leader of Solidarity's
parliamentary delegation, and Andrzej Stelmachowski, marshal of the
Senate.
   Walesa had been open and talkative all morning, but the mood
changed when he left for Belvedere Palace, the official residence of
President Wojciech Jaruzelski, to present his proposal for a
coalition government.
   Two soldiers guarded the entrance as Walesa, Malinowski and
Jozwiak arrived in separate cars at 3 p.m.
   An hour went by, then a familiar red Peugeot with only a driver
turned into the palace drive.
   ``Kiszczak,'' the reporters said. Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, the
prime minister elected by Parliament, had arrived.
   After another hour, the meeting ended. Walesa assessed the
meeting, through the glass of a car window, with the single word
``Good.''
   Back at the hotel, dozens of reporters followed him to his room,
hoping for news of his encounter with the stolid general in dark
glasses, whose declaration of martial law in December 1981 sent
Solidarity into eight years of limbo.
   Resolute and brief, Walesa said Jaruzelski favored the coalition
concept and that Kiszczak had resigned. He pushed his way into the
room and closed the door.
   Less than an hour later, the drab, faithful Polonez took Walesa
to Parliament for a meeting of senators and deputies elected with
Solidarity backing in June's partially free elections.
   Once more to the hotel, then to the residence of Cardinal Jozef
Glemp, the Roman Catholic primate of Poland.
   There was no rush here for the devout man who so often seeks
advice from Pope John Paul II, a fellow Pole.
   He spent an hour with the cardinal, and a reporter asked when he
came out: ``What next?''
   ``Sleep,'' Walesa replied, ending a day no one dreamed when he
vaulted the Lenin Shipyard's fence in Gdansk nine years ago to lead
the strike in which Solidarity was born.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
