<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Contras     08-17 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Contras,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Reconnaissance Mission To Visit Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations will send a team to
Central America to prepare for a U.N. military observer group that
will help monitor repatriation of the U.S.-backed Contra rebels,
officials said Thursday.
   The advance team will travel to the region in early September,
said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   He had no further details on the composition or itinerary of the
advance party, although he said it would probably visit all five
Central American nations.
   The U.N. peacekeeping mission will consist of 100 military
observers and a 50-member support staff. Canada, Spain and West
Germany have agreed to provide personnel, Giuliani said.
   Central American leaders meanwhile asked Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar to set up a U.N. and Organization of American
States civilian mission to help disband and resettle the Nicaraguan
rebels.
   The commission, which is expected to travel to Central America in
September, is to aid ``the voluntary demobilization, repatriation or
relocation in Nicaragua or third countries of the Nicaraguan
resistance and their families.''
   Central American presidents agreed earlier this month to disband
the so-called Contras by mid-December. In return, Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega agreed to hold free and fair elections in
February.
   About 11,000 Contras and 12,000 dependents live in camps in
Honduras. Since the U.S. Congress cut off their military aid last
year, they have received $4.5 million monthly in humanitaritan
assistance.
   The Sandinista government and the Contras agreed March 21 to
suspend offensive operations, but talks aimed at a permanent end to
the 7-year-old war stand at an impasse.
   The White House has agreed to abide by the Tela plan but insists
the rebels must voluntarily agree to disband. Many rebel leaders
have said they will not.
   The United Nations and OAS, however, could help persuade them,
the Central American leaders say. In addition, Honduras has said it
will cooperate with the plan and Nicaragua has offered to help
resettle the rebels.
   Nicaraguan deputy foreign minister, Victor Hugo Tinoco, said
returning Contras will be given land and all other aid to which
Nicaraguan peasant farmers are entitled.
</TEXT>
