<FIRST>u a AM-Rostenkowski-Seniors     08-17 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rostenkowski-Seniors,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Jeered by Seniors Over Stance on Health-Care Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 angry senior citizens jeered Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski on Thursday and briefly blocked his car from
leaving a meeting with community leaders opposing his stance on the
Comprehensive Health Care Act.
   Members of the crowd _ yelling, ``Liar! liar!'' ``Impeach!
Impeach!'' and ``We won't forget at election time'' _ followed
Rostenkowski when he left his car and walked to a location a block
away while his car was driven around the crowd. He then was able to
get back in the car, which drove off.
   During the walk, Rostenkowski refused to acknowledge the
gathering crowds or answer reporters' questions. His only comment
was, ``I don't think they understand what's going on. That's too
bad.''
   Rostenkowski began his day at a community center in the Northwest
Side Chicago district that for 30 years has sent him to Congress,
where he is chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
   He discussed his support for the controversial catastrophic
health care law during a private, 90-minute meeting with
representatives of six organizations representing senior citizens.
   Jerry Prete, president of the Illinois State Council of Senior
Citizens, said Rostenkowski ``wasn't receptive'' to suggestions made
during the session.
   Prete said the group leaders hoped to persuade Rostenkowski to
oppose measures that would shift more of the cost of health care to
seniors.
   Although the meeting may not have gone smoothly, Rostenkowski's
real troubles began after he left the meeting and refused to address
200 people who had gathered in an auditorium outside the private
meeting room.
   As he made his way toward the door, Rostenkowski was roundly
booed and many of those present followed him onto the streets.
   ``We told him we weren't going to boo,'' Prete said. ``We said we
were going to show respect.''
   Rostenkowski walked past the group and climbed into his car.
   People in the crowd, several carrying signs reading, ``Read Our
Lips, Catastrophic Plan Is A Catastrophe,'' then surrounded the car
and one woman refused to move from in front of the vehicle.
   ``We think this man is inhumane,'' said Lawrence Dobson, 67, who
was part of the gathering. ``He's not answering the questions or
needs of the people. Is he afraid of senior citizens?.''
   The catastrophic health insurance program would improve benefits
for the 200 million people, or 85 percent of Americans, who are
underinsured against catastrophic long-term illness.
   Higher income retirees who pay most of the cost of the program
have been lobbying the committee to spread the cost among all
taxpayers, not just older citizens.
</TEXT>
