<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0606,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Turned Back as Israel Tests New Card System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 9th pvs, `His death...' to UPDATE with four
wounded in clashes; picks up 10th pvs, `Near Erez...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EREZ CHECKPOINT, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers blocked
about 1,000 Palestinians from entering Israel Thursday in a test of
new ID cards that have intensified the struggle between Israeli
authorities and Palestinian leaders.
   Officials said about 5,000 other Palestinians got through the
Erez checkpoint during the four-hour test because they had applied
for and received the identification cards, which will be required of
all Gazans who want to enter Israel starting Friday.
   Officials have said they may extend the new system to the West
Bank.
   The experiment came off without violence, unlike five days
earlier when masked youths threw stones at hundreds of cars at
checkpoints to protest the cards.
   Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip have been ordered to
begin a boycott Friday of their jobs in Israel to protest the cards,
which Israeli authorities say are aimed at increasing security.
   In the occupied West Bank on Thursday, soldiers shot and killed a
Palestinian prison escapee carrying an Uzi submachine gun when he
ignored a warning to halt, the army said.
   Shahadi Darwish, 25, was killed night near the village of Idna,
20 miles southwest of Jerusalem.
   The army said Darwish escaped in May from a jail where he was
detained ``on suspicion of committing several terrorist acts,''
including the murder of a police officer.
   His death raised to 537 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli troops and Jewish settlers since the uprising began in
December 1987. Another 95 Palestinians accused of collaborating with
Israel have been killed by fellow Arabs, and 38 Israelis have been
killed.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, troops shot and wounded four
Palestinians, including a 5-year-old boy, Arab hospital officials
said. The army said it was investigating the incidents.
   Near Erez crossing, Brig. Gen. Arye Ramot, head of the Gaza Strip
military government, said the new computerized ID cards will prevent
``potential offenders'' from entering Israel.
   He said nearly 60,000 new cards had been issued and 30,000 to
40,000 more would probably be given out by the time the system
becomes fully operational in three months. A few thousand people
have been refused cards because they have criminal records of been
accused of security offenses, Ramot said.
   Ramot would not give details on why people were refused cards but
said even some people arrested in the uprising could receive them if
they stopped anti-Israeli activities.
   Palestinians maintain the new system is mostly intended to quell
the uprising by putting an economic squeeze on Gaza, where poverty
is widespread and the population of 700,000 depends heavily on jobs
in Israel.
   Graffiti in Gaza called for a two-week boycott of Israeli jobs
starting Friday, and a leaflet from the PLO-backed uprising leaders
ordered a one-week sympathy strike by workers in the West Bank to
start Friday.
   Enforcers for the committees that run the revolt have been going
through towns, villages and camps to seize the cards.
   Near Erez on Thursday, a 48-year-old Palestinian father of eight
complained he'd had to pay his back taxes to get a card and that now
fellow Arabs probably would seize the card.
   Non-payment of taxes has been a major tactic of the uprising, and
Palestinians who want cards must pay all back taxes.
   Ramot said about 1,000 people had asked for second cards after
their first ones were seized.
   According to government figures, 50,000 Palestinians from the
Gaza Strip work in Israel, along with about 60,000 residents of the
West Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
