<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Blake 1stLd-Writethru a0657 08-17 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Blake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0657,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Gunsmoke' Star Amanda Blake Dies at 60</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, `The show's ..., to UPDATE
with comment from Dennis Weaver.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Amanda Blake, who as Miss Kitty
reigned for 19 years as the queen of Dodge City's Long Branch Saloon
in the TV series ``Gunsmoke,'' died after a long battle with cancer.
She was 60.
   Miss Blake died Wednesday night at Mercy General Hospital, said
hospital spokeswoman Jerri Ewen.
   ``She was a beautiful and gracious lady who had a lot to do with
the success of `Gunsmoke,''' series star James Arness said Thursday.
``We were a family together. There are a lot of people for whom
`Gunsmoke' had a special meaning, and they will be sharing the
memories today.''
   The actress had surgery for oral cancer in 1977, and later
appeared throughout the country for two years on behalf of the
American Cancer Society. She was once a two-pack-a-day smoker.
   In 1984, the Cancer Society gave her its annual Courage Award,
which was presented in the Oval Office by President Reagan.
   Miss Blake left ``Gunsmoke'' in 1974 after 19 years. The show
lasted one more season on CBS, then was canceled.
   Set in the lawless cattle town of Dodge City, Kan., in the late
1800s, ``Gunsmoke'' was one of television's original ``adult
westerns'' _ more violent, saltier and sexier than the cowboy fare
offered young viewers in the mid-1950s.
   The show's original cast starred Arness as Marshal Matt Dillon,
Dennis Weaver as his limping deputy, Chester Goode, Milburn Stone as
``Doc'' Adams and Miss Blake as Kitty Russell, the throaty-voiced
owner of the Long Branch.
   ``I loved her very much,'' Weaver said. ``She was very talented
and a real joy for me to work with.''
   There was a love interest between the red-haired Kitty Russell
character and Arness' Marshal Dillon, but the writers kept it off
screen.
   ``We keep it very subtle,'' she said in a 1962 interview. ``We
let people let their imagination do what they want them to do.
Actually, I love the scenes where all we do is, as Jim says,
`eyeball it.'''
   Gunsmoke's story lines softened when it was moved in 1961 from
its late Saturday night time slot to early Monday or Tuesday nights.
Miss Kitty was no longer a potential rape victim of leering bad
guys. Instead, she was abducted a lot.
   ``Good Lord, have I been kidnapped!'' she said in 1968. ``I'm
sick and tired of it. The writers claim I can't be in jeopardy as
long as I'm in town _ because Matt would protect me. So they keep
having me kidnapped.''
   After ``Gunsmoke,'' she worked only sporadically, usually in
guest appearances for TV game shows, movies of the week and such
series as ``Edge of Night,'' ``Hart to Hart,'' and ``Love Boat.''
   Miss Blake, born Beverly Louise Neill in Buffalo, N.Y., made her
dramatic debut as a 10-year-old in a school pageant. She signed a
contract with MGM while still in her teens, and her first film role
was in the 1950 film, ``Stars in My Crown.''
   Besides her work for the American Cancer Society, Miss Blake was
a longtime activist for animal protection.
   A statement issued through the hospital requested that memorials
be sent to the Amanda Blake Memorial Fund at Farmers and Merchants
Bank in Galt. Funeral plans were pending. Miss Blake had no children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2350EDT</FILEID>
