<SECOND>AM-Obit-Schott, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0707,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Horse Owner Dies At 66</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT spelling of Schott.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcia Whitney Schott, a prominent owner of race
horses for nearly 30 years, died Thursday of cancer. She was 66.
   Mrs. Schott was ``a gracious and elegant lady who had won wide
respect in the American world of horse racing,'' said Joe Hirsch,
executive columnist of the Daily Racing Form.
   Among her top horses were Willow Hour, winner of the Travers
Stakes at Saratoga in 1981; Kilts n' Kapers, winner of the Monmouth
Oaks in 1970; and Answer, winner of the Oak Leaf Stakes in 1975 and
the Hollywood Oaks in 1976.
   Mrs. Schott, an interior designer, is survived by her husband,
Lewis, three children and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
