<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Exodus     08-17 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Exodus,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Escape From Beirut To Israeli Security Zone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEATRICE HAMIZRACHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAYT YAHUN, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Lebanese fleeing war-torn
Beirut on Thursday reached this checkpoint on the border of Israel's
self-designated security zone in southern Lebanon.
   ``We all live in fear, and shells keep falling around,'' said
21-year-old Lina Baydoun. ``It makes no difference whether we are
Shiites or Christians, we all suffer.''
   Ms. Baydoun, a physics student at Beirut's American University,
is among more than 25,000 refugees who have escaped to this area
since artillery duels between Syrian forces and Gen. Michel Aoun's
Christian troops began in March.
   By Lebanese police count, at least 776 people have died and 2,076
wounded in the confrontation.
   Foreign and Israeli reporters, on a tour of the Bayt Yahun
checkpoint, five miles north of Israel, saw at least 300 Lebanese
who arrived from Beirut Thursday.
   Most of them said they live in the security zone, a
six-to-10-mile wide belt along the border that Israel carved out in
1985 after withdrawing most of its troops from Lebanon following a
three-year occupation.
   Others own a second house in the zone, and still others said they
would stay with relatives there until the latest round of fighting
ends.
   Adnan Bazzi, a social worker, said he and his relatives have
recently made at least 10 trips to Beirut and back, checking if
their Beirut house was damaged in the shelling.
   ``Every day shells are falling on our houses,'' he said. ``I have
never seen so much shelling, and it continues into the night. Some
shells even pierce the underground (bomb shelters).''
   Some of the refugees settle in abandoned houses in the area,
Israeli army officers said.
   The Lebanese arrived carrying their luggage. They were not
allowed to bring in their vehicles for fear of suicide car bomb
attacks like the Aug. 9 incident in which five Israeli soldiers and
an allied militiaman were wounded.
   The extremist Shiite Moslem Hezbollah group claimed
responsibility in the bombing, which it said was in retaliation for
Israel's July 28 kidnapping of a Shiite cleric from south Lebanon.
   Reporters were ordered to wear bulletproof vests and helmets as
their convoy, accompanied by an Israeli armoured personnel carrier
and military jeeps, crossed into southern Lebanon.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, speaking at an army base on the
Israeli side of the border, told reporters that 90 percent of the
refugees were Shiites, but said he believed they sought refuge.
   ``I believe that they realize the stability, the relative
tranquility in the security zone,'' he said, ``and they prefer to
find a refuge either in the security zone or in its vicinity in
southern Lebanon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
