<DOCNO> AP890817-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Crowe     08-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crowe,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Head Says U.S.-Soviet Relations In ``Uneasy Transition''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the Soviet Union seems sincere in
seeking better relations with the United States, the superpowers
must survive an ``uneasy transition'' before the Cold War truly
thaws, the nation's top military adviser said Thursday.
   ``I am persuaded that we are entering a period of uneasy
transition which will hopefully lead to a new era in the superpower
relationship,'' said Adm. William J. Crowe, Jr., chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   ``But there are many uncertainties still on the horizon, and my
assessment is that we may be in this unsettled state for a long
time, even though that is not comforting,'' he said.
   Crowe is retiring Sept. 30 after 42 years in the Navy, including
four as chief military adviser to the President, the Secretary of
Defense and the National Security Council.
   He said the U.S. government and people must ``keep cool'' in the
face of numerous troop and arms reduction proposals from Moscow.
   ``My deepest concern is that our own impatience, American
impatience, might tempt us to move prematurely ... with broad leaps
of hope and faith, when we encounter inevitable frustration with the
pace of bilateral developments,'' Crowe said. ``We just must be
patient. My own reading of Americans is that they don't like to wait
... they want a better world and they want it tomorrow.''
   Crowe, who in June became the first Joint Chiefs of Staff
Chairman to review Soviet domestic military forces, said he is
convinced Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is trying to
liberalize his country, but may have underestimated the time and
effort ``perestroika'' and ``glasnost'' require.
   Crowe said problems that plague the Russian economic, political
and social scenes extend to its military _ and the people's
expectations of Gorbachev make solutions even more critical.
   ``They realize that they must improve the quality of consumer
goods and services available to the Soviet people as a whole,''
Crowe said. ``In turn, those aims suggest they must somehow reduce
the enormus military burdens on their economy.''
   Although some cuts have been made in the Soviet military,
Gorbachev believes defense must be the top priority, Crowe said.
Even with further reducation, the Soviets would still have more than
four million troops and hold the largest inventory of military
hardware.
   ``Moreover, other elements of Soviet power remain untouched by
reductions announced thus far, including military activities in
space, strategic forces _ mainly nuclear _ and defensive forces, air
defense units, naval combatants, and strategic mobility assets,''
Crowe said.
   After the speech, Crowe urged military restraint against
terrorists, saying the military ``is built for one thing and we're
trying to apply it to another.''
   Answering questions from members of the Japan-America Society of
Honolulu, which sponsored the speech, Crowe said ``we could level
Beirut'' but that would not solve the problem.
   Terrorists holding 16 hostages _ including eight Americans _ in
Beirut ``do not make good military targets'' because they are very
mobile and easily replaced by their sponsors, especially Iran, Syria
and Libya, Crowe said.
   Besides, Crowe said, Americans were not ready to deal with the
repercussions a military strike would bring.
   ``Americans don't want to go to war over terrorism,'' he said.
``What they really want is these problems to go away in a week,
without a lot of energy and investment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
