<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather     08-17 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantic Depression Weakens To Wave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upper level winds weakened an Atlantic tropical
depression to a tropical wave Thursday, forecasters said.
   A tropical storm watch that had been in effect for the Leeward
Islands was discontinued. The islands were expected to receive only
some leftover showers, thunderstorms and gusty winds, said Bob
Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables.
   Forecasters said the sixth Atlantic depression of the season had
been located Wednesday about 500 miles east of the northern Leeward
Islands, but was weakened significantly by upper level winds late
Wednesday night.
   A depression becomes a named storm if its maximum sustained winds
reach 39 mph. Dean, the second hurricane of the June-to-September
Atlantic season, died earlier this month in the North Atlantic after
causing minor damage in Bermuda.
</TEXT>
