<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--747Record     08-17 0125</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--747 Record,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Sets World Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Quantas Airlines 747-400 set a world record
Thursday for long-distance flight by a commercial jet, flying from
London to Sydney, Australia, in 20 hours, eight minutes, Boeing
announced.
   The Boeing-built plane flew 11,156 miles non-stop, eclipsing the
previous record of 10,281 miles set by a Boeing 747SP in flying from
Everett, Wash., to Capetown, South Africa.
   ``We're excited with this flight,'' said Jack Gucker, project
manager for the 747-400. ``In the near future, however, as more
747-400's enter service, ultra-long distance flights will become
commonplace because that's what the plane was designed for.''
   The first 747-400 was delivered in January. By the end of July,
24 customers had ordered 211 planes, Boeing said.
</TEXT>
