<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Chile     08-17 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Shuffles Cabinet To Replace Ministers Running For Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lame-duck President Augusto Pinochet
appointed five new Cabinet members Thursday in a move prompted by
the resignations of two ministers who plan to run for senator in
December elections.
   The entire 17-man Cabinet resigned Aug. 11 to allow Gen. Pinochet
to decide on the changes but, as expected, the 73-year-old president
and army commander rejected most of the resignations.
   The new ministers were sworn in by Pinochet at noon today.
   The changes were not expected to bring significant political
changes in the 16-year-old military government.
   Among those leaving the Cabinet were the Labor and Public Works
ministers, Guillermo Arthur and retired army Gen. Bruno Siebert, who
have announced plans to run for the Senate, and Economy Minister
Pablo Baraona, who will direct the campaign of Hernan Buchi, the
pro-government presidential candidate.
   Pinochet appointed Maria Teresa Infante, an economist, as the new
labor minister. The new economy minister is Adm. Pedro Larrondo.
Gen. Hernan Abad was named public works minister.
   Pinochet also accepted the resignations of Planning Minister
Sergio Melnick and the government's secretary-general, Gen. Oscar
Vargas.
   Luis Larrain, who was Melnick's deputy at the Planning Ministry,
was promoted to succeed him, while army Col. Cristian Labbe took
over as the new secretary-general.
   No reasons were given for those two changes.
   In the Dec. 14 elections, the first since the bloody 1973 coup
that brought Pinochet to power, Chileans will pick a new president
and Congress.
   Pinochet was obliged to call the election after losing a
referendum last year on a proposal to extend his rule until 1997.
Pinochet was barred by the constitution to run in the December
election.
   The leading presidential candidates are Patricio Aylwin, a
70-year-old former Senate president suported by a coalition of 17
opposition parties, and Buchi, 40, Pinochet's former finance
minister.
   The new president and Congress are to take office on March 11.
</TEXT>
