<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0660 to restore two dropped grafs at end</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dole To Visit Poland, Soviet Union, Morocco and The Netherlands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with congressional trip to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole and Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, his wife, will leave Friday on a visit to
four countries, including Poland, which is undergoing historic
political change.
   In announcing the trip, the minority leader's office said the
pair ``will carry President Bush's greetings to the heads of state
they will meet.''
   The Doles will leave Friday, traveling first to Soviet Armenia.
The Doles will take with them relief and rehabilitation supplies
furnished by Project Hope, a charitable organization.
   The trip to Poland comes at a time when President Wojciech
Jaruzelski, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and others are involved in
negotiations designed to form a new government led by the
once-banned trade union movement. If that came to pass, Poland would
have the first non-communist government in the Eastern Bloc in 45
years.
   The Doles will meet with a host of Polish figures over a two-day
period, including Jaruzelski and Walesa, Dole's office said. said.
   Besides the meetings with leading Polish figures scheduled for
Thursday and Friday, Mrs. Dole will discuss possible Labor
Department projects as part of the administration's proposed $100
million aid package to Poland.
   The pair will also visit Morocco and will wind up their 10-day
trip Aug. 28 with a trip to The Netherlands and talks with Queen
Beatrix.
   Also visiting the Soviet Union next week will be a congressional
delegation exploring ways of increasing U.S. agricultural exports to
the Soviets.
   Leading the delegation will be Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas,
who said the visit would let the Americans ``see first-hand the
progress of Mr. Gorbachev's economic reforms.''
   ``The Soviet Union is one of our most important agricultural
export markets, and we want to explore ways to increase our
agricultural trade. We will also discuss the possibility of new
cooperative agreements that would help the Soviet Union improve its
entire agricultural sector,'' de la Garza said.
</TEXT>
