<DOCNO> AP890817-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina     08-17 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Approves Legislation to Speed Up Sale of State Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress approved a bill Thursday
to speed the sale of dozens of state companies, giving President
Carlos Menem his first legislative victory.
   Losses by state companies have produced huge deficits and pushed
inflation.
   The legislation, which takes effect immediately and lasts for 180
days, transfers from Congress to Menem the authority to sell state
companies. The legislation, drafted by Menem's Cabinet, can be
renewed once for an additional 180 days.
   ``A very important step has been taken toward re-establishing the
republic'' on a basis that will allow economic growth, Interior
Minister Eduardo Bauza said.
   Two television stations in the capital will be sold within two
months, according to a presidential decree. Next in line are the
state telephone company and airline, Aerolineas Argentinas,
government officials said.
   Menem was elected on May 14 amid economic crisis. After taking
office in July, Menem said state companies should be sold to cut the
drag on the economy and promote foreign investment and growth.
   The cost of living soared 196.6 percent last month. At least 14
percent of Argentines are unemployed or underemployed, and wages
fell by 60 percent during the first six months of this year.
   Operating losses this year at the several hundred state companies
are projected at $5.5 billion, or about 7 percent of the gross
domestic product, the Public Works Ministry said in July.
   The state oil company alone is expected to lose $1 billion this
year and the state railway, $500 million.
   The State Reform Law passed Thursday authorizes the sale, partial
sale or co-management with private investors of port facilities,
grain elevators, Buenos Aires' subway, the national ship line,
petrochemical plants and oil fields.
   A companion bill would suspend state subsidies to private
businesses, remove barriers to foreign investment, enforce tax
collection and halt Central Bank bailouts of provincial banks and
state companies.
   Congress was expected to approve that bill next week.
   The decision to sell state companies was a policy reversal for
Menem, whose Peronist Party last year blocked attempts by former
President Raul Alfonsin to implement the same legislation.
   Unions, traditionally the mainstay of the Peronists, fear job and
wage cutbacks. But confronted with economic crisis, they have gone
along with Menem on the issue.
   So far, Menem's economic policy has been almost universally well
received.
   In six weeks, he negotiated voluntary wage and price guidelines,
cut the fiscal deficit by increasing state-controled rates for
public utilities by 600 percent and more, and devalued the austral
currency by 54 percent.
   Inflation for August is expected to be less than one-half July's
rate, according to private as well as government economists. It is
thought the September rate will fall below 10 percent.
   Also Thursday, the car of labor leader Saul Ubaldini was
destroyed by a bomb blast. There were no injuries in the explosion,
directed at the secretary-general of the 3-million-strong General
Labor Confederation.
   No group claimed responsibilty for the explosion. Police said
they were investigating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
