<DOCNO> AP890817-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0697,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Strike And Threaten To Resign After Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th pvs, ``He did...'' to update with nationwide
police sweep. Pickup 5th pvs, ``Late Wednesday...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's judges went on strike and
threatened to resign Thursday to protest security conditions after
the slaying of a court magistrate who had ruled against two leaders
of the Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Union leaders met in emergency session Thursday in response to a
wave of shooting deaths and intimidation of magistrates, said Helmut
Romero, the union's vice president.
   ``In view of the government's inability to protect its judges, we
decided to begin a nationwide indefinite strike and intend to offer
our collective resignation,'' Romero said.
   He did not say when that would happen.
   Police announced late Thursday that 51 people were arrested and
$7.7 million in cash and gold bars were seized in a nationwide
sweep. Police spokesman Alfredo Salgado also said about 50
submachine guns, revolvers, pistols and hand grenades were also
seized since Wednesday.
   Late Wednesday, gunmen on two motorcycles and in a taxi opened
fire with with machine guns on Magistrate Carlos Valencia Garcia,
43, as he left his office in central Bogota.
   Valencia Garcia, who had rejected court motions to exonerate two
leaders of the Medellin cartel for their part in the 1987 slaying of
a journalist, was shot six times. He died a short time later at a
hospital.
   Every judge who have investigated cartel leaders Pablo Escobar
Gaviria and Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha are either dead, have resigned
or were forced to leave Colombia by death threats.
   Romero called on the government to step up protection of federal
judges involved in drug trials ``because it is not acceptable that a
judge is slain in Colombia every 15 days.''
   Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, the head of Colombia's secret police,
late Wednesday said police would adopt new security measures to
protect judges but refused to say what they were. Maza Marquez last
month escaped an assassination attempt that he attributed to the
cocaine cartel.
   ``The assassination of Valenca Garcia should unite us to look for
ways to combat our common enemy _ drug trafficking,'' Maza Marquez
said following an urgent meeting of the National Security Council.
   Maza Marquez said Valencia Garcia was accompanied by two armed
security guards and was wearing a bulletproof vest when he was shot
and killed.
   Antonio Salom Beltran, president of Colombia's Supreme Court,
said the war against judges had reached an ``intolerable point.''
   In the last 10 years, 23 judges have been assassinated, and
officials blame nearly all the deaths on drug traffickers.
   Three years ago, 12 members of Colombia's Supreme Court were
killed when guerrillas took over the Palace of Justice in Bogota.
The government said rebels were working with drug smugglers and
destroyed hundreds of files on drug trafficking.
   The Medellin cartel, named after the Colombian city where it is
based, is the world's largest cocaine ring. It is believed
responsible for up to 80 percent of the cocaine that is smuggled
into the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0549EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     08-17 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0662</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The moon blushed in Alabama, turned taupe in Minneapolis, glowed
orange in Maine and Texas, and disappeared altogether in Washington
during a rare ``prime time'' full lunar eclipse that attracted awed
sky watchers from coast to coast.
   Clouds spoiled the view for much of the United States, but where
the skies were clear observers reported a spectacular celestial show
of light and color.
   In the nation's capital, the moon rose as a golden orange, tinted
grayish brown as the eclipse began, then winked out altogether as
the lunar disk swept into the dark inner core of the Earth's shadow.
   ``I finally saw one disappear,'' said Alan Fiala, a Naval
Observatory astronomer who has studied eclipses for 15 years.
   A little girl, watching with her mother in a park in Minneapolis,
also saw it fade from view.
   ``Is the moon going to come back tomorrow?'' she asked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies may learn to crawl and walk a little slower
if their mothers drink while nursing, according to a study released
today that suggests even small amounts of alcohol in breast milk can
affect development.
   While the results are troubling, experts caution that there is no
clear proof that nursing mothers will harm their babies if they
drink moderately.
   ``I would not worry about drinking during lactation until this
finding has been confirmed in at least one more study,'' said Dr.
Ruth E. Little, principal author of the research report.
   Even if their babies are slow to walk, she said, mothers should
not blame their occasional drinking, because babies normally vary in
when they learn these skills.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today begins a
three-week seaside vacation, visiting with family and entertaining
two world leaders away from Washington's summer doldrums.
   Bush arrived here Wednesday, announcing he was aiming to ``get my
body in shape'' with his favorite vacation pastime _ intensive
exercise.
   The president and first lady Barbara Bush were expecting separate
visits from Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and Danish Prime
Minister Poul Schluter, but those were to be personal rather than
business-oriented, the White House said.
   Bush flew to this resort town from Miami, where he made a one-day
campaign foray in behalf of Republican congressional candidate
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, who is vying against Democrat Gerald Richman to
succeed the late Democratic Rep. Claude Pepper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting a telephone installed by any of the
four strike-bound regional phone companies requires patience, but
officials say customers are having better luck with operator
assistance.
   ``We ask our customers to continue to be patient with us,'' said
Steve Ford, a spokesman for Ameritech, one of the four companies hit
by the 11-day-old strike.
   Recorded messages Wednesday continued to tell 411 directory
assistance callers that ``due to the work stoppage, your call may be
delayed.'' But telephone company officials said the waits are
becoming shorter as management personnel get to know the computer
equipment.
   Operator-assisted calls, maintenance and repairs are being
handled at near pre-strike levels in many areas, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Official U.S. displeasure over the Chinese
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement is putting a damper on
departing Ambassador Han Xu's farewell to Washington.
   The most prominent Americans among about 500 guests at Han's
Chinese Embassy reception Wednesday night were retired rather than
active public officials.
   They included two former secretaries of state, Henry Kissinger
and Alexander Haig, and two former Senate leaders, Republican Hugh
Scott and Democrat Mike Mansfield. Also there was former Democratic
Sen. J. William Fulbright.
   The absence of top members of President Bush's administration and
cabinet reflected the president's post-June 3 policy of balancing
U.S. public outrage over the killings of Chinese pro-democracy
demonstrators against the decision to continue dialogue with the
Chinese government.
</TEXT>
