<DOCNO> AP890817-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-AfterTiananmen-Reverses Adv27   08-17 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-After Tiananmen-Reverses, Adv 27,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>China's Crackdown on Dissent Reverses Trends Toward Liberalism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-After Tiananmen, b0743</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese leadership's crackdown on dissent
since early June would not be so startling if it did not follow one
of Communist China's most lively periods of debate in the arts and
social sciences.
   Early this year, for example, the prestigious China Art Gallery
in Beijing allowed controversial exhibits of nude paintings and of
avant-garde art, at which a young artist shot her own work with a BB
gun to show her rejection of Chinese culture.
   Young economists developed schemes for distributing state-owned
factories to the workers in hopes of stimulating productivity and
cutting workers' dependence on the state.
   Government television aired a documentary that challenged
cherished notions of the superiority of traditional Chinese
civilization and denounced the Great Wall as a symbol of all that is
insular and backward in China.
   Such new ideas were silenced by the gunfire in Tiananmen Square
in June.
   Since then party officials have demanded that the entire nation
``unify thinking'' by studying the speeches of top leaders in
defense of the crackdown.
   Here are some examples of unorthodox thinking that preceded the
crackdown, and what is being said now:
   _A banner carried by reporters from the Communist Party
newspaper, the People's Daily, on May 4: ``We want to speak the
truth.'' A People's Daily article July 30 about ``certain erroneous
views'' in Chinese journalism: ``Different classes and different
social groups have different standards of so-called truth,
objectivity and fairness.'' The main role of the media is to be a
``party mouthpiece.''
   _Wang Renzhi, head of the Communist Party's Propaganda
Department, speaking at a national arts conference May 20, 1988:
``China's art and literature should embrace various concepts and
forms. ... From now on ... the party will get involved as little as
possible in art creation, performances and controversies.'' Wang,
meeting with artists and writers July 7: ``We should earnestly fight
against bourgeois liberalism in literary and art circles and make
socialist literature and art dominate.''
   _Social scientist Wu Jiaxiang, writing in December in the
now-closed World Economic Herald of Shanghai: ``The insecurities and
fear small private business people have that the government policies
may change some day should be allayed with theoretical guarantees as
well as specific measures.'' The China Daily newspaper July 30:
``Private business people, whose wealth is displayed by their
private cars, expensive imported clothes and gold jewelry, play a
major role in the phenomenon of `unfair distribution.' The incomes
of an estimated 40 percent of the 100,000 private business people in
Beijing are considered to be `not reasonable'.''
   _The director of the president's office at Beijing University,
Huang Huaicheng, speaking at the university's 90th anniversary
celebration in May 1988: ``Beijing University students have a
tradition of being concerned about the future of the country.'' Vice
Minister of Education He Dongchang, speaking to college officials
Aug. 10: ``Students in many universities have admitted they have
three major weak points _ overestimating their own ability, lacking
an overall understanding of China's actual situation and knowing
little about Marxism.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-AfterTiananmen-Foreigners Adv27   08-17 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-After Tiananmen-Foreigners, Adv 27,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Few Foreigners and Tourists Seen These Days in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-After Tiananmen, b0743</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a small number of the foreigners who fled
China after the army crushed the democracy movement in June have
come back.
   It is possible now to walk through the Temple of Heaven Park, one
of Beijing's leading tourist attractions, without seeing a single
foreigner.
   The Friendship Store, a three-story government department store
stocked with souvenirs and imported food for foreigners, is packed
with Chinese these days.
   The store is so desperate for shoppers it has raised its daily
quota of Chinese visitors. It has slashed prices, too: a can of
oolong tea sells for 12 yuan ($3.25) now, half the pre-June price.
   The two blocks between the Jianguo and Jinglun hotels for
foreigners and the Friendship Store used to be crowded with young
men offering to exchange money at black market rates. Now, the money
changers are gone.
   Some legitimate businessmen want to give up.
   ``I'm trying to unload my business, but no one wants to buy,''
said a clothing vendor in a private market formerly jammed with
foreign tourists.
   Many hotel workers and others affected by the drop in tourism are
suddenly taking ``vacations'' at reduced salaries. Chinese workers
do not ordinarily get vacations.
   Foreign residents in Beijing are trickling back. The U.S.
Government gave approval Aug. 11 for embassy dependents to return,
and other countries are doing the same.
   The government said two-thirds of the nearly 1,170 foreign
companies with offices in Beijing have not resumed normal
operations. Many businessmen commute in from Hong Kong only to
handle pressing matters.
   But a Western business consultant in Beijing said companies that
already have invested in China cannot afford to walk away, and
although new investment likely will suffer, some companies still
regard a presence in China as essential to their Asian marketing
strategies. Others have found they can get better terms now from
Chinese partners keen for investment dollars.
   ``You would like to punish the government, but how can you?''
said the consultant, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The moral
issue always comes up ... but at the end of the day it's just
business.''
   It is less clear how cultural exchanges will fare. The American
Joffrey Ballet canceled what was to have been a black-tie
performance this fall. The British Council postponed indefinitely a
exhibition of modern British art.
   Some scholars have dropped plans to teach in China in the fall
and others are still trying to decide. The Chinese government has
suspended the U.S. government-sponsored exchange of Fulbright
scholars.
   Ignatius Cao, a Chinese-born political science professor at the
State University of New York in Oneonta, said halting scholarly
exchanges would be tragic.
   ``At least many Chinese can know the other world through our
presence,'' he said. ``I don't urge (the students) to make
revolution. I just want them to understand ... the realities outside
the socialist camp.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
