<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Woulda-Coulda-Shoulda Adv21   08-17 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Woulda-Coulda-Shoulda, Adv 21,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Woulda-Coulda-Shouldang</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're people haunted by regret over choices
in life. ``If only...,'' they say, ``... but it's too late now.''
   ``They're the people who are always thinking about the past,''
said psychologist Arthur Freeman. Such ``ruminators,'' mired in
their pasts, believe their lives have been irrevocably altered by
choices they'd like to change.
   ``What they think of is how things were. They don't see the flip
side of how things are,'' said Freeman, a professor at the
University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey and the
University of Pennsylvania.
   They can be recognized as soon as they start talking about their
problems, he said. They say: ``I look at the past and see more
failure than success,'' ``I would like to change my job, but it's
too late,'' ``I should have become an artist,'' or ``I could be
happy if only I were rich.''
   Freeman encourages his patients at Penn's Center for Cognitive
Therapy to rethink such comments. ``If only I hadn't given up my
career to have children'' becomes ``I have three wonderful, loving
children.''
   In a new book, ``Woulda-Coulda-Shoulda'' (Silver Arrow Books,
$17.95), Freeman and Rose DeWolf of The Philadelphia Daily News
explore second-guessing, outline a course of action and, using
specific situations, describe how readers can either fall back into
the habit or break it.
   ``Insight, in and of itself, is not sufficient to change,''
Freeman said. ``I'm more interested in what keeps you doing the same
stuff and how you can change. Change is the name of the game. Not
just sitting here talking about change but actively working on
change.''
   The first step is acknowledging a problem and wanting change.
Ruminators should examine their assumptions, such as having an
unlimited skill (``I'd be happy if I were a successful surgeon.'')
or being able to know the future (``We'd be rich if I had sold the
stock at a higher price.'').
   The next step is to write down the advantanges or disadvantages
as a way to evaluate the change and the person's willingness to risk
it.
   Freeman encourages his patients to challenge their thinking and
conclusions by examining the assumptions inherent in their
statements. Once the assumptions are understood, he said, ruminators
should decide a course of action.
   His former dentist, in the midst of a successful practice and
teaching position at Penn, decided to become an engineer. After
several years of night school while continuing to work, he graduated
and reached his goal _ an example Freeman cites of goals that are
not unattainable, but have to be accomplished step by step. Failure
to overcome the problem usually occurs when a person can't take the
final step and risk a change.
   ``Making a change is difficult,'' Freeman said. ``The
woulda-coulda-shoulda person thinks of the endpoint but refuses to
get involved in the process.''
   Once the change is made, a former ruminator may have trouble with
others who want to continue that thought pattern. Freeman's book
suggests several methods for avoiding that trap, which he calls ``a
tug of war.''
   ``The message of this book is that it is possible to look back in
a new way,'' he wrote. ``The key to progress in life is returning to
the present. The Hall of Memories becomes a fascinating place to
visit _ no longer a place in which to live _ or even linger.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
