<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-Ice Adv21   08-17 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Ice, Adv 21,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Researcher Experiments with Ice Construction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wilfrid is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilfrid Nixon has true grit _ and he hopes
to mix it with water and make ice strong enough for offshore Arctic
oil platforms.
   Some companies have built drilling platforms of ice, but ``adding
sand would make it stronger, and you could make the structure
quicker because you're adding less water to achieve the same
volume,'' said Nixon, whose is studying alluvium-reinforced ice at
the University of Iowa.
   ``I've spoken with some of the engineers at Mobil who do research
in the ice area. They think it's a good idea,'' he said. So did the
National Science Foundation, which gave him a $35,000 grant in
November to test his theory.
   Clad in sandals and a short-sleeved shirt, Nixon oversees
experiments done in 23-degree temperatures at the Institute of
Hydraulic Research lab, where he and associates freeze water and
different types and blends of sand into beams and cylinders, some of
them seven feet long and weighing 1,000 pounds. ``We've tested 400
beams and anticipate testing another 400 before it's all over.''
   In the Arctic, sand could be shipped in or dredged from the sea
bed and mixed with water from ``huge great versions of snow making
machines'' used to make the base. A base of sand and ice would weigh
about 10 tons, Nixon said.
   Platform bases have made of steel, concrete and ice. With sand
and ice, he said, ``A base for a drilling platform would take about
30 days as opposed to 50 days for just the ice. Sixty to 90 days is
typically how long it takes to get it constructed with the other
materials.''
   Nixon estimates a company could save $500,000 with a sand-ice
base.
   He hopes to test his theories at a reservoir near Iowa City if
it's cold enough this winter. ``We'd basically throw a hole in the
ice and drop through two tubes, one to get water and the other to
get whatever's on the bottom. We'd suck them up, spray them out and
hopefully create a small platform base maybe 10 feet in diameter.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
