<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-17 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0848</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial production rose for the first time
in three months in July, the government said in a report analysts
saw as evidence that a recession will be avoided this year.
   The Federal Reserve said Wednesday its industrial production
index last month stood at 141.7 percent of its 1977 base, compared
with 141.4 percent in June.
   The 0.2 percent increase in July followed consecutive declines of
0.1 percent in May and June. Overall production was up 2.7 percent
over a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing starts rose for the second straight
month in July, the government reported, and analysts said
single-family construction should continue at a moderate pace the
rest of the year.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that housing starts were
up 0.8 percent last month, following an 8.5 percent hike in June.
New homes and apartments were started in July at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.43 million, up from 1.42 million in June.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Philippines and bank
creditors announced tentative agreement on a new debt package,
allowing the Bush administration to claim a second victory for its
program to reduce the debt burden carried by the Third World.
   The Philippines will receive new money in addition to a partial
reduction in its $28 billion debt burden, about half of which is
owed to commercial banks.
   The Philippines agreement, announced Wednesday, follows an accord
reached last month with Mexico, the developing world's
second-largest debtor with $108 billion in loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. said it will suspend
payments on $208.6 million in institutional debts, an apparent step
to give it a stronger hand in negotiations with its bank lenders.
   The cash-short computer giant has been trying to negotiate a new
line of credit with a group of eight banks, led by Bank o Boston, to
replace a $300 million credit line that expires Sept. 30.
   By suspending payments Wednesday on the $208.6 million in
commercial paper and bank notes, it is putting more pressure on the
eight bank lenders, since those banks also hold some of the
securities in question.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sea Containers Ltd. said its board rejected a
sweetened $1 billion takeover bid and is making plans instead for a
cash payout to shareholders.
   Sea Containers' board said Wednesday that the revised bid from
Temple Holdings Ltd., owned by Sweden's Stena Holdings AG and
Britain's Tiphook PLC, was inadequate and not in the best interests
of its shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock brokers who deal in low-priced, often
risky securities known as ``penny stocks'' must obtain a customer's
written approval before completing a sale, under a rule adopted by
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The new rule adopted Wednesday comes in response to a dramatic
rise in the fraudulent sale of penny stocks, which are usually not
traded on exchanges or quoted on the National Association of
Securities Dealers Automated Quotation (NASDAQ) System, commonly
known as the national over-the-counter market.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago Mercantile Exchange yen trader pleaded
innocent to fraud and racketeering charges, the 14th trader to do so
following indictments stemming from the government's investigation
of the nation's major futures markets.
   Meanwhile Wednesday, attorneys for traders indicted in the probe
said they want a year or more to prepare for trial, although a
federal judge indicated he might not give them that long.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. moved to drop another subsidiary
as it announced plans to sell Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc. to an
affiliate of Unicord Co. Ltd. of Thailand for $269 million in cash.
   The deal disclosed Wednesday is unusual in that the buyer is from
Thailand, a poor Southeast Asian nation that is trying to catch up
with the Far East's Four Tigers: South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and
Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications took a big step toward
getting its commercially sponsored Channel One news show in schools
across the country, awarding Philips Consumer Electronics Co. a $150
million-plus contract to ``build a video pipeline'' to the
classrooms.
   The Knoxville, Tenn.-based media concern picked Philips over two
other contenders Wednesday for the huge assignment, which involves
making and installing up to 300,000 television sets, 16,000
videocassette recorders and 8,000 satellite dishes at participating
schools.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks faltered Wednesday after a strong opening rally fizzled,
but the market still finished with a small gain. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials rose 5.51 points to finish at 2,693.29.
   The dollar drifted mostly lower against major foreign currencies
after a mixed performance overseas.
   Bond prices rose for the second straight day.
   Energy futures prices advanced modestly; soybean futures dropped
sharply and grain futures were mixed; precious metals prices
retreated; copper advanced and livestock and pork futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
