<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ManagementConference     08-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Management Conference,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn, Jackson, Dalai Lama To Attend Management Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate raider Carl Icahn, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and the head of giant investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. are getting together for a friendly takeover battle.
   The unscripted _ but simulated _ drama about a hostile raid will
take place next month at a conference on management in the 1990s by
the World Management Council, the group said Wednesday.
   Also scheduled to attend the three-day conference in Manhattan
are the Dalai Lama, the Tibetan spiritual leader; leveraged buyout
specialist Henry Kravis; former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul
Volcker; Italian industrialist Carlo de Benedetti; Texas oilman and
sometime raider T. Boone Pickens; and dozens of other business,
political and education figures.
   In the mock takeover, Icahn will make a surprise hostile bid for
a fictitious company headed by former Arco Inc. Chairman Robert O.
Anderson. The raid comes during a company board meeting addressing
other issues.
   Jackson is scheduled to be a board member but he may switch to a
more characteristic role as a shareholder rights defender or
community figure, said John Diebold, president of the World
Management Council, which held its first congress in 1924.
   Drexel Chief Executive Frederick Joseph, whose firm has provided
financial backing and advice for many corporate raids in the 1980s,
originally was cast as Icahn's investment backer. ``Now he's decided
he wants to be the company's banker,'' said Diebold, who is chairman
of the management consultant Diebold Group Inc.
   The takeover scenario is being developed by a case writer at the
Harvard Business School, he said.
   The Dalai Lama, the traditional high priest of Lamaism, a form of
Buddhism, will be honored for protecting individual human rights at
the Sept. 21-23 conference in New York, Diebold said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
