<FIRST>r f PM-GMTrucks     08-17 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Trucks,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM to Use Pontiac Plant Through 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s Pontiac Central
plant will remain in use through next year after its medium-duty
truck line is shifted to a plant in Janesville, Wis., GM said.
   Clifford Vaughan, GM vice president and executive in charge of
the truck group, said the plant will produce a special chassis for
school buses and vehicles such as delivery vans.
   Originally the plant was to close at the end of the year when
medium-duty truck production stopped. Vaughan said truck production
would stop as scheduled but chassis production would be added.
   The plant employs about 2,100 people. That will be cut when the
truck production is moved to Wisconsin, but GM officials haven't
said how many employees will work on the special chassis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
