<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SeaContainers     08-17 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sea Containers,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sea Containers Board Rejects Sweetened Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sea Containers Ltd., which leases shipping
containers and runs ferries, said its board has rejected a sweetened
$1 billion takeover bid and is making plans instead for a cash
payout to shareholders.
   Sea Containers is based in Hamilton, Bermuda, and operates
ferries in the English Channel.
   Sea Containers' board said Wednesday the revised bid from Temple
Holdings Ltd., which is owned by Sweden's Stena Holdings AG and
Britain's Tiphook PLC, was inadequate and not in the best interests
of the company and its shareholders.
   The board recommend that shareholders refuse to tender their
shares under terms of the offer, which is scheduled to expire Aug.
28.
   At the same time, the board directed management to proceed with
previously disclosed efforts to develop a recapitalization plan that
would involve ``a substantial cash distribution'' to shareholders
and the issue of new common stock and other securities.
   It said management had hired the investment firm Goldman, Sachs &amp;
Co. to advise on arranging financing for the recapitalization.
   The board said it would propose a recapitalization even if the
Temple bid were withdrawn.
   Temple disclosed Tuesday that it was raising its tender offer for
Sea Containers' common stock to $63 a share from $50 and for its
convertible preferred stock to $101.43 per share from $80.50.
   A spokesman for Temple said the new bid valued Sea Containers at
$1.02 billion, up from $824 million in the initial bid launched May
26.
   Stena already owns about 8 percent of Sea Containers stock.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Sea Containers rose
$1.12{ a share to $68.25.
   In another development, the debt rating service Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp. said it was continuing to review whether to lower Sea
Container's credit ratings. S&amp;P has been reviewing the matter since
Temple launched its unsolicited bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
