<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-Loomis     08-17 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-Loomis,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Investment Firm Buys 12 Percent of Texas Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boston investment firm said its 12 percent stake
in Texas Air Corp., parent company of Continental Airlines and
Eastern Airlines, is strictly for investment purposes.
   Loomis, Sayles &amp; Co. said it had been accumulating Texas Air
stock since May, but didn't file notice of the stake with the
Securities and Exchange Commission until Wednesday. Investors are
required to notify the SEC of stock holdings when they exceed 5
percent of a company's total shares.
   Ken Heebner, a portfolio manager for Loomis, Sayles, said its
interest in Texas Air is strictly for investment purposes and does
not represent a possible takeover attempt.
   Texas Air said it welcomed the investment.
   ``We are pleased to have such a well-regarded financial
institution showing such confidence in the company,'' said spokesman
Art Kent.
   Texas Air recently reported a second-quarter loss of $109.3
million. The company also has posted two consecutive years of
multimillion-dollar losses.
   ``A challenge in investing is buying something that's not making
money right now,'' Heebner said of the Houston-based holding company.
   ``The company will make money in 1990,'' he said. ``The company
is getting healthier.''
   Continental, also based in Houston, has had business problems in
the past, but the airline's health has improved, Heebner said.
   ``In addition, I hear the service facilities have improved,'' he
said. ``You'll see more business travelers.''
   Heebner also predicted that Eastern will emerge from its
bankruptcy reorganization as a profitable subsidiary of Texas Air.
   ``You'll see a smaller Eastern, but it'll be a profitable
Eastern,'' he said.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
March 9, five days after its Machinists union members went on
strike. Since then, it has been rebuilding as a smaller airline
using non-union workers.
   Loomis, Sayles manages more than $20 billion in assets for
institutional and individual clients. The firm is a wholly owned
subsidiary of The New England, an insurance company.
   Texas Air stock closed Wednesday at $17.87{ on the American Stock
Exchange, down 12{ cents.
   The largest stockholder of Texas Air is Jet Capital Corp., Texas
Air's holding company, which owns all of the Class A common Texas
Air stock, Kent said. J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc. owns 11.7 percent of
the common stock, while Scandinavian Airlines System has 9.8 percent
and Equitable Life Assurance Society of the U.S. has 6.4 percent.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo owns 48.7 percent of Jet Capital
while Minneapolis banker Carl R. Pohlad, who owns the Minnesota
Twins, owns 12 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
