<DOCNO> AP890817-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0730EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-17 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mostly higher in moderate
European trading early today ahead of the release of U.S. trade
figures later in the day.
   Gold prices fell.
   The dollar's strength indicated an easing of fears of a slowdown
in the U.S. economy, some traders said. But most said it showed that
market players were expecting a narrowing in the U.S. trade deficit.
   Dealers said they were expecting the trade deficit to have shrunk
to about $9.4 billion in June from $10.24 billion in May.
   ``The market is bullish and that's why the dollar remains at this
relatively high level,'' said a trader at a large U.S. bank in
Frankfurt.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5730 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5725 late Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.9500 West German marks, up from 1.9470; 1.6810
Swiss francs, up from 1.6775; 6.5900 French francs, up from 6.5700;
2.1968 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1925; 1,401.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,397.75; 1.1765 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1785.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.52 yen to a closing 142.32 yen. Its price in
London was 142.77 yen.
   Gold prices were pushed down by the expectations of a
narrower-than-expected trade gap, which would divert investors from
the bullion market.
   Gold opened in London at $365.85 a troy ounce, lower than a late
bid price of $368.75 Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $366.10, compared with $368.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.15 to close at $366.69.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.18 a troy ounce, down from
$5.24 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
