<HEAD>Marvin Davis Ups Bid for UAL to $6.2 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis has sweetened his offer for
UAL Corp. to $6.2 billion and prepared to wage a possible proxy
fight to gain control of the company's board.
   Davis raised his offer for the parent of United Airlines to $275
a share Wednesday from his original $240 a share, or $5.4 billion,
bid.
   UAL stock closed Wednesday at $251.75 a share on the New York
Stock Exchange, down $2.50. Davis' new bid was revealed after the
market closed.
   UAL directors are expected to consider the new offer at a meeting
today.
   Spokeswoman Sara Dornacker said the company would have no comment
on the sweetened offer before the meeting.
   UAL also declined comment on Davis' filing of documents asking
shareholders to remove all 16 directors other than Chairman Stephen
M. Wolf and replace them with a five-member board headed by Davis.
   Davis spokesman James Fingeroth said the California billionaire
does not intend at this time to solicit votes against the current
board.
   He said the documents were filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission only to establish a time frame _ Aug. 16 to Oct. 15 _ for
determining which shareholders would be eligible to vote should
there be a proxy battle.
   The filing ``was prompted by press reports that raised the
specter of a transaction which might interfere with the ability of
shareholders to promptly maximize the value of their investment in
UAL,'' said Fingeroth.
   Davis's offer has sparked interest in UAL among other possible
suitors, including the airline's top managers who reportedly met
with the Air Line Pilots Association for discussions of a possible
management-employee buyout.
   Jim Damron, spokesman for the pilots union, refused to comment on
Davis' latest moves.
   In a statement, Davis said his offer could go higher after a
review of the company's financial data.
   He said that by the end of next week he should be able to provide
details of the financing of the proposed deal.
</TEXT>
