<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Computer     08-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Computer,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Reports 3 Percent Drop In Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. reported today its
earnings in its third fiscal quarter fell 3 percent, reflecting the
acquisition of Apollo Computer Inc. and continuing problems
predicting demand for its product lines.
   Hewlett-Packard said its earnings for the period ending July 31
totaled $187 million, or 79 cents a share, down from $192 million,
or 80 cents a share, for the third quarter of 1988.
   The $476.4 million acquisition of Apollo Computer in May cut
earnings 13 cents a share, the computer and scientific instrument
maker said. Without the purchase, profits would have been 92 cents a
share, 15 percent higher than the same period last year,
Hewlett-Packard said.
   Revenue, helped by an increase in orders, increased 23 percent,
to $3 billion from $2.43 billion in the third quarter of last year.
   ``Areas of strength included workstations, personal computers and
personal peripherals,'' John A. Young, company president and chief
executive officer, said in a statement.
   The company also enjoyed an increase of demand in
test-and-measurement instruments and medical- and analytical-product
orders, he added. However, Hewlett-Packard, like other computer
companies, also saw ``order weakness'' for high-end minicomputers
and electronic components, Young said.
   Hewlett-Packard earlier this week warned investors of
lower-than-expected profits, predicting earnings of between 75 and
80 cents a share. Many analysts had been expecting quarterly
earnings in the 90-cent-per-share range.
   The company said it has stopped hiring and imposed expense
controls as a way of improving profitability.
</TEXT>
