<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower On Slack Export, Rain Chances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices were mixed and grain
futures fell in early trading on the Chicago Board of Trade today,
reflecting signs of slack export demand and forecasts for rain in
the Midwest.
   Wheat exports have been slow and traders fear that Mexico's bid
for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn may be endangered because of
concerns about contamination by aflatoxin, a cancer-causing fungus
that infected some of last year's crop.
   ``The market's looking for fresh export business but we don't see
too much right at the moment,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Showers are expected this weekend in the Midwest, where the bulk
of the corn and soybean crop is grown.
   And a National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued late
Wednesday called for above-normal rainfall in the region in the
latter half of next week.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97 a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 1} cents lower with September at $2.33} a bushel; oats were
{ cent to 2 cents lower with September at $1.36 a bushel; soybeans
were 2{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with August at $6.21 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August at
73.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with August at 84.60 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with August at 47.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were unchanged to .25 cent higher with August at 26.87
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
advanced.
