<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices briefly reached 1989 highs during the
trading day on London's Stock Exchange Thursday, partly in response
to better-than-expected U.S. trade figures.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended up 14.2
points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,360.0. It touched a 1989 record trading
high of 2,374.8 earlier in the day.
   The market started strongly, then roared ahead on news that the
U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $8.17 billion in June,
down from a revised $10.08 billion in May.
   ``The market just wanted to go forward today,'' one trader said,
``and found any excuse to move higher.''
   However, buying interest began to fade at higher levels and a
nervous opening on Wall Street encouraged the market to fall from
its peaks.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended 13.2 points higher at
1,975.0. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 6.0 points to
close at 1,326.39.
   Volume came to a healthy 544.3 million shares, up from 449.8
million shares Wednesday.
</TEXT>
