<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0351</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was broadly lower in moderately
active trading today after an unexpectedly sharp narrowing of the
June U.S. trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 19.54 points to
2,673.75 at 2 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was off 14.04 points
at noon.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by about 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange with 925 issues down, 462 up and 533 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 117.33 million shares.
   Wall Street analysts said the market was lower across the
spectrum, with no one group leading the decline.
   ``It's unusually featureless,'' said Eugene Peroni, technical
analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott.
   The stock and bond markets rallied early in response to the June
merchandise trade deficit. But bond prices quickly retreated, and
stocks followed, on renewed concern about the economy's strength.
   The Commerce Department reported the June U.S. trade deficit
narrowed to $8.17 billion from a revised $10.08 billion in May.
Exports increased 1.5 percent to a record level of $30.91 billion
while imports fell 3.6 percent to $39.08 billion.
   ``The concern is that the gap shows the economy was stronger than
people thought,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, vice president at A.G.
Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
   A strengthening economy reduces the likelihood that the Federal
Reserve will lower interest rates.
   Later, the market's concern turned to the strengthening dollar,
traders said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.97 to 191.67.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
1.85 to 377.75.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, UAL was up 13] at 265[
after news that billionaire Marvin Davis raised his bid for United
Airlines' parent to $275 a share. AMR Corp. was up 1] and General
Electric had climbed [ to 57|.
   Hewlett Packard was down 1] to 51[, Ford Motor was off } to 51[
and Navistar was off \ to 4~.
