<FIRST>r f AM-BancoSantander-Kemper     08-17 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banco Santander-Kemper,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banco Santander Takes 3 Percent Stake in Kemper Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banco Santander, Spain's fourth-largest
commercial bank, Thursday announced it had taken a 3 percent stake
in Long Grove, Ill.-based Kemper Corp. to prepare for the creation
of a single European market in 1992.
   Sources close to the deal said the bank paid an estimated $60
million for its stake in Kemper, making it one of the largest
shareowners of the parent company of Kemper Financial Companies.
   The bank said the move combined with other recent alliances
``places (the bank) in a unique position among European financial
institutions'' to meet increased competition expected after the
creation of the unified market in the 12-nation European Economic
Community.
   Kemper is among the leaders in the domestic U.S. market in the
management of mutual funds, investment-related insurance products
and brokerage services.
   Through its subsidiary operations, Kemper has offices across the
United States, a network of 3 million clients and more than $55
billion of assets under management.
   The statement also said the Spanish bank and Kemper have signed
an agreement to cooperate in activities ranging from mutual fund
management to investment banking to trading in Spain, the United
States and other countries where both operate.
   The Spanish bank has recently taken aggressive moves to build up
its international presence in advance of 1992, when the EEC is
eliminate most barriers to capital movements.
   In July, the bank reached a deal for Japan's Nomura Securities
Co. to acquire 1.5 percent of the bank and 10 percent of its
investment bank, Banco Santander de Negocios, for an estimated $100
million.
   Banco de Santander has also established a European business
alliance with Royal Bank of Scotland, it which it owns a 10 percent
stake.
   Banco Santander is the holding company for a financial group with
1,608 branches in 36 countries in Europe, America and the Far East
involved in commercial banking, investment banking, leasing,
mortgage banking and asset management.
   As of June 1989, Banco Santander had total consolidated assets of
$34.3 billion. Its pre-tax profits for the first half of 1989
reached $321.7 million, an increase of 32 percent over the same
period last year, the bank said.
</TEXT>
