<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-Guatemala     08-17 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Guatemala,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Scrubs Guatemala Project After Environmental Outcry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition by Guatemalan archeological and
environmental officials recently prompted Exxon Corp. to scrap a
multimillion dollar oil drilling project planned among Mayan ruins
in a rain forest, the company says.
   The showdown over the project in the Central American nation came
as the giant oil company faced continued scrutiny and criticism from
government officials and environmentalists in the United States over
the disastrous oil spill in March off the Alaskan coast by the
tanker Exxon Valdez.
   But Exxon said Thursday that its decision to terminate the
project at two sites in central Guatemala _ including the
government-protected El Ceibal national park _ was not prompted by
the U.S. uproar over the Alaskan spill.
   ``While Valdez certainly has focused more attention on Exxon
overall, it did not influence our decision concerning withdrawing
from Guatemala,'' said Exxon spokeswoman Ann Frechette.
   Exxon said it spent $21.4 million during four years of
preliminary testing at the Guatemalan sites.
   The New York-based company received permission to drill from
Guatemala's Ministry of Energy and Mines, but Culture Ministry
archeologists in late May physically blocked Exxon workers from
moving equipment into El Ceibal.
   ``Exxon is a very important company, but Guatemala is more
important,'' Guatemala President Vinicio Cerezo said recently in
announcing Exxon's withdrawal.
   El Ceibal, site of ruins including dirt mounds that archeologists
believe may be Mayan burial sites, was declared a protected area
after Exxon began testing there.
   Frechette said Wednesday that the company received drilling
permission from the Ministry of Energy and Mines in May and
consulted with environmental and archeological officials during the
project's preparation.
   ``What we did was to make a careful study of the vicinity where
we wanted to drill in cooperation with a local archeologist to help
us ensure that where we drilled would not in any way compromise the
integrity of the nearby ruins,'' she said.
   Frechette said that once drilling started, Exxon planned to
monitor the site to keep workers away from Mayan ruins and to
hand-clear dirt from some areas.
   ``In early June when our equipment showed up to enter the park we
were prevented by doing so by members of the Culture Ministry,'' she
said. ``They basically said you cannot enter this park, you cannot
do this work.''
   Vocal opposition also came from the government's National
Commission on the Environment and political figures, according to
reports from Guatemala.
   Several weeks after it was barred from El Ceibal, Exxon decided
to pull out of Guatemala. ``It seemed to be something that was not
going to be resolved,'' Frechette said.
   Exxon formed Esso Exploration Guatemala in 1985 to conduct
exploratory activities. The company conducted preliminary seismic
testing and identified two areas to drill wells. Exxon performed
test drilling at the first site, known as Machaquila, but it proved
unproductive.
   The Guatemala project was one of Exxon's ``frontier exploration
groups'' to identify possible oil and gas deposits around the world.
   Elsewhere in Latin America, Exxon earlier this year closed a
project in Ecuador after conducting exploratory drilling but has an
active exploratory program in northern Argentina. Exxon also is
producing oil and gas and mining coal in Colombia, and mining copper
in Chile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1630EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Venezuela-Debt     08-17 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Debt,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuelan President Insists on 50 Percent Debt Reduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuelan president Carlos Andres
Perez insisted Thursday that Venezuela will seek a 50 percent
reduction of its estimated $20.3 billion debt with commercial banks,
cautioning that a U.S. trade deficit was partly caused by Third
World debt.
   Perez, speaking in his twice monthly press conference, added that
the position was not an ultimatum.
   ``We cannot say this or nothing. But the conclusion is that we
must seek more or less this 50 percent reduction because it is what
we need,'' said Perez.
   Venezuela has insisted in preliminary conversations with its
commercial creditors that it needs to cut its annual debt burden in
half in order to meet its commitments and generate needed economic
growth.
   Banking representatives rejected Venezuela's initial position
late last month, reportedly claiming Venezuela was in better shape
to meet its debt payments than Mexico, the first country to reach an
agreement with banks on debt reductions.
   Mexico's creditors agreed last month to a three-tiered approach
to reducing that country's $54 billion commercial debt: a 35 percent
reduction in debts, a ceiling on interest rates, or fresh loans to
help make back payments.
   Venezuela stopped paying capital on its $33 billion debt, the
fourth largest in the developing world, in January, and stopped
interest payments in February.
   Perez quoted former President Reagan in warning that if Third
World countries did not succeed in alleviating the burden of foreign
debt, trade deficits in the industrialized countries would grow
worse.
   ``I remember when Reagan said that if Latin America had been
buying U.S. products in the '80s at the same rate they were buying
in the '70s, the U.S. would not be suffering its tremendous trade
deficit,'' he said.
   Latin American economists have called the '80s the ``lost
decade'' as the countries of the region have sunk into an economic
tailspin, blamed largely on the debt burden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
