<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferruzzi Seen As Big Seller Of Soybean Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of soybeans for August delivery fell
sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a sell-off sparked
by ideas that the Italian grain giant Ferruzzi was liquidating some
large holdings.
   Other soybean futures prices closed mostly higher while most
grain futures finished slightly lower.
   Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA, one of the world's largest grain
processors, is believed to hold a large number of contracts to take
delivery of soybeans against the August contract, which expires
Tuesday.
   Heavy selling of soybean contracts Thursday by trading companies
with close ties to Ferruzzi prompted a flurry of selling by others
seeking to profit from the drop in prices that a large-scale
sell-off by Ferruzzi could cause.
   Traders had no proof that Ferruzzi was actually a seller but
``that's the perception,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   The Italian firm is believed to have accumulated a large position
in August soybean futures after being forced by the Board of Trade
to abandon a huge position in the July contract last month.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97\ a bushel; corn was 2{
cents lower to { cent higher with September at $2.35{ a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower with September at $1.37 a bushel;
soybeans were 16 cents lower to 6 cents higher with August off 16
cents at $6.07{ a bushel.
