<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0273</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell in moderately active
trading today, pressured by a sharply narrower U.S. trade deficit
that showed unexpected strength in the economy.
   Wall Street analysts said the decline was broad-based and came in
response to a fall in the bond market.
   Both markets initially rallied after the report but a closer
examination aroused bondholders concern that the economy is too
strong and that the Federal Reserve might not ease credit.
   The Commerce Department reported that the June U.S. trade deficit
narrowed to $8.17 billion from a revised $10.08 billion in May.
Exports increased 1.5 percent to a record level of $30.91 billion
while imports fell 3.6 percent to $39.08 billion.
   ``The concern is that the gap shows the economy was stronger than
people thought,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, vice president at A.G.
Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
   Although the data is good for the economy, the market is not
satisfied, said Eugene Peroni, technical analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott.
   ``It's looking for things that would compel the Fed to ease.
Lower interest rates are good because they would tend to fuel the
economy and bring borrowing rates down,'' Peroni said.
   Friday's report on consumer prices could provide further evidence
of the economy's growth. Consensus expectations are for the consumer
price index to edge up 0.2 percent, analysts said.
   But a much higher CPI number could be interpreted as inflationary
and therefore bearish for the market because it would further dim
hopes of the Fed lowering interest rates, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
