<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices slipped lower Thursday on
largely technical factors in the absence of any major news.
   The September contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 29 cents to close at $18.68 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, erasing a
29-cent gain from the previous session. Among refined products
traded on the exchange, unleaded regular gasoline for September
delivery fell 0.58 cent to 52.35 cents a gallon after rising 0.87 on
Wednesday.
   Heating oil futures edged 0.11 cent lower, settling at 51.04
cents a gallon.
   Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said energy futures were retreating slightly in response to a
more than $1 a barrel rise in crude prices during the past two weeks.
   Lebow called the market trendless, with no news on supplies or
production to influence trading.
   ``It's going from one trading range to another,'' he said.
