<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1714EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Bakes Bjt   08-17 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bakes, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Eastern Will Be Bigger Than Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines President Phil Bakes says the
carrier is doing so well at overcoming its strike that the rebuilt
Eastern will be bigger than first announced.
   ``The airline's going to be larger than what we projected last
April,'' Bakes said in an interview Wednesday evening. ``We will
have more employees, it will service more cities, and we'll have
more airplanes.
   ``We're very pleased,'' Bakes said of Eastern's progress since it
announced plans to rebuild at two-thirds its pre-strike size from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization despite the 5-month-old strike
by its unions. ``What we announced last April was the impossible and
there were a lot of skeptics, to say the least.
   ``The fact is, we're exceeding targets (and) we will accelerate
the schedule a little bit,'' Bakes said.
   Among the revised, increased plans, he said, are:
   _Instead of the 17,000 employees planned, there will be
``18,000-plus, maybe more.''
   _Instead of the 1,700 pilots planned, there will be more ``in the
next year or two, maybe in the next few months in small groups.''
   _Instead of 157 aircraft, Eastern next year will fly from 165 to
180 planes and also has the first nine of 40 new Boeing aircraft on
order available for 1992.
   _Instead of 800 daily flights serving 77 cities, Eastern will
probably add cities and flights, but no figures have been decided
upon.
   _Instead of $1.8 billion in asset sales, the figure may be as low
as $1.5 billion. Fewer assets may be sold because transactions such
as aircraft sales, Philadelphia gates and the Northeast shuttle sale
have earned more money than expected and Eastern is winning back
customers at faster rates than expected, Bakes said.
   Negotiations, reportedly with rival American Airlines, have
continued on the possible sale of another major Eastern asset _ its
South American routes _ but Bakes declined to give details. He said
he wouldn't place odds on whether the routes will be sold.
   A spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, which was
meeting in executive session in Washington, said time would tell
whether Bakes' projections hold true.
   ``The company's promised a lot of things since the beginning of
the strike and bankruptcy. Some of them they've delivered and some
they haven't,'' spokesman John Mazor said.
   Mazor said Eastern still has a training bottleneck for newly
hired pilots and also is having trouble hiring mechanics to replace
strikers.
   With the ALPA leadership discussing possibly ending the pilots'
strike, veteran pilots by the dozens crossed picket lines last week.
Eastern last Friday said it had stopped hiring pilots or accepting
strikers back.
   Bakes said Eastern has 750 to 800 union pilots who are crossing
picket lines. He said it has graduated 300 new pilots and has 700 in
training.
   ALPA contends that any union pilot must get job preference over a
pilot still in training, but Bakes said Eastern is committed to
protecting the pilots in training.
   ``They became employees of the company the day they started
training,'' he said. ``The people who came back last week ought to
get down on their hands and knees and thank the people who are in
training, who left jobs at other carriers, left their jobs at
corporations, retired from the military, moved their families, took
their chances.
   ``We are going to protect those people. That's why we shut the
door. They are going to be out flying,'' Bakes said. ``The fact is,
most of the people still out there (striking) have lost their
careers at Eastern Airlines. That's sad and that didn't have to be.
But we don't look back. We have to move forward.''
   He said Eastern has hired about 800 new mechanics since the
strike started March 4, had 150 Machinists union members cross
picket lines, and has 1,000 non-union supervisors assigned to
maintenance duties. Eastern plans to have 2,400 to 2,500 mechanics,
but will contract out routine maintenance as needed, Bakes said.
   Eastern is temporarily leasing 15 planes and crews from sister
carrier Continental Airlines to meet its planned increase in
schedule Sept. 7, when Eastern says it will jump from 390 daily
flights to 600. Bakes rejected suggestions that the deal is another
example of how predominantly non-union Continental is being used to
break Eastern's strike and how Eastern cash is ``upstreamed'' to
Texas Air Corp., parent of Eastern and Continental.
   Bakes said such ``wet-lease'' deals are traditional in the
airline industry and that Eastern will profit on the routes flown
for it by Continental.
</TEXT>
