<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-17 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Worldwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply worldwide on Thursday,
bolstered by a better-than-expected U.S. trade report, but its gains
were capped by profit-taking and uncertainty over whether the upward
momentum can continue.
   The rise brought the dollar back to almost to the highs reached
in June, the period of its most recent rally.
   Gold prices were mixed. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery gained 10 cents to close at
$368.30 troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York said gold was
bid later at $366.20 an ounce, down from $366.50 on Wednesday.
   The U.S. currency began gaining ground following a Commerce
Department report that showed the June trade deficit narrowed to
$8.17 billion _ the smallest since December 1984 and down
dramatically from a revised gap of $10.08 billion in May.
   A low deficit is seen as positive for the dollar because it makes
traders believe the currency probably won't have to decline any
further to help improve the U.S. trade picture.
   ``The market believes that we're heading for a soft landing and
not a recession for the time being,'' said Scott Horwitz, a vice
president at the Bank of Boston.
   ``With that in mind, the market is tempted to think the (Federal
Reserve) may not ease as rapidly as we thought,'' he added,
referring to interest rates. Lower interest rates make U.S.
securities more expensive and, therefore, less attractive to foreign
investors.
   Profit-taking both at home and abroad as well as rumors of
intervention took the dollar down from its peak levels in hectic
trading.
   ``The variables here are the central banks,'' said Ian Spence,
chief dealer at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. ``There's a lot of
uncertainty over whether the dollar will go much higher.''
   Traders also were looking to Friday's release of the consumer
price index for July for further evidence that economic growth is
continuing and that monetary policy need not be altered.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar firmed to 142.32 Japanese yen from
142.20 late Wednesday. Later in London, the dollar traded sharply
higher at 143.95 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 143.53 yen,
up from 142.19 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5590 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's $1.5735. In New York, one pound cost
$1.5605, less expensive than $1.5805 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates included: 1.9637 West German marks, up from 1.9420;
1.6925 Swiss francs, up from 1.6716; 6.6280 French francs, up from
6.5615; 1,412.25 Italian lire, up from 1,395.00, and 1.1819 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1778.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's late
rates included: 1.9690 West German marks, up from 1.9500; 1.6980
Swiss francs, up from 1.6790; 6.6325 French francs, up from 6.5835;
2.2190 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1905; 1,412.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,397.50, and 1.1815 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1822.
   Gold bullion prices varied. Gold closed at $366.35 a troy ounce
in London, up from $365.75 on Wednesday. But in Zurich, gold slipped
to $365.25 an ounce, from $366.25. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed
at $366.45 a troy ounce, down from $368.25.
   Silver prices also were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $5.246 a troy ounce from $5.186
late Wednesday. Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.20 a troy
ounce, down from $5.24.
</TEXT>
