<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hit Another All-Time High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 462 money market mutual
funds rose by $2.29 billion in the latest week to a new all-time
high of $340.51 billion, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   It was the seventh straight week of new records in the fund
assets, despite a decline in interest rates that has made such
investments less attractive.
   The rise broke the record set a week earlier of $338.21 billion,
revised downward slightly from the $338.35 billion figure originally
reported.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 227 general purpose funds rose $1.74 billion to $108.76
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds rose $1.61 billion to
$146.26 billion, and assets of 140 institutional funds declined
$1.05 billion to $85.48 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds in the
week ended Tuesday was 8.33 percent, unchanged from the previous
week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal based in
Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.45 percent from 8.53 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 40
days, down from 41 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.46 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.47 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.11 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.25
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.27 percent
the previous week. Yields were 8.25 percent on 1-year CDs,
unchanged; 8.17 percent on 2{-year CDs, unchanged; and 8.17 percent
on 5-year CDs, up from 8.16 percent.
</TEXT>
