<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Declines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about interest rates shook the stock
market Thursday and sent prices down in the busiest day this week.
   The drop came in response to a sharp decline in the bond market
after release of the June U.S. trade deficit report. The numbers
showed a surprising narrowing of the deficit that suggested
underlying strength in the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 13.66 points to
finish at 2,679.63, after trading down about 25 points during the
session. Last Thursday, the Dow Jones average closed at 2,712.63,
near the all-time high of 2,722.42 reached in August 1987.
   The Dow Jones transportation average gained 26.67 to set another
record at 1,428.34, due largely to takeover speculation in airline
stocks.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by a margin of about 8 to 5
in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
887 issues down, 561 up and 540 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 157.56 million
shares, up from 150.06 million in Wednesday's session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 185.56 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported that the June U.S. trade deficit
narrowed to $8.17 billion from a revised $10.08 billion in May. The
improvement was due mainly to a 1.5 percent increase in exports to a
record level of $30.91 billion while imports fell 3.6 percent to
$39.08 billion.
   The stock and bond markets initially rallied after the report,
which eased recession worries. But closer inspection aroused
bondholders concern that the economy is too strong and that the
Federal Reserve might not ease credit conditions.
   What should have been interpreted as good news for the overall
economy was bad news for the market, said Larry Wachtel, analyst
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``The market is concerned that if the economy is too bubbly the
Fed will not accommodate and lower interest rates,'' Wachtel said.
   Some Wall Street analysts said, however, that the market was
overreacting.
   ``It's a knee-jerk reaction to sell stocks when bonds go down,''
said Philip Roth, equities analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
``But that's misplaced because economic strength is good if not
accompanied by inflation or too strong an economy.''
   Roth said while the fear is that the Fed will not lower interest
rates, ``company earnings are not going to be killed by the Fed not
easing.''
   Despite the busier pace, the market was ``unusually
featureless,'' with the exception of airline stocks, traders said.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market declined $11.781 billion, or 0.35
percent, in value from Wednesday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.69 to 191.95.
   Among most actively traded issues on the NYSE, UAL Corp., parent
of United Airlines, rose 14| to 266] on news that billionaire suitor
Marvin Davis raised his bid to $275 a share, or $6.19 billion.
   Delta Air Lines rose 1 to 75\, Continental Bank gained \ to 25
and AT&amp;T rose \ to 39].
   Hewlett Packard, meanwhile, fell 1{ to 51, Navistar lost \ to 4~
and Bristol Meyers dropped [ to 47}.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 1.46 to 394.27, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index declined 1.21 to 344.45.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
0.04 to 460.83. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 378.34, down 1.26.
</TEXT>
