<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Rally Strengthens; Supply Worries Mount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rocketed higher Thursday on New York's
Commodity Exchange, extending to seven days a rally fueled by miner
strikes, tightening supplies, bullish chart signals and signs of
renewed economic strength.
   On other markets, soybeans for August delivery tumbled; energy
futures were lower; most livestock and meat futures advanced ahead
of a government cattle report; and precious metals were narrowly
mixed.
   Copper settled 2.9 cents to 4.5 cents higher on heavy volume with
the contract for delivery in August at $1.2675, the highest
settlement of a spot contract since May 5. The more active September
contract settled at $1.2625, which represents a 15 percent gain
since Aug. 8.
   Copper prices reached a record high of $1.6475 a pound last Dec.
8.
   Prices initially rose Thursday following the Commodity Exchange's
report that stocks of copper stored for delivery against futures
contracts had dropped by 1,140 tons Wednesday to 16,708 tons.
   Traders follow the daily Comex stocks reports as an indicator of
overall supplies. Wednesday's sharp drawdown reinforced fears that
miner strikes in Peru and Canada, as well as production problems in
other copper-rich nations, are cutting into supplies as the seasonal
peak demand period _ which begins in the fall and ends in the earlyl
spring _ approaches.
   Analysts said the September contract pierced considerable
technical resistance at $1.23 a pound, bringing in further buying
that brought it to within about 5 cents of its lifetime high of
$1.3150, reached on March 8.
   Analyst James Steel of Refco Inc. said the rally was almost
entirely technically inspired, but he also cited the Commerce
Department's report of a strong improvement in the trade deficit.
The report signals economic strength, a key component of copper
demand.
   Soybeans for August delivery fell 15{ cents a bushel on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a sell-off sparked by ideas that the
Italian grain giant Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA was liquidating some
large holdings. The contract settled at $6.08 a bushel.
   Heavy selling of soybean contracts Thursday by trading companies
with close ties to Ferruzzi prompted a flurry of selling by others
seeking to profit from the drop in prices that a large-scale
sell-off by Ferruzzi could cause.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with September at $3.97\
a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to } cent higher with September at
$2.35} a bushel; oats were { cent to 1{ cents lower with September
at $1.37 a bushel; soybeans were 15{ cents lower to 6 cents higher
with the September contract at $5.84 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in cautious trading ahead of a monthly
Agriculture Department report showing 4 percent fewer cattle on
feedlots Aug. 1 than on the same date a year ago. That number was
near market expectations, but the report also showed more cattle
placed on feedlots in July than expected, which could trigger a drop
in prices on Friday.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .60 cent higher with August
at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .27 cent
higher with August at 84.65 cents a pound; hogs were .35 cent lower
to .70 cent higher with August at 47.85 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent lower to .80 cent higher with August at 26.77
cents a pound.
   Most energy futures prices slipped lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange on largely technical factors in the absence of
any major news.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 29 cents lower to 14
cents higher with September at $18.68 a barrel; heating oil was .11
cent to .36 cent lower with September at 51.04 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .28 cent to .58 cent lower with September at
52.35 cents a gallon.
   Gold settled 10 cents lower to 10 cents higher on the Commodity
Exchange with August at $368.30 a troy ounce; silver was 5.8 cents
to 6.3 cents higher with September at $5.265 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
