<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Cocoa     08-17 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Cocoa,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Price Support Relaunch Plan in Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN STAINER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New proposals from cocoa producers to relaunch the
price-support system in world markets are unlikely to be accepted by
consumers, officials of the cocoa-buying nations said Thursday.
   The producers were expected to confer in Africa later this month
on the proposals, their officials said.
   Earlier this year, the price of cocoa dropped to a 13-year low.
The price was a modest $1,311 a ton in London this week.
   Cocoa is the source of 30 percent of the foreign exchange
earnings of Ivory Coast _ the biggest cocoa producer _ and is an
even more important earner for Ghana.
   The proposals are from a private consultant who has not been
publicly identified and who is believed to be backed by Ivory Coast.
The proposals were called ``wrong on crucial points'' and
``outrageously unrealistic'' by some industry experts.
   Earlier this month, Ivory Coast confirmed it was working on an
initiative to revive the cocoa agreement's market-support regime,
which is administered from London by the 41-nation International
Cocoa Organization.
   Since then, the private consultant, acting on behalf of a U.S.
company that recently bought 500,000 metric tons of new-crop Ivorian
cocoa, has drafted a discussion document for the Cocoa Producers'
Alliance on how the pact could be resurrected.
   The alliance groups all key producers and was expected to meet in
Africa at the end of August.
   The cocoa pact's regulatory provisions have been frozen for 18
months because of a dispute between its producer and consumer
members over the minimum price a proposed new stockpiling scheme
should defend and a lack of cash to finance it.
   The cash shortage is the result of arrears in producer payments
to the cocoa organization of almost $115 million. Ivory Coast is the
largest debtor, owing $70 million.
   According to the consultant's document, producers would be asked
to pay at least part of their debts.
   Consumer officials say the implementation of most proposals would
mean amending the cocoa treaty, a process requiring lengthy legal
procedures involving the United Nations.
   It is not yet certain whether the document will form the basis
for a joint producer proposal to consumers on reviving the cocoa
pact at the next cocoa organization meeting in London in September.
   Members are to make a decision then on what should happen when
the pact expires at the end of September next year.
   Traders said if the pact's control function is revived next month
this would boost the chances of a decision to extend the accord with
its regulatory power intact for one or two more years.
   If there is no extension, the 250,000-ton stockpile already held
by the cocoa organization will have to be liquidated under current
rules within 4{ years from September 1990.
   Traders said the sale of so much cocoa would pull down prices,
already depressed by five straight seasons of overproduction and the
prospect of another in 1989-90.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890817-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1910EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     08-17 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three leading measures of the nation's money
supply rose in the week ended Aug. 7, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3,132.4 billion from $3,127.5 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose to a seasonally adjusted
$4,011.3 billion from $4,005.2 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose to a
seasonally adjusted $778.7 billion from $775.7 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The annual growth rate in M2 so far this year is 2.7 percent,
which is below the Fed's target range of 3 percent to 7 percent. The
annual growth rate in M3 is 4.1 percent, which is within the Fed's
target range of 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent. The Fed has not set a
target for M1 growth since early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,096.9 billion, a 2.7
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,979.5 billion, up 3.3 percent, while M1 fell
5.2 percent to an average of $774.1 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $520 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from
$654 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $292.1 billion in the two-week period ended Aug. 9, up from
$289.5 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
