<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Computers     08-17 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computers,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard, Flat; Sun Micro's Big Loss; Intel's Bad News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production and inventory problems produced a
loss at Sun Microsystems Inc., the computer workstation maker, while
creating flat earnings for industry giant Hewlett-Packard Co., the
companies reported Thursday.
   Analysts said the reports, along with a prediction by
semiconductor manufacturer Intel Corp. that its third-quarter
profits could fall, reflected a generally flat computer market and
as well as shifting marketing strategies by the companies and
problems associated with those changes.
   Sun Microsystems Inc. of Mountain View, one of the leading makers
of technical workstations, said it lost $20.3 million in its fiscal
fourth quarter ended June 30, in contrast to a profit of $25.3
million, or 33 cents a share, in the final quarter a year earlier.
Revenue increased 18 percent to $431.2 million from $365.1 million.
   For the fiscal year, Sun's earnings fell 8 percent to $60.8
million, or 76 cents a share, from $66.4 million, or 89 cents a
share, for 1987. Revenue for the year was up 68 percent to $1.77
billion from $1.05 billion.
   ``The problems the company has are growing pains; the demand
didn't match what they planned in their marketing department,'' said
Lisa Morgenthaler, an analyst with the California Technology Stock
Letter in San Francisco. Sun was founded in 1982.
   Steve Ossad, an analyst with Montgomery Securities in San
Francisco, warned the company could continue losing money.
   ``I don't sense that it's turned around,'' Ossad said. ``I
couldn't rule out continued negative surprises.''
   Company President Scott McNealy, who has headed what had been one
of the fastest-growing companies in the country, in June warned
investors of the impending loss and last month hinted that a return
to profitability wasn't certain in the current quarter. On Thursday,
the company reiterated that profits ``cannot be assured'' for the
first quarter.
   McNealy and analysts attributed the fourth-quarter loss, the
company's first since going public in 1986, to a transition to a
line of new products, saying the company was unable to meet demand
for the new products introduced in April.
   Meanwhile, Hewlett-Packard Co. of Palo Alto reported a 3 percent
drop in third-quarter earnings for the period ending July 31 on a 23
percent increse in revenue. from $2.43 billion in the third qurater
of last year to $3 billion for the period just ended.
   Earnings were $187 million, or 79 cents a share, down from $192
million, or 80 cents a share, for the third quarter of 1988. Revenue
increased from 2.43 billion in the third qurater of 1987 to $3
billion for the period just ended.
   The report reflected Hewlett-Packard's $476 million acquisition
in May of Apollo Computer Co., an industry leader in the technical
workstation market, and two months of Apollo's operating results.
   John A. Young, company president and chief executive officer,
said the purchase cut earnings 13 cents a share and that otherwise
profits would have been 92 cents a share, 15 percent higher than the
same period last year.
   For the latest quarter, HP said it experienced faltering demand
for high-end minicomputers and electronic components. But HP
apparently had unexpected demand for so-called ``low-end'' products,
such as workstations, personal computers and PC peripherals.
   ``Their earnings shortfall is not dramatic in any shape or
form,'' said analyst Bob Herwick of Hambrecht &amp; Quist in San
Francisco.
   Hewlett-Packard said it had halted hiring except for select sales
and support positions and imposed expense controls.
   Intel, the Santa Clara, Calif., chip maker, said in a statement
Wednesday that its third-quarter performance would be hurt by
slower-than-expected sales of its 80386 microprocessor, the heart of
many top-of-the-line personal computers.
</TEXT>
