<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-WangReorganization     08-17 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wang Reorganization,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Wang Official Resigns in Shakeup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. on Thursday announced
the resignation of a top official as part of a major shakeup in the
troubled computer firm's worldwide sales and marketing operations.
   Wang Chairman and Chief Executive An Wang said Ian W. Diery would
step down as executive vice president for worldwide operations in a
reorganization that would direct more responsibility to geographic
sales management teams.
   The restructuring follows last week's ouster of Frederick Wang,
son of founder An Wang, as president and chief operating officer and
a financial crisis that led the firm to halt payment on more than
$200 million in debt.
   An Wang said in a statement the move affects sales groups for the
company U.S. operation, European, African and Middle Eastern
operation, and American and Asian-Pacific operation.
   An Wang said the senior vice presidents in charge of each
operation will report directly to acting president Harry H.S. Chou.
   The company recently announced a $424 million quarterly loss and
this week halted payments on $208.6 million in institutional debt
while continuing negotiations with lenders.
   Founded in 1951, Wang grew from a small calculator maker in the
1960s into a billion-dollar manufacturer of word processing systems
for businesses in the 1970s.
   But the company failed to take advantage of the personal coputer
revolution this decade, sticking instead with high-priced systems
that weren't compatible with International Business Machines Corp.
equipment.
</TEXT>
