<DOCNO> AP890817-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 2214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Disney-Lorimar     08-17 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney-Lorimar,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorimar Sues Disney for $126 Million in Film Lab Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorimar Telepictures Inc. filed a $126 million
lawsuit Thursday against the Walt Disney Co., claiming that Disney
has refused to pay processing costs at a jointly owned film
processing lab.
   Disney immediately filed a $42 million countersuit, alleging it
had been fraudulently induced into entering into the Metrocolor
partnership. Disney claims it was prevented from selling its share
of the lab.
   The Burbank-based entertainment giant also alleges that Lorimar
has refused to return to Disney footage from its films ``Beaches''
and ``Turner and Hooch'' and footage from movies made for Disney's
theme parks.
   Both lawsuits were filed in Los Angeles Superior Court.
   Lorimar maintains that Disney and its subsidiaries are refusing
to pay more than $8 million in film processing costs incurred at the
Los Angeles Metrocolor facility, founded in 1987.
   Lorimar's lawsuit alleges that early this year ``Disney began to
express displeasure that the Metrocolor lab was not as profitable as
Disney had anticipated, and Disney began to press plaintiffs for
concessions.''
   The concessions, the lawsuit states, imposed a ``heavy and
unjustified burden'' on Lorimar. Disney announced in June that it
would no longer honor the partnership, according to Lorimar's
lawsuit.
   Lorimar's court action seeks the $8.2 million Disney allegedly
owes for work done at Metrocolor and an affiliated lab, at least $18
million in damages for breaches and misconduct, and more than $100
million in punitive damages.
   The Disney suit alleges that it entered into the partnership in
the belief that it could sell its stake, but was unaware that
certain restrictions prevented any sale until 1992.
   Disney says that a buyer, the Rank Organization, offered no less
than $65 million for controlling interest in the lab last year.
Disney also says that income from processing was not as high as the
company had been led to believe it would be.
   In addition to asking for return of the film stock, the Disney
suit seeks at least $30 million in damages.
</TEXT>
