<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 2ndLd-Writethru f0322 08-17 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0322,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Board Says Too Early To Decide on Davis Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 7th graf pvs `On Wednesday... with Davis
statement; Picks up 8th graf pvs, `UAL _ parent...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. directors reviewed California
billionaire Marvin Davis's latest buyout offer Thursday but said it
was premature to make any decision on whether to sell the company.
   The 16-member board of United Airlines' parent company also
confirmed speculation they had been contacted by other potential
buyers and that their financial advisers had met with an employee
group.
   A company statement did not specify what employee group, and UAL
spokeswoman Sara Dornacker refused to say if it was the pilots,
whose union has expressed interest in buying UAL.
   Ms. Dornacker also would not say what other potential buyers
other than Davis have surfaced.
   ``The board concluded that it was still premature to make a
decision as to whether a sale of the company to any party was
appropriate,'' the board said in a statement after Thursday's
meeting.
   The statement added that ``all possible financial and strategic
alternatives should continue to be pursued.''
   On Wednesday, Davis turned up the heat on the board by offering
to ante up another $800 million, raising his bid to $6.19 billion,
or $275 a share. That total represented a 15 percent increase over
Davis' original offer two weeks ago. Davis also said his offer could
go higher after a review of the company's internal data.
   After the meeting, Davis said in a statement that he and his
associates are awaiting ``with interest the board's conclusions and
continue to look forward to working with UAL's board, management and
labor groups to develop a transaction that works to the benefit of
all parties concerned.''
   UAL _ parent company of United Airlines, the nation's
second-largest carrier _ has 22.5 million shares outstanding.
   UAL stock, which had climbed a dizzying $90 per share in less
than two weeks in anticipation of a bidding war for the company,
jumped $14.62{ a share to $266.37{ in consolidated New York Stock
Exchange trading.
   Davis' announcement Wednesday sought to portray his offer as
friendly, apparently hoping to avoid alienating United pilots and
other employee groups whose cooperation could prove crucial to any
takeover attempt.
   But Davis did say if the bid was successful, he intended to
replace the 16 directors with five _ including himself; his two
sons, John A. Davis and Gregg J. Davis; and James Kneser, a top
Davis aide.
   He said he would retain UAL Chairman Stephen Wolf, credited with
helping turn the company around.
   Davis also filed a consent solicitation with United, ensuring the
company would not issue new stock to an employee-ownership plan or
another proxy that could be used to thwart a takeover.
   Davis apparently was not the only one trying to anticipate
United's next move.
   Speculation in recent days suggested that Wolf, in conjunction
with other UAL executives, may plan a bid for the company himself _
or recapitalization with employee ownership. There also has been
talk that buyout firms Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts &amp; Co., and
Forstmann Little &amp; Co. have contacted UAL about a possible deal.
   The airline's pilots' and machinists' unions also have been
mentioned as key players in any scenario for restructuring the
company. The United unit of the Air Line Pilots Association, with
7,125 members, made a bid for the company as recently as 1987.
   ``All we're aware of is that there's a board meeting. We won't
speculate what's going on, but I will say our leadership is in
constant touch with our financial and legal advisers,'' said Hank
Krakowski, a spokesman for the pilots.
   He said membership had not taken a position on a possible
acquisition of the company by Davis ``or any outsiders in general.''
   While declining to confirm reports about a scheduled meeting
between the pilots, the machinists and Davis, Krakowski noted the
letter sent by union officials to member pilots earlier this week,
which said ``concessions in exchange for equity was an option they
may have to face.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
